text: Simple consistent food. Sets are mostly $4.70 and come with 2 soft boiled eggs and a drink. Mains include kaya toast (4 square pieces), French toast, soft bun or egg baguette.<br><br>I&#39;ve tried them all and they are worth the price. The kaya here is thick and I do ask for a little extra for my French toast sometimes.<br><br>You get a bigger cup of tea when it&#39;s takeaway but often less thick.<br><br>The eggs are always nicely done but.. They often take very long to be served!<br><br>Staff are pleasant.

text: This little coffee and breakfast place has been here for more than 5 years. Run by a group of aunties who are always cheerful and efficient. The coffee is your traditional kopi tiam coffee, strong enough to stand a spoon in. The spanking new  ya  ku which opened up a couple of doors down can&#39;t match this kopi-o for strength and flavour or price.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/qGk-kDvzvmIWMt51Szb-yg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ya-kun-family-cafe-singapore?reviewid=evI7nd4XD3D82o7mBke0rw&select=qGk-kDvzvmIWMt51Szb-yg', 'altText': 'Photo of Ya Kun Family Cafe - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: I&#39;ve got to have my soft-boiled eggs at least once a week. Sometimes I boil it myself at home, but I can never mimic successfully the way Ya Kun does their eggs. Apparently, neither can many kopitiams or similar kopi-and-toast chains.<br><br>Try watching how the staff do it. Or time them if you can. Is it the way the boiling water keeps running or the huge container of boiling water with the exact volume or the rotation of boiling water and cold water mixed? No idea. <br><br>Their eggs are perfection. Bouncy, glistening, firm but with runny insides. This outlet at Toa Payoh has got a mini &#39;al fresco&#39; section, you can choose to sit outside if the weather&#39;s fine and you find it too cramped inside. I&#39;ve ordered Milo in the mornings a few times, they make it SINFULLY thick and sweet, which is a perfect accompaniment to the eggs.

text: I have passed this place several times in the evening and it was always crowded.  I was able to stop by for lunch and several pints today. <br><br>1. Great people watching spot if that is your thing.  It&#39;s not mine. <br><br>2. I ordered the chili crab spaghetti; it&#39;s got a small kick to it. I enjoyed it for what it&#39;s worth and would order it again.  If your sensitive to heat maybe you can order it without  but what&#39;s the point?  <br><br>3. Service was very friendly with all the staff I encountered. BUT. yup, there is one.  No one checked on me until I had to ask for a refill. My empty bowl became a second entity for the table. Even after my first refill, I had to call someone over for another.   Oh and for my drinks, there are no free refills.  <br><br>Would I come back? Sure. Only if I have time to lose.  Service speed is really slow. The open bar patio area is great for a crosswind; which one can really appreciate in Singapore.

text: Stayed at V Hotel across the street and decided to stop by for breakfast. It was the only restaurant nearby that had a line out the door so I decided to give it a try. <br><br>You queue up and order your food first. They&#39;ll make you your drinks right a way and give you a buzzer to let you know when you&#39;re good is ready. My group of 3 ordered 3 of the specials and we enjoyed them all. All the food seemed high quality. The laksa was really good with a tasty broth. <br><br>It gets pretty busy around 7-8am, but the line dies around 9am. Seating wasn&#39;t too bad, not much of a wait. Toast box is a must try when you&#39;re in Singapore.

text: When traveling in Asia, breakfast is the Bomb as you get to eat stuff that Westerners would classify as lunch or dinner food along with your typical Western breakfast.  Breakfast is generally included in most hotel rates or you can look for packages that include breakfast.<br><br>Why a hotel breakfast?  You start your work or travel day with energy, you generally know the quality will be high and consistent on a daily basis, you don&#39;t have to travel far - generally downstairs, you don&#39;t have time to go searching for a cafe or diner.....yep, all of my excuses to stay lazy and in the hotel for breakfast.<br><br>Multiple dining sections in this Cafe, some tables with booths, some indoor and some outdoor.  Service is consistent and attentive.  Take Away (Singapore for &#34;to go&#34;) available on a hot tea, cappuccino, or latte which is included with your buffet breakfast if you need that extra kick.<br><br>Typical choices: <br><br>Western Station - Cook to Order Omelettes or Eggs, Pancakes /Waffles/French Toast, Bacon, Ham, Cold Deli Meats, Yogurts, Baked Goods, Salad, Fresh Fruit, Juices<br><br>Asian Section - Noodle Bowls, Porridge or Congee Bar, Rice with a Meat &amp; Gravy or Sauce, Naan, ..  I love the Asian choices as I get to have lunch for breakfast!  All kinds of pickeled , dried, fresh, stuff that you can add to your congee or noodles!<br><br>Oh yeah, they have a dinner buffet nightly that has Lobster, large Crayfish, Crab Legs, Raw Ousters, Shrimp, with a large variety of other choices.  I find that Chili Crab is messy but I&#39;ll use the sauce for my other seafood!<br><br>Overall, high, consistent standards although pricey.  In Singapore you also need to visit the Hawker Centers, Food Courts, and the Quays to experience lunch and dinner!

Excellent dinner seafood buffet on Thursdays. Great tasting good quality selections of all sorts. <br><br>Excellent breakfast buffet each day until 11 am including some lunch items (Chinese and indian). Omelets station, three dim sum daily, soups, desserts,  <br><br>Service is extraordinary,  really helpful, and friendly. <br><br>Best hotel food in a very long time. Truly 5star

To celebrate the Singapore Marriott Tang Plaza Hotel&#39;s 20th Anniversary celebrations this year, Marriott Cafe has this $20++ high tea buffet promotion from from 4 May to 31 July. This promotion is limited to the first 20 reservations per day, so make sure you make your booking ASAP and at least 2-day reservation required. I am lucky to get a reservation for 5 persons during its weekend high tea buffet which usually costs $42++ per person. It is even cheaper than the usual credit card 1-for-1 promotions.<br><br>Although reservation has been made long before, we are met with a long of people waiting before the buffet start. The local high tea buffet comes with an amazing line-up of more than 50 treats.<br><br>There is wide variety of cooked food such as Satay, Nasi Lemak, Chicken Rice. There is also a variety of malay kueh. For dessert lovers, there is sliced cakes and pastries. Using your creative ideas to make your favourite Ice Kacang. The dessert of the day turns out to be Tau Suan (split green bean soup). There is also ice cream station with 5 different flavours available. One of the favourite station is the DIY salad station which has a variety of items and even items such as chai seeds. Great for those who are eating clean. There is live stations for laksa and crepe. You get to choose the items such as vegetables and noodles for the laksa and the chef will cook for you.  For the crepe station, one can get to choose the filling such as banana, chocolate and kaya. There is topping such as caramel chocolate bits, desiccated coconut, marshmallow and clotted cream. For those who prefer traditional English style of high tea, there is scones, served with clotted cream and jam. The scone is not bad except that it is a bit dry. <br><br>There is a wide variety for the high tea buffet which comes with free flow of coffee and tea. But the time duration for the buffet is a bit limited as it is just for 2 hours from 3pm to 5pm. Overall food is not bad with wide variety such as cold seafood, smoked salmon, bak kut teh soup, rojak, salad, crepe, nacho, bread pudding and local kuehs.

text: simple flair- nothing extraordinary stands out.<br>has the basics- crustless,finger sandwiches (salmon, cucumber, n im guessing tuna), bland scone (orange zest would b nice). i did single diner n had my friend drink the beverage as she didnt want to eat but kept me company. the tip for that is, food isnt topped up (was ok, bc there isnt i would eat a 2nd portion of)<br>sad to note- a strawberry jam jar was already opened n placed bk onto the dispener.<br>would i do it again? no.

For those who have been to Taiwan: If you loved the famous Ice Monster Mango dish and was disappointed by the local franchise... you should be looking out for this spot as it gives an almost as almost kick for their mango drink!<br><br>I had a cup of their Mango Smoothie. The smoothie is rich and flavourful, almost like what I&#39;ll imagine blending the Ice Monster Mango ice into a drink! It has the great balance of mango (lots of it), milk and ice. So if you&#39;re in the area, make it a point to grab a drink from here. I reckon their options should be just as fantastic. Really refreshing drink in our hot weather!

text: As I was trying to find this cafe coming from Ann Shang Hill Park and walking down the stairs, making a left and then, being spit out into the busy street , expecting to find a normal looking cafe ... <br><br>Well. I was wrong. <br><br>Located on the second level inside a REALLY Cool bar, Dapper Coffee put me in a daze: a dimly lit space with a beautiful bronze bar and few seatings by the window. <br><br>At first, I was like &#34;hmm, is it wrong to drink at noon? I barely had lunch. To appease my inner Debbie Downer , I ordered a banana walnut muffin to cover the fruit and healthy fats group... Yay lunch! <br><br>Since we&#39;re at a bar, I had to get an &#34;Espresso + Tonic&#34; -- an easy drink on a hot day. (When does Singapore ever had a cold day?!) and you know what? That&#39;s exactly what it is. The caffeine buzz after was exceptional, especially since I usually don&#39;t get espressos. <br><br>I hung around for awhile so I was able to try their Campari Spritz as well. Served in an extra large wine goblet, this bevvy was bitter and refreshing to my taste. I highly miss good, low ABV cocktails and given the high prices of cocktails in Singapore, I wouldn&#39;t necessarily spend $$ on low ABV drinks! :p  so this was an exception. <br><br>My first time here blew me away that whenever I get recommendations for a chill mid-afternoon hangout, Dapper Coffee is the first thing that comes to mind.

text: The outlet was located at the second level of the shophouse, with a small wooden signage at the ground floor next to the stairs. At the second level, walked into the place, one was met with shelves full of different bottles of liquors. The place was dim and lay back in decoration.<br><br>Menu was a simple used looking booklet.<br><br>Flat White<br>The coffee was rich and thick.<br><br>Unicorn Tears ($10)<br>Served in a bottle with a chilled glass. Best served chilled. A bluish drink, which tasted light and refreshing. <br><br>Fully Loaded Baked Avocado ($8)<br>avocado, cheddar, caramlised bacon, sour cream, spring onions<br>It was like a healthier version of baked potato. So rich and creamy. Buttery in taste too.<br><br>Gula-Melaka Walnut Oat Cake ($9/ slice)<br>Local flavours are the best flavours! oat-based sponge (so it&#39;s basically health food right?), coated with coconut cream and drizzled with gula melaka toffee. Finished with toasted walnuts and coconut chips!<br>The cake was quite soft and unable to hold its weight. The gula melaka was not strong enough. It was more like a coconut cake as the desiccated coconut was distinct in the texture and taste.<br><br>Salted Egg Black Sesame Cake ($9/ slice)<br>Super light black sesame chiffon and black sesame frosting, topped with salted egg yolk custard drizzle, and salted egg crumble.<br>Although the cake was soft, I felt that it was a bit too dry.<br><br>Overall the cooked food and drinks were great, but the cakes were a bit too expensive and too dry.

Dapper Coffee is a bit of hidden away on the second floor at at 73 Amoy Street. It is actually the same location as the Spiffy Dapper but that it the night time venue that serves cocktails. During the days the serve cafe style food and pretty decent coffee. The interior is also more pub or bar like but not that it really bothers me.<br><br>I tried both a regular cappuccino and the cold brew here. The cappuccino was pretty decent but nothing special. The cold brew, served from a bottle, was however very good. The draw back here is that it is hike up some pretty steep stairs and that the prices are on the high side. Otherwise a fine place for a cup of coffee and relaxation. I do however already have so many other places for coffee and while this was good I do not see myself coming back that often due to the abundance of good alternatives and this is just not enough to lure my away from any of my other favorite spots.

text: The moment you walk into this hole-in-the-wall restaurant, you will not know you&#39;re in CBD area, the most busiest district in Singapore. If you want to chill out or not want to queue at the long ass Amoy queues, it&#39;s the perfect spot. Keep in mind that they only have one Chef so it will take some time for your order but the food is pretty alright. I have had my share of bland chicken breasts but this place knocks it out of the park with their Chicken and Greens ($10). Regardless, the place is worth a visit for sure.

text: I got here right as they opened and they weren&#39;t quite ready for customers.  The staff was friendly, as far as attentive they seemed to be very preoccupied with opening the cafe and doing what they needed to do.  I was the only customer in the place and had to flag them down a few times.<br><br>Food was fine, nothing spectacular.  I&#39;m glad others mentioned it was hard to find otherwise I would never have found it.  I bought both kind of Unicorn tears.  They told me they were different flavors.  They are not.

text: Dapper coffee is located on the second floor of a shophouse. It&#39;s a bit of a climb up, but once you enter, you feel like you&#39;ve stepped into a secret world where people talk about all things indie and where you&#39;ll find out who&#39;s the next hottest underground artist. I ordered their latte, along with a Salted Egg Earl Grey chiffon cake. Their coffee was pretty nice, and I decided not to get their famous &#39;unicorn tears&#39; or &#39;Merlion&#39;s blood&#39;, both of which APPARENTLY are basically nicely presented lemonade and ribena respectively, but I&#39;ll have a taste myself next time I drop by. In any case, it&#39;s not a very big space, with a bit of a narrow walkway between the bar and the rest of the seating (sat at the bar). I really liked my cake though, because even though salted egg has been done to death, the chiffon cake was very soft and melded well with the salted egg sauce, making for a light but satisfying snack. I&#39;d come back, but pity they only open during work hours on the weekdays!

text: Nice outlet at T4 Changi too!<br>This morning we planned to have breakfast at this outlet but it&#39;s our busy Monday so I had to skip it but to our delight, Heavenly Wang now is at T4 Changi Airport. Tonight on our back home to Jakarta we had a big chicken bun and &#39;roti prata&#39; for dinner. It&#39;s delicious as expected. It&#39;s a quiet outlet here but well, it&#39;s kind of late anyway.

text: The place was pretty crowded for a Sunday morning. Best chop a table first before joining the queue at the counter to place order for food. After placing order, one would be given a buzzer which would light up when food is ready for collection. As for drinks, wait for the staff to call your buzzer number at the counter. Quite messy, so best take a table near the counter. Anyway we get to see the staffs working on our bread.<br><br>Steamed Bread Set (S$4.50)<br>Soft &amp; fluffy warm steamed bread with fragrant kaya butter spread<br>Served with large hot drink (Kopi/ Teh) and 2 half boiled eggs<br>The half boiled eggs were cooked just right with the yolks still runny. Nice with just a dash of dark soya sauce and pepper.<br>I selected Teh C for set which was rich without too sweet.<br>The bread was soft and moist, with thick layer of spread on top.<br><br>Kaya &amp; Butter Bun Set (S$5.50)<br>Served with large hot drink (Kopi/ Teh)<br>2 Thick buns with thick layers of spread on it. Although it was just 2 buns, it was quite filling.

text: Rather disappointing that this chain took over the classic Red House. I was here on a weekday day afternoon, the place was rather empty so it was a quiet respite compared to the other chain across the road at I12. It&#39;s just like another kopi joint selling kaya and boiled eggs. This outlet also sells the old school bitter cakes. However, it&#39;s nothing like the old world charm of the former Red House.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/isUiaup5JEID1WskucRCZw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/delifrance-jelita-singapore?reviewid=6YhJZi62m-8RlKnfxRFm7g&select=isUiaup5JEID1WskucRCZw', 'altText': 'Photo of Delifrance Jelita - Singapore, Singapore. Brie and ham sandwich', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Brie and ham sandwich'}]
text: If you are looking for a place to relax for a while, or have a bite at Jelita Shopping Centre, then Delifrance is the only option you have. Well, unless you want to buy the roast meat or sushi or bread from Cold Storage and Cedele below. <br><br>The food is average as per the norm in the other Delifrance outlets. It has upped the ante by offering brie and camembert instead of the usual sliced cheese. While the food is nothing to rave about, the service is pretty good. The staff is friendly and accommodating. They gave me a glass of ice to go with my order of tea to make my own iced tea as the only iced version is the lemon tea from the machine. <br><br>With no good food to draw a crowd, Delifrance is usually quiet and you can always find a table here. Perfect if you want to have a cuppa while someone else is doing the grocery shopping or at the clinic or you are just waiting to kill time. <br><br>With Times the bookstore across, you can also pick up a book or magazine and read it at over a slice of cake and tea.

text: Not the first time that I have to wait for more than 15mins for my food. Today&#39;s the worst as the staff took a pretty long time to get the customers&#39; orders. The restaurant wasn&#39;t even crowded. They also ran out of soup of the day and you gotta wait for at least 20mins for it. Not a place to come to if you are in a rush.

text: I am a big fan of Cedele, so whenever possible, I make sure to pick up a sandwich or salad from the nearest Cedele for lunch or a quick pick-me-up in the afternoons. <br><br>This particular Cedele in Novena Square is a little small and feels cramped. It&#39;s also along the route to the MRT station so there&#39;s always lots of traffic going by, making this place pretty noisy as well. <br><br>I wouldn&#39;t recommend staying here for your meal, especially since it&#39;ll be hard to get a table in the first place, but the food is, as always, excellent, and it&#39;s totally worthwhile to grab something to take away.

My beef pastrami sandwich... Clearly not the Katz&#39;s Deli behemoth that I was dreaming of, lol. $8.50', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "My beef pastrami sandwich... Clearly not the Katz's Deli behemoth that I was dreaming of, lol. $8.50"}]
text: Oh dear.<br><br>My most recent visit here was an unfortunate reminder of why I don&#39;t come here in the first place. I was looking for something fast and healthy-ish, and needed a break from my usual lunch rotation. <br><br>Looking at the menu, the pastrami sandwich caught my eye. I was pretty hungry, and thoughts of a nicely stacked pastrami slices for $8.50 seemed like a good idea.<br><br>When my buzzer went off, I fought through a crowd of people waiting to be served, only to finally reach the counter and see a plate with a high-tea sized sandwich. <br><br>Check out my picture. There were 2, at most 3 slices of pastrami. 3 out of 4 of the bread slices were a bit too toasted, and 1 slice wasn&#39;t even toasted at all. More evidence that my bread was no good? I had to use a sizable amount of force to bite through it, causing crumbs to fly to the nearby tables (which are pretty close together, by the way.) It was pretty painful, as by the end the roof of my mouth felt... abused. It was as if it were burned!<br><br>As I struggled to get through the saddest sandwich in the world, I longingly looked at the Burger King opposite, wishing I went there instead. That&#39;s saying something, as I&#39;m team McDonald&#39;s all the way!

text: For organic products, prices are kept considerably affordable at Cedele. I had tea at their branch in Novena Square yesterday with two friends. With so many interesting items on their menu, it was hard deciding what to get! In the end, we had some of their sweet breads, Raspberry Thumbprint and their vegetarian Mexican&#39;s Wedding cookies. While the Raspberry Thumbprint cookie was crummy and a bit of a letdown, the flavourful scones, buns and Mexican Wedding cookies were delightful.<br><br>This branch is quiet, so we were seen to promptly and had no problems getting seats. The polite, patient staff and cosy ambience in the cafe enhanced the pleasure of the experience and we exited with happy bellies.

text: Being a vegetarian, I am not usually spoilt for choices in SG. However, cedele is one of the places which serves veggie sandwiches (which btw r seriously overrated!)<br>this place isn&#39;t usually my first choice to have a good meal but i made an exception today (which I m deeply regretting).<br>The quality of service and the attentiveness of the staff at the Novena Square 2 mall is simply appalling. I ordered a set menu consisting of a (veggie for me) sandwich, soup (veg again) and iced tea which they promptly WROTE down. Although the soup and tea were ready to serve but I was still made to wait and finally when my sandwich was ready I had to remind them that the rest of my order is nowhere to b seen.<br>With great displeasure the guy at the counter quickly poured some brownish water (ice tea apparently!) and some soup all around the bowl.<br>To my utter disgust I found out that the soup contained chicken pieces when one of the shredded pieces rolled around my tongue ( as a vegetarian there is nothing more Disgusting than that, trust me).<br>I guess it was wrong on my part to assume that they got my order right which they had duly noted (may b it is just to get the charge right).<br>I write this review with utter disgust and dismay and vowing to never go to this place ever again!

Been wanting to try Maccha House since I was in Japan earlier. Not my everyday stop but definitely a good treat yourself and lovely cafe to share some sweets with friends! <br><br>FOOD: <br>1. Mille crepe cake 3/5: we wanted to get Lady M but the queue was long, so we settled for this crepe cake. However, we were really disappointed as the layers were thick and the overall cake rather dry. There was also strawberry compote and azuki red beans that were just too sweet when combined with the rest of the cake. <br>2. Green tea tiramisu 5/5: comes with tea to combat the subtle sweetness. <br>3. Ice cream parfait 4/5: use that long spoon to get to the bottom pudding layer! The matcha soft serve itself is really rich and impressive, so combined with mochi, azuki, and all that other flair, this parfait still satisfies your sweet tooth without overshadowing the dominant matcha flavor.

text: Cozy and quiet place in the middle of Orchard Road to indulge in all things matcha. I chose an order which had a bit of everything- soft serve, crepe cake and fruits. Would have appreciated a bit more fruits but otherwise the portion is just nice and not too overwhelming. Can definitely taste the matcha flavour and it&#39;s not too sweet. Would drop by again in future.

text: I had seen photos of the famous matcha tiramisu all over social media and could not wait to try it. Unfortunately, I must say that I was unimpressed by the matcha tiramisu here. Each bite was much too soft and soggy for my taste. I was hoping that the dessert itself would be more cake-y and not taste so strongly of soaked ladyfingers, but this was not the case. Additionally, the portion size was tragically small. The presentation was simple and clean, but the thick edges of the box meant that the dessert itself was extremely small.<br><br>I&#39;m glad I finally got to try this famous dessert, but it was definitely overhyped in my opinion.

text: Smart Idea: There are lots of restaurants upstairs. Go there for a meal, then come down here for desert. Make sure you save enough room for desert... well, there is ALWAYS room for desert anyways, right?<br>That&#39;s exactly what I did. Even though my friends and I were full, we couldn&#39;t help but to come here to continue our eating adventures.<br>*Celeb alert: There is a waiter here who is an internet celebrity! There were girls taking &#34;selfies&#34; with him in the background.<br><br>We shared the green tea sampler which is a good way to try all the deserts, including the green tea tiramisu. We also had the deconstructed green tea cheesecake. <br><br>Overall, not a bad place for desert, but its a little bit pricey!

I pass by Maccha House frequently and finally gave in at one point as I do love me some matcha, but it was underwhelming to say the least (at least compared to my expectations).<br><br>I ordered the teriyaki chicken kamameshi - chicken, rice and veggies that came with salad and soup. The portion itself was quite small, so the additional sides helped. The taste was nothing to write home about, a bit bland and required chili to make it more pleasing. <br><br>I also ordered their iced matcha latte, while great with the amount of matcha, it was too sweet for my liking.<br><br>OK to have tried as a one time option.

Meh :-/ Fancied iced matcha and ramen, saw the sign, thinking &#39;hooray they actually sell both&#39;, and was given free choice of seating.<br><br>Ordered with a very obnoxious wait staff - she pretended to not speak English and then spoke it two tables away from me. <br><br>The tonkotsu ramen special - practically &#34;smacked&#34; in front of me - was nondescript, the actual dish greatly deviating from the picture; very small pieces of meat, with actually just fat. <br><br>Iced matcha was nice but I can make that at home so no magic involved there.<br><br>Speaking of magic: the lunch-set at 13,99 S$ came to S$ 16,50 - plus tax, plus service charge.<br>Service, what service?<br><br>The girls sitting two tables away from me ordered a dessert platter they wanted to share, only to find out that when it arrived the portions had magically shrunk compared to what was pictured in the menu...<br><br>A truly magical place I will stay away from in the future!

text: Convenient location to satiate that Matcha craving.  Albeit a bit artificial tasting as compared with the more traditional options in the nearby Takashimaya, I enjoyed the green tea soft serve and tofu skin green tea soba soup noodles reasonably.  Not the best, not the worst.

The serving of the Spicy Fried Pork with Half-Boiled Egg Rice Bowl was very little and not much wow factor into it.<br> <br>The Tonkotsu Ramen was not really impressive as the pork belly was very little and the broth taste wasn&#39;t as strong as the other tonkotsu ramens I have tried before. The half-boiled egg was still passable though.<br> <br>The Regular Matcha Latte was also a disapppointment item as the matcha tastes rather powdery.<br> <br>Will skip this place unless desserts are available

text: Delicious matcha soy milk pudding coated with sweet kuromitsu sauce. Their matcha latte had a strong matcha flavor which is good (much better than Dolce Tokyo&#39;s which tasted like melted ice cream). Look forward to returning to try out more of their desserts and maybe food.

text: stop by this cute little joint  and it was good, great tasting tea especially when it&#39;s cold. It is convenient and tasty too.<br>Not everyone can get quality like this

meh dessert at the basement of orchard central - okay in a pinch, but tsujiri&#39;s much better. although to be fair, their vanilla soft serve isn&#39;t too bad.<br><br>it&#39;s a large open cafe, and somewhat dingy despite being new - it&#39;s suffering from crowds, with less than white tables and a rather inefficient queueing system. you go up to the counter to rather confused staff who can&#39;t quite deal with the crowd, so it takes time to place an order, and more time for it to arrive at your table. it may have lauded provenance - it&#39;s meant to be a kyoto chain, but you wouldn&#39;t know it.<br><br>we had a couple of desserts - the typical parfait bowl with soft serve, jellies and syruped fruit, a vanilla in-cone soft serve, and a couple of green tea drinks. not impressed at all. the soft serve was passable, but very watered down in comparison to tsujiri&#39;s, and it melts down too quickly (which is possibly the greatest sin a soft serve could commit). <br><br>not cheap (though possibly it&#39;s more just to say it&#39;s not quite worth plonking down your good money for), and the place feels dingy - I&#39;d recommend even the slightly-too-sweet cold stone creamery upstairs instead of this.
The tiramisu was frozen. The green tea latte looked like it was going to be hot based on the picture but was served cold with too many big square pieces of ice which almost completely filled the cup.

text: So Cali cafe has been revamped with a new interior, new concept and looks like the same management with a different direction. <br><br>They serve American cuisines with an Indian twist. The management seems to like Indian food and you will always notice an Indian guy standing at the front welcoming customers. I&#39;m guessing he&#39;s the boss. <br><br>The staff are friendly and they know that most customers walk in during lunch with a groupon that they&#39;ve sold thousands of coupons online. <br><br>The food has improved. No more burnt food. Their portions have improved. I had the fish and chips twice I was there.

text: Food is decent. Nice mushroom soup. Great honey butter fries. Good honey grilled chicken. Wagyu burger could be buttered but otherwise ok. Service staff were great but sadly I probably won&#39;t be back because they don&#39;t serve plain water. I need to drink when I eat. I don&#39;t mind paying a charge for water. But when you serve good food at cafe prices the water is really a marginal cost. I don&#39;t drink soft drinks so to keep paying for Evian.....sorry...no go.

text: This place is quite bad. I waited 30mins for my pizza when they had no other customers. Then I said I wanted to take it to go but they wanted to charge me for $5. What kind of customer service is this? This is actually in conjunction with a hotel so the price is quite high. <br><br>It&#39;s run by Indian guys so it&#39;s not authentic Hawaiian pizza. They make it like Indian pizza with super thin hard crusts that it almost broke my teeth because it was over baked. And there is no flavour in the pizza and no little pineapple.

text: Second time here. The first visit was almost 2 years ago, heard that they had revamped the menu so thought I&#39;d give it another shot, but standards have unfortunately only dropped further. <br><br>Had dinner for 2 - shared a plate of ribs and a mushroom soup. The ribs were lukewarm on the outside, cold on the inside. Obviously had just been microwaved. The mushroom soup was hopelessly bland. My companion described it pretty accurately - &#34;Tastes like water with blended mushrooms, with a few dashes of truffle oil in a futile attempt to save it&#34;. The fries that came with the ribs were the only saving grace. <br><br>Worst of all, BOTH times I visited, we were visited by a rat scurrying around the alfresco area - Perhaps not the fault of the restaurant per se, but disturbing nonetheless. and an issue that restaurant management should really consider raising to their premise manager.

text: One of worst cafes in the world. I wun even bother to try to find words to describe this disaster except to say it as it is. Overpriced. Tasteless. Gst n service charge (wat service?).. My secondary school BBQ can do a better marinate than this. If u are here using 1-1 coupon, u din get any 1-1. Basically u got in value wat u paid for. Pathetic food! When is it closing down. I can spend double the amount and feel completely satisfied. Or half the amount here and feel totally disgusted.

text: Avoid.  We were the only people there and the food wasn&#39;t cooked nicely.  Carbonara was tasteless, sauce was watery.  Chicken tasted like a $5 chicken from ntuc...  Actually half of a $5 chicken. Plate came dirty.  Please try something else.

Very very aromatic coffee! Consistently thick and just so goood! The lurking chocolately-ness of the coffee is almost waiting to pounce on you as you have your sip. This place makes magic local Singapore coffee or what we call &#39;kopi&#39;. Must-try!!

text: I don&#39;t recommend using the eatigo app for this restaurant. It took them about 20 minutes to bring the drinks, 40 minutes to bring the eggs Benedict out. Meanwhile I observed the table next to us get their drinks within 3 minutes of ordering, and their Eggs Benedict within 15minutes. <br><br>My food arrived cold and the lettuce was rotten. You&#39;ll notice the difference in service over the measly 10% you&#39;ll save on the eatigo app. Shame, my first time using the app to make a reservation and probably my last.<br><br>Also worthy to note, the food took 40+ minutes to arrive, but when they served the food they asked for payment right away. No enjoyment to be had here.<br><br>TLDR: if you can swing full price, do it. Won&#39;t be making that mistake again if I dine here again.

text: Whilst waiting for our movies to start, we needed a place to chill for a good hour so we walked around and found this place. At $8 SGD per person every hour, we both thought it was a steal. For that amount, beverages (coffee, tea, and sodas) and snacks (chips, cookies, crackers) galore and access to their video game consoles, computers, and a mini pool table. <br><br>Jerry snagged the pool table. It seems to be a game I suck at horribly but I remained determined and calm for the most part. He had fun beating me and making fun of me and of course I laugh it off and hit him occasionally. I swear, we tease each other like this everyday regardless if we&#39;re at work or not. <br><br>We had fun. Jerry and I have worked together for years. Because of this trip, we have gotten closer. I cannot believe how much fun we have had in the past 3 weeks we have been here in Singapore. It doesn&#39;t even seem like work. <br><br>Highly recommend this place.

text: HOT stands for House of Taste.  Coffee by day, after work watering hole by night. The space is uniquely shaped, and small, but they have done a good job of maximizing the seating area.   The interior design is industrial modern and very cool.  They are known for their single origin specialty coffee.  There will always be something new to taste or smell here as they change their coffee bean selection regularly.  They always have 3 options of beans to choose from.  Depending on how you want your coffee - espresso style, or V60 pour-over.  All their coffees are served double shot.   There is also a selection of tees, cold-pressed juices, and aloe vera drinks.  They also had a selection of deserts, in house made sandwiches, and yoghurt-granola jars. The menu can be overwhelming for a first timer like me, but the staff were extremely friendly and helped walk me through my options.  They suggested that I try an iced coffee latte.  It was refreshing, flavorful,  and served in a mason jar that is yours to keep (included in the price). Quality coffee at decent Singaporean prices.  I wish my hotel was near this spot as I would have come back here several times during my trip if I could.

text: I absolutely loved the Kaya Toast here! I&#39;ve been itching to try Singapore&#39;s infamous Kaya Toast and luckily, Toast Box was only a few minutes away from my hotel. Not to mention, it was opened bright and early, which was perfect for the jet lagged me. <br><br>Toast Box is situated at the basement of The Centrepoint and one of the earliest places opened for business in the building. When I got to Toast Box with my boyfriend, there were already a few customers enjoying their breakfast and one person ahead of us. When it was our turn, we told the lady what we wanted but she asked us questions in Mandarin. Unfortunately, our Mandarin is pretty crappy but we used context clues. LOL. My boyfriend saw noodles on the menu so he tried to order that but it wasn&#39;t available. Not sure if it&#39;s not a breakfast thing or just no longer on the menu. So he got the cheese toast (came with ham and egg on top) while I got the Kaya toast. The lady asked us what drinks we would like with our meals and what type of eggs we wanted with the Kaya Toast. We went with honey tea, milk tea, and soft boiled eggs (came with 2 eggs). <br><br>The seating area is small but there&#39;s more seats and tables outside of the enclosed space! The drinks, Kaya toast, and eggs were ready under 5 minutes. But the cheese w/ ham &amp; egg toast took awhile. Understandable as there was only one lady managing the cash register and one man cooking. <br><br>My kaya toast was delicious! Crusty on the outside and amazingly sweet and warm inside. The kaya (coconut jam) flavor was very subtle and blended perfectly with the slice of butter that was slightly melting from the warm toast. What surprised me even more were the soft boiled eggs. Omg. How can something so simple taste so addictingly good?! The cheese toast was just alright. Really liked the milk tea too. Comparable to Hong Kong&#39;s cha chan tang&#39;s. <br><br>I saw jars of Hainanese kaya being sold by Toast Box for around $5-$6. I was really tempted to buy it but then I found kaya being sold at Cold Storage. It was a supermarket on the same floor as Toast Box. It wasn&#39;t the Toast Box brand but it was only $3 so I went with that instead lol.

text: I was early for a meeting and decided to get a cuppa of coffee and snack. I always like Maison Kayser&#39;s breads and tarts. The menu at this Chulia Street branch is different from the one at Scott&#39;s. Here they cater to the office crowd. With so many other cafes around the area, like Cedele, Artease, Starbucks, Maison Kayser stands out for their delicious breads. The sitting area is also spacious unlike those cramped small stools and tables at close proximity. And yes, did I mention the cheerful and wonderful service from the guys at the counter!

text: Famous Thai tea brand in Thailand has multiple outlets here in Singapore. <br><br>I&#39;ve been to this branch a couple of times and the staff have always been very nice and the drink have never disappointed. Thanks! :) <br><br>Classic original Thai milk tea, Thai milk tea extra gold are the two norms for me. Also the Thai green tea I&#39;ve tried and was okay and is more like Jasmine green and was good too but I prefer the classic Thai and Thai extra gold. <br><br>I believe the extra gold has a much stronger tea taste. <br><br>You can order drinks hot or cold or even some blended.<br><br>They also sell coffee, matcha, and honey milk. This branch also has Shibuya thick toast and simple sandwich sets. <br><br>Overall ambiance, pretty chill and nice staff. Order on one side and collect on the other part of the counter. Many office workers come from in from around this area too. Generally a good place I can count on for a good cup of tea. <br><br>Tip/ you can ask for more/less ice <br>Tip2/ it&#39;s inside the Far East Square mall <br>Tip3/ they have wooden chairs and tables inside and outside the place too<br>Tip4/ cash only

text: *Coffee Snob Intro*<br>When you&#39;re let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.<br><br>These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.<br><br>I&#39;m going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.<br><br>----------------------------------<br>OVERALL: 4 stars<br><br>Ambience: 5<br>Coffee: 3<br>Food: N/A (did not try)<br>Meeting Place: 4<br>Working Space: 4<br>----------------------------------<br><br>*Coffee Review*<br><br>Quaint. Quirky. Quizzical. This space has it all, and I&#39;ve run out of Q&#39;s.<br><br>Adorning the walls are assorted bric-à-brac that wouldn&#39;t be out of place in your Grandma&#39;s kitchen.<br><br>I had 2 Long Blacks and a Soy Latte. The coffee was good, but not great.<br><br>However, the ambience really excels here and gives you a boost. In addition to the attractive art deco style, is the interesting plethora of people coming-going-and-enjoying the space. <br><br>There were friends catching up for coffee and a chat; business people interviewing potential hires; young mothers grabbing a coffee on-the-go; fit people getting their java buzz after a workout; and myself looking for somewhere to chill and sip a coffee whilst working on the mundaneness of a LinkedIn profile.<br><br>I didn&#39;t try the food, so cannot comment on that.<br><br>As a place to meet, greet and have a quick laptop lurk, this cute little cafe in Lor Kilat (near Bukit Timah) cannot be beat.

text: The cafe was located across the road from the MRT station. The place looked cozy and warm especially when outside was raining. The drink menu was listed on the board, with assorted cakes and pastries on the display shelf.<br><br>Lemon Drizzle Loaf Cake (S$5.20)<br>The cake was heated when served. It was soft and not too sweet or sour.<br><br>Merry Trio Latte (S$7)<br>Vanilla, Hazelnut, Caramel<br>I had the iced version, which was served in a jar. Refreshing drink but could not really taste the distinct flavours in it. <br><br>There was free wifi in the cafe. I was sitting at a table by the wall, which had a row of power points. There was a note paste on top which allowed customers to use the power point but limited to 15 minutes.

text: I have heard lots about Carpenter and Cook, though I don&#39;t remember exactly what it is I am supposed to try. I guess with the flurry of small cafes, bakeries, patisseries sprouting up in recent months (or is it years already?), it is hard to keep track. After a while, they really do seem to serve the same old stuff, taste about the same, cost also about the same, that most are pretty forgettable. <br><br>I may like a pretty thing but what will leave an indelible impression will be the taste. Taste over appearance for me. <br><br>The first impression of Carpenter and Cook is the darkness and seemingly messiness. It is not really messy, but it has a lot of things (antique or old stuff) crammed into the shop. And many wooden furniture inside also makes the place look darker than it actually is. <br><br>I do quite like the vibe. Almost indie to me. Everything sort of work together even though everything is so mis-matched. That adds to the charm. You just share a big table if there are no smaller tables available. Quite nice actually. Everyone talks in a normal/soft tone so it is just a low hum of conversation, nothing jarring to the ears. And so you won&#39;t be an unwilling eavesdropper at all, even if you are sharing a table with strangers. <br><br>After checking reviews on what was the recommended food (i.e. passionfruit meringue tart and lemon cream tart - isn&#39;t that wonderful of having a smartphone and internet and google and yelp and blogs?), I went to place my order. <br><br>While there, I was very taken with the lemon meringue cake and the banoffee tart. They looked very tempting. I decided to just try the lemon meringue cake. It is quite rare to find a meringue cake and even rarer to find one which does it well. <br><br>I love the lemon meringue cake which has 2 layers of sponge cake with a thin layer of  lemon curd and topped with meringue all around. The cake was moist and you could really taste the freshness of it. No day-old cake at all. The tartness of the lemon made a perfect foil against the slight sweetness of the cake and the sweeter meringue which was also very nicely done.  I liked that the meringue was not the typical hard type when served on its own but was a bit foamy soft and yet could stand on its own. You could just taste the egg white and sugar whipped until stiff and then browned a little in the heat. <br><br>The sea salt chocolate caramel tart was nice but nothing memorable. For a chocolate lover, it is saying a lot when I actually prefer the tart instead of the sweet.<br><br>P.S. I like the placement of lemons scattered all over the place. It does create a pop of color and cheer in the brownness of the place.

text: Uh oh... Is Success and popularity getting to Carpenter and cook&#39;s head? <br><br>Ever since I first tried the place... I&#39;ve seen and tasted a steady decline amongst the sweet cakes and tarts. <br><br>So far, some of the crew&#39;s greetings resembles somewhere between a frost bite and an eclipse. <br>The food itself seems..well...it taste and feels like the love that was poured into the making of those tarts... Have left. <br>What was once raved as one of the best, if not the best place to have fantastic tarts, has now slowly started fading.<br><br>From our last 3 visits, we&#39;ve experienced overcooked and slightly burnt pastry, followed by undercooked pastry and finally today, salad with arugula that looks like it&#39;s been sitting in the bowl since this morning. Although the lettuce seemed fresher, it really looked like all they did was top up and left the bottom as it was, soaking in whatever dressing was there and turning into a dead mush in the process. <br><br>It really feels like the basics have gone out the window. <br>That said, we&#39;ll still be back and I just hope it doesn&#39;t decline any further that it already has.

text: My favourite secret spot for Sunday brunch and a delectable piece of passion fruit meringue tart

Lots has been said about Carpenter &amp; Cook so I believe the average yelper (or any foodie worth her salt) would have heard about it this place. <br><br>First off, the positives: the ladies at the counter were friendly, the decor of the place gives a feel of something found if Old-school and Indie got married. I&#39;m a bit biased when it comes to arty decor and the ambience of this place just hit it off with me so very well. <br><br>Now, the not-so-good stuff: Despite all the praises sung about the pastries, I honestly felt I could find much better alternatives elsewhere. I found the lemon meringue to be average at best, and the sea salt choc tart... well... something I&#39;d try once and only once. And now where I get really picky: I&#39;ve tried Liberty coffee - and while I immensely enjoyed the latter, I found the coffee at C&amp;C to be rather weak. So.... I&#39;d have to say I differ in my opinion from what seems to be everybody else when I say that the coffee was rather disappointing. <br><br>All in all, though I really loved the design of the place, I don&#39;t think I&#39;d come back. The food was decent, but nothing particularly noteworthy for me; and if you&#39;re as picky about coffee as I am, you&#39;d know there are plenty of other places to go to get a good dose.

text: I admit my friend is one of the 3 owners but why I came 3 times in 2 weeks starting with a private soft-launch (even though this is out of my way) is because I love the lemon meringue tart (it&#39;s very tarty you might say which suits me to a T-for-Tart), the brioche is full of yums (yes I brought my saturday brunch mate friend as soon as we could find the time so she could try it) and the coffee is very respectable despite the lack of latte art. It&#39;s roasted by Liberty and drinking the coffee there a few times made me want to go checkout Liberty (but they&#39;re always closed and I only have so much time on weekends anyway).<br><br>Love how all the furniture is so unique and while I am a modernist at heart, the place has a real character and comfy quirky vibe without looking old-fashioned.

text: always wanted to try it out and headed down for brunch on Sunday with my friend.<br> We were both raving about the Passionfruit meringue tart - refreshingly savory. The bacon quiche was delicious as well and I&#39;m not a salad person, but their side salad was really good. <br><br>We also tried the Raspberry brownie but the flavor was too dark chocolatey for our liking. Gets rather gelat after a while. <br><br>Still, nothing like enjoying a nice meal with their quaint ambience, and sipping tea and coffee. Will come back next time for their tarts!

text: Beautiful cafe! Has the most amazing, delicious desserts! I absolutely looooooved the desserts at this cafe. Highly recommend this place to everyone :) a must try !

text: Headed down for a quick lunch meeting so I didn&#39;t get to try much other than the tea.<br><br>I have to say the decor for the place is absolutely spiffing and probably the thing Enid Blyton novels are made up of. Love the bits and pieces on display and for sale. Pick up some tea cups if you even want an extra quality in your life. You can just start with your first special tea cup, even if you don&#39;t want to pick up the entire set. Trust me when I saw tea works better in special teacups.<br><br>I&#39;ve heard amazing things about their quiche and passionfruit meringue tart. Marcus&#39; story about the place below sounds amazing so I&#39;m looking forward to partake in the &#34;cook&#34; part of this cafe.<br><br>I know of a friend holding an engagement party at this very spot!<br><br>All in all, I&#39;ll give a go for the atmosphere alone - non-pretentious and pretty private amongst your seating space. The servers are polite and helpful without being too intrusive, something which I always appreciate. Will be back to try more of the food and review this spot again!

Best lemon cream tart in Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Best lemon cream tart in Singapore'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/l_51qn8BcljIDvhYnrDzXw/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/carpenter-and-cook-singapore?reviewid=nn52ZBUNNhg3Hcwpsow31A&select=l_51qn8BcljIDvhYnrDzXw', 'altText': 'Photo of Carpenter and Cook - Singapore, Singapore. Freshly baked pastries', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Freshly baked pastries'}]
text: Once upon a time, there were 3 girls with a dream, a dream of having their own little place, decorated with curated pieces of vintage and filled with the buttery aroma of cakes and bakes. It&#39;ll be a place where friends will share secrets over a pot of tea, where lovers reunite, where lost treasures are found. But dreams will remain as dreams unless you have the courage to pursue it. So they did. And Carpenter and Cook was born. <br><br>The shop is exactly out of a fairy tale. The nostalgia and charm of a time lost and then rediscovered. The interior is warmy and cosy, peppered with an eclectic mix of handpicked and restored furniture. There is just this air of positivity and hope. I guess it must have come from Phoebe, Shenn and Eunice, who obviously have put in their heart and soul into the place. <br><br>There is something romantic about old furniture. Who did it belong to? What was the owner like? Why did they buy it? Who was it for? Each piece comes with a history that we may never know about; each a mystery.<br><br>I pondered these over the freshly baked tarts (S$6.20) and a cup of mocha. The bakes are as dreamy as everything else. These are made by the Cordon Bleu trained hands of Shenn and each bite was as delicious as you can imagine. For me, my search for the best tart ends here. <br><br>The crisp and buttery tart base is everything one would look for. It doesn&#39;t fall to pieces when you cut or bite into it. Neither is it too soft that it fails to hold the filling. <br><br>The Chocolate Sea Salt Caramel tart was a bitter sweet delight. I like that it isn&#39;t too cloyingly sweet. A hint of sea salt gives way to a smokey caramel and then you hit the bitter notes of the chocolate in the aftertaste. There is a clear separation of the chocolate and the tart but it melts from the warmth of your lips and becomes a rich elixir that goes down easily. <br><br>The Lemon Cream tart was a custard and eggy delight. It&#39;s a little sharp but that&#39;s it&#39;s character. I guess a person&#39;s taste preference is also an indication of what they are like. Obviously i&#39;m not the sweet and docile girl. I declare this to be the best tart in Singapore. It can&#39;t get better than this.

This kooky little cafe tucked away in the Upper Bukit Timah neighbourhood of Lorong Kilat is certainly no stranger to being reviewed.  When we got to Carpenter &amp; Cook one Sunday afternoon, we were greeted simultaneously by the chatter of diners, the clinking of cutlery and the aroma of oven-baked goodies the moment we pushed through the wood-panelled door. As we waited in line for a seat, the couple next to us used a vintage display cabinet as a tabletop for filling in a form to have their pre-wedding shoot held here.<br><br>As with all wildly popular eateries, there&#39;s always a presumption that service will be brusque and impersonal. I&#39;m happy to report that the servers we encountered at Carpenter &amp; Cook were welcoming and chirpy. Furnished with rustic pieces acquired by one of its three co-owners from all over the world, the cafe exuded a homely and laid-back vibe in spite of the teatime crowd. Communal seating is practised here, which is fine by me since I&#39;ve recently been trained not to attack openly affectionate couples.<br><br>Lavender Bundt Cake, $4.00 - Whilst surveying the pastries on display, we were a little taken aback by how steep the prices were. It took just four bites to finish this palm-sized bundt cake (we&#39;re talking preschooler hands here), which tasted quite uninspiring. It was my first encounter with lavender in cake form, though apart from some notes of cinnamon I frankly couldn&#39;t detect anything else in the cake. I also felt the honey glaze was superfluous since it added neither depth of flavor nor moisture to the cake, which was a little too dry.<br><br>Passionfruit Meringue Tart, $6.50 - Highly raved about in almost every review of Carpenter &amp; Cook I&#39;ve read, this tart had a crisp, buttery shell that broke off easily when you cut into it with a fork. The beautifully seared meringue peaks had a texture akin to toasted marshmallow innards... that&#39;s actually meant to be much more delicious than it reads. Found the passionfruit curd way too sweet, but supporters swear by it so if too much sugar&#39;s your thing, go right ahead and order this.<br><br>Smashing Savoury Brioche Bun (Veg.), $6.50 - A sprinkle of sundried tomatoes, pine nuts, olives and a couple sprigs of parsley on a fluffy brioche bun. I have to say the bun was moist, soft and wonderfully herby, but for six friggin&#39; fifty? I wouldn&#39;t have ordered this if I were allowed to have things my own tyrannical way.<br><br>Triple chocolate chip muffin, $3.50 - This was a flat out disaster. The muffin was so dry that every poke of the fork triggered an avalanche of crumbs. Also, the chocolate used was sickeningly sweet and of exceedingly poor quality - I say this as someone who has no qualms about eating Van Houten chocolates by the boxful.<br><br>Flat White, $5.00 - Like any Singaporean cafe worth their salt, Carpenter &amp; Cook utilises the Speakeasy blend from Liberty Coffee. Sadly, premium beans alone do not a good cup of coffee make. My flat white was served lukewarm, left a slightly acrid aftertaste, and came with zero art boohoohoo. Maybe it was because the cafe was crowded when we visited, but they could definitely pay a little more attention to detail for drink prep.<br><br>By the end of our visit we were left scratching our heads about the hype surrounding Carpenter &amp; Cook. It&#39;s obvious that they have the leisurely come-burn-your-weekend-afternoon-with-us ambiance bit down pat, but food and price wise there&#39;s so much room for improvement you could fit Mariah Carey and her entourage in there. I&#39;d like to think that we visited on an off-day. I guess I wouldn&#39;t mind coming back if I happen to be in the area, though it&#39;ll be an uphill task convincing me to go out of my way to visit Carpenter &amp; Cook a second time.

text: Staff are really friendly. Deserts are in quite small servings so we got to order a wide selection of choices and shared! Plus point, their tea has an free refill so definitely something you would want to have all that cake go down easily (:

Phoebe, Shenn &amp; Eunice - You girls did such an awesome job with the place&#39;s deco and most importantly FOOD. I&#39;ll definitely be back here again (although I live sooo far away). That&#39;s how much I&#39;ve fallen in love with the place. Thanks for taking the time to chat with us and explain the lovely selection of food. <br><br>The Food  <br>1) Quiche  (ham and mushroom) -  It was amazing!!! The texture was smooth &amp; practically melt-in-your-mouth.  The crust was baked to perfection! It&#39;s no surprise to learn that the cook trained in the prestigious Cordon Bleu in London. This is indeed no ordinary Quiche<br><br>2) Passionfruit Meringue Tart - Another must try item!!! It&#39;s just heaven!!! omg!!! I&#39;ve never been a huge fan of tarts but this one was AMAZING. It took all my will power to not gobble up the whole piece and leave some for Kah Hong to try. I think I managed to leave like 1/4 (at least I tried)... haha... he loved it too!!!  The passionfruit filling was creamy, thick and not-too-sweet. While the crust was crispy and baked to perfection just like the Quiche. <br><br>3) Drinks - I love the Elderflower soda (makes me think of LOTR for some reason. food for the elves. I am sure they would approve). The Ginger beer was a tad bit too strong for me but Kah seems to be ok with it. He&#39;s the adventurous foodie. Anyways, what a unique selection of sodas they have! Seriously, I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve seen them anywhere else in Singapore. <br><br>The Ambiance<br>Beautiful! Vintage furnitures that has a nostalgic old world, British cafe feel to it :)<br><br>Tip: Heard it gets pretty crowded on weekends so go early! or on weekdays nights (perfect chill out place after a long day of work).

In a word - gorgeous.<br><br>This is a story of three friends, who all do different things, but somehow marry their interests to form one pretty cool spot.<br><br>Phoebe is the &#34;carpenter&#34; - she&#39;s responsible for picking up most of the furniture and knick-knacks you see in the store, including the tables and chairs you sit on. All of it was picked up as a hobby while she used to live in London, when it hit her that she should ship all of it back home. Lucky us, eh? I&#39;ve seen seriously cool stuff, including a couple of rotary phones - they even use one for the shop phone.<br><br>Shenn is the &#34;cook&#34;, and she makes all the bakes... and this includes the brioche they use for their sandwiches, and the tart shells in their ridiculously awesome passionfruit meringue tarts, and even the killer passionfruit marshmallows. Yes, she makes marshmallows. Oh, and she makes jams too. Just sayin&#39;.<br><br>Eunice is the &#34;and&#34;, and boy does she tie everything together. She runs the cafe front, and if that isn&#39;t enough, she also offers food styling and dessert table services. It&#39;s a little much for me to digest, so you&#39;ll want to check with her for more details.<br><br>These lovely ladies have put together quite a stellar store, and you have to go check them out, if even just to see all the stuff for yourself.

The good: Brushed through a group outside, walked through the door and was greeted with a salutation and a huge smile. Told her it was my first time and she cheerfully recommended a few items, 2 of which I got: lemon tart and bacon quiche. Atmosphere was buzzing, full house but I managed to get a seat.  It&#39;s an amazing throw back to the 20&#39;s, ragtime music, sewing tables and old school advertising. Felt like I was on an episode of The Pickers: everything is for sale. <br><br>The bad: Quiche was served cold and the so called best lemon tart in Singapore was good but not mind blowing. The custard was spot on, but the crust was too thin and hard. Was also served my latter in a glass...WHY?  This isn&#39;t the only spot that is guilty of this, but I can&#39;t for the life of me figure out why places do this. You should never put hot water in glass. First of all once the heat from the water will go to the surface of the glass causing the glass to absorb heat, making it fire hot.  Secondly, after the glass gets scorching hot, the water gives up heat into the air, reducing the temperature of the water (drink gets cold quick = bad).  Because of this, your drink goes from scorching hot to ice cold faster than you can say Carpenter + Cook, and unfortunately there isn&#39;t enough time to drink it in between.  People don&#39;t just use mugs for the cute handles, it serves a purpose.  <br><br>The ugly: Carpenter has his stuff together but Cook needs to step up their game just a bit and really wow with the food. That&#39;s the difference between 3, 4 and 5 stars: the wow factor.  Although I enjoyed 20+ minutes of old timer songs, I don&#39;t think I could handle much more. I don&#39;t know how those employees do it...but perhaps that&#39;s what makes them so smiley...they&#39;ve gone insane from the tunes.

I was pleasantly surprised to find out that a new cafe has opened up in my armpit of a neighbourhood- Jalan Jurong Kechil, the less glamourous part of Bukit Timah. I am no cafe spotter, but as a fourth year (and very restless) undergraduate with too much time on my hands, the easy excuse of &#34;coffee hunting&#34; has brought me to coffee haunts in all corners of Singapore. Now that with one just minutes from my house- there was simply no excuse to not go.<br><br>I decided to check out the place with a friend on a Sunday afternoon. Being familiar with the area we did not have any trouble locating the place, but I can imagine how the unassuming shopfront (very dark tinted windows) might be easily missed by first-timers, especially since the cafe is modestly nestled among rows of tuition centres. Even then, any trouble would be well worth your while the moment you step in- the place is warmly lit, the air is cool and well ventilated (I have a thing about smelling like the food I just ate). The decor of the place was lovely (lovely china and well-done vintage without a hint of gaudiness). Many of the ornaments and furniture are for sale, hence the &#34;Carpenter&#34; in &#34;Carpenter &amp; Cook&#34;.<br><br>The food looks absolutely delicious - tarts, pastries, cakes, coffee/teas (there isn&#39;t really any savoury food). I would have ordered every pastry available just from the way they looked- but having come from a heavy lunch, we eventually compromised on a lemon tart, a long black and an iced latte. The lemon tart definitely convinced me to make a return visit. It is is possibly my favorite lemon tart right now! It was simple- exactly how I wished it was- a sturdy pastry (perhaps a bit too hard for some) filled with a really smooth lemon curd. I won&#39;t go so far as to say it completely blew my mind- but if you&#39;ve ever had a great pastry that made your toes curl, you&#39;d totally get it. The coffee also did not disappoint- even my friend who is very much of a coffee snob remarked that it was &#39;not too bad at all&#39;.

Best lemon tart I have ever had (and I have eaten MANY all around the world).<br><br>The crust of the tarts at Carpenter &amp; Cook win HANDS DOWN.  It&#39;s crisp, buttery and a great texture in your mouth.  <br><br>Oh and it helps that you are eating on antique plates.  Makes it that much more delectable. <br><br>Would go back again and again to try everything on the menu.  This place is quaint and totally worth the trip.  Go when it&#39;s quiet so you can check out the antiques in peace.

If you are missing some old vintage charm, sneak into this enclave at Lor Kilat. In spite of the fame of the korean restaurants along this lane, the Carpenter girls ( a.k.a. the owners) have a winnng formula of vintage + bakes + retail. Every cutlery has its place in history, and effort has been made to envelop you in a forgotten era. Owing its charm to their stays in London, the bunting and pieces that litter the shop do indeed remind me of East London. <br>The cakes are divine, who would have thought passionfruit meringue tart could be this addictive? Try their selection of cakes, they hardly disappoint! Prices are fair, given the ambience, the charming fixtures that you can take home if you want, at a price of course. Chat with the staff to find out more about their interesting finds, or just put on your bell bottoms and head down here.

A place where you can go to indulge in everything Britannia, Carpenter &amp; Cook is one of those places that I fell in love with at first sight. <br><br>Discovered by chance while we were searching for a coffee joint one day after lunch, we spotted this charming little vintage furniture store and decided to venture in to take a look. Imagine my surprise when I saw there was a nice little English style bakery to boot as well. Offering up plenty of heart English sweets like scones and cakes, it&#39;s one of those places that manages to capture the quaint British essence perfectly. <br><br>Being too engrossed with taking in everything the bakery had to offer, I have to say the furniture become forgotten quickly enough and I can&#39;t really recall much.

A vintage furniture store with a twist, Carpenter &amp; Cook comes with a charming little English-style artisan bakery to boot. <br><br>We found this place while searching for furniture for my new room and my friend was delighted with what was on offer. There are plenty of hearty English sweets like scones slathered with butter and the tangy Lemon Drizzle cake. <br><br>The coffee was also good (made by local boutique roasters Liberty Coffee). I haven&#39;t been back yet, but as soon as I feel a little British fever, you can be sure I&#39;ll be!

text: Really happy I found this tiny cafe tucked away on bukit timah. The coffee was great and all the desserts looked spectacular. Really like the decor and vibe of the place .. looking forward to making a second trip.
Beef rendang ($13.90) - 5 stars<br>Simple, homey and they don&#39;t use MSG apparently. Relatively small portion.<br><br>Great place to study or chill as well. Wifi is available.

Definitely more seating in the back', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Definitely more seating in the back'}]
text: Orange Thimble faces stiff competition from their next door neighbour, Tiong Bahru Bakery. They are a bit different in that it&#39;s more a small cafe with savouries, sweets, ice cream, and coffee.<br><br>I&#39;ve only ordered their cappuccino for takeaway, and my basic coffee tastes have rendered it good. My colleagues say the food is horrible but they&#39;re a fussy bunch so I&#39;m not sure you should believe them 100%.*<br><br>On the plus side, they have a really cool space that&#39;s perfect for hanging out, catching up, or getting some work done. I&#39;ve never been able to explore the rooms further in but looking through the windows from the cashier, it looks cute.<br><br>If the &#34;too cool for school&#34; crowd next door is bothering you, Orange Thimble is a great alternative. If you chill in the outdoor space, you might get a visit from Bob, the local celebrity kitty! <br><br>*Did I say that out loud?
Great place in terms of value for money compares to most places in Tiong Bahru. The portion size is reasonable for a 13$ stew. <br>The place is rarely busy for dinner which is a plus.

text: I like Orange Thimble because it&#39;s a nice casual chill cafe. Not too noisy. Coffee is still reasonably priced. They do a nice piccolo too. Haven&#39;t tried their food though. Oh, and they have art on their walls for sale by local artists. I think that&#39;s pretty cool! I actually wanted to buy one or two pieces everytime I&#39;m there. It&#39;s like, buy coffee and art to go, pls. Hahaha. Nice little place. (It stretches all the way to the backyard)

text: I heard this place can get pretty crowded so I suppose I got lucky to head down on a slow day.<br><br>The place is lit with orange-tints which makes for a very cheerful greeting when I found it. Entering the shop, you see a welcoming display of bakes, enticing you to pick them. Wasn&#39;t up for coffee so I eventually settled for a hot chocolate and a slice of brioche (from the entire loaf I bought).<br><br>The hot chocolate was well-creamed with a fluffy foam to it and pair really nicely with marshmellows. Quite possibly the best hot chocolate I have had in SG. The lads behind the counter very nicely toasted the brioche for me to a perfect warmth. The bake was just that slight bit crispy while keeping a soft, fluffy bite within. I didn&#39;t have stomach space but was really tempted by more of the bakes. <br><br>Will definitely make a next visit.

I&#39;m kicking myself for not grabbing coffee from TBB right next door instead - it&#39;s truly daylight robbery to charge $4.50 for a Piccolo Latte that was both under extracted and washed out with burnt milk - I gave up after two mouthfuls.<br><br>This was my first try of Orange Thimble and sadly, it&#39;ll probably be my last. Of all the cafés in Tiong Bahru, I&#39;d say that they lose out based on both quality and on decour. It&#39;s truly a shame; I wished this experience wasn&#39;t so disappointing!

text: I have to admit, they&#39;ve put in lots of effort to ensure that this would be a good-looking café with a stylish set-up. However, I&#39;m not necessarily bowled over by the food or the drinks. The coffee is alright, and the cakes are good but not good enough for me to want to return and have them a second time. <br><br>All in all, this feels a bit like a case of style over substance. Getting as trendy as it is, Tiong Bahru is certain to have quite a few of these (and it certainly does...) and I&#39;m not one of those who can be won over by something that&#39;s average but happens to be well-packaged.

text: Amidst the cafes and bakeries that has sprung up in the Tiong Bahru estates, Orange Thimble is one of my favorites because it has all the right things that makes it good. Firstly it is adequately big enough for humans to be inside and not feel cramped up. However I read about how it is getting very crowded now so I would avoid it on weekends if I don&#39;t feel like dealing with everyone trying to &#39;relax&#39; at a stressful environment.<br><br>I also really liked the decor of the place. It is all vintage knick knacks and carefully sourced plates and cups. The food itself is nothing amazing to shout about, though I think they have handmade ice cream from somewhere else, and the cake I had tasted good too.<br><br>It is the perfect place to just have a cuppa and read, or have a nice catch up with a friend.

I used to frequent this stretch for brunch since it&#39;s practically next door, just great for rolling out of bed unkempt. Granted, there are more of the arty farty types hanging around now, but I figure they&#39;re too concerned with their own cool vibes than to notice my messy bed hair. <br><br>Go to orders are always, always the English Breakfast and two cups of flat white coffees. I always find English Breakfasts in SG to be severely overpriced - why do restauranteurs insist on charging upwards of $10 for toast, bacon, sausage, tomatoes, baked beans and mushrooms? Alas, being too lazy to DIY has its downsides. <br><br>How it works is that you order and pay, and are handed a buzzer that flashes and vibrates violently when your order is ready. The coffee is always aromatic and smooth, and served with an old school Iced Gem biscuit. On the other hand, the breakfast&#39;s standard tends to vary from day to day. Sometimes I get two sausages, sometimes no mushrooms, sometimes this, sometimes that. They usually make up for it in some way though. <br><br>This place gets very crowded and the wait staff are usually not able to handle the crowds. People mill around, waiting for their buzzer to buzz, and then collect their chow at the cashier, which makes it quite a bit of a squeeze. I used to go to OT out of sheer laziness, but don&#39;t go there anymore.

text: I&#39;m not a fan of sandwiches, so it&#39;s hard to give it a thorough review, but i&#39;ll say this: <br>- Cute ambience<br>- Tasty prawn floss sub- very flavorful and creative

Pretty little place along the Tiong Bahru stretch where all the hipsters now seem to be congregated. The Orange Thimble is a cute little cafe with a nice outdoor area. The decor is a bit old school and a bit modern at the same time.<br><br>Came here for coffee; there are better places for coffee. The desserts and ice cream were also okay, but not much to shout about. Not sure about the food. May come back and check it out again. But there are so many places in this area...

text: Nice place! Many cosy areas to hangout. Only pity is that like many cafés in Tiong Bahru, it doesn&#39;t provide free wifi.

Orange Thimble serves decent coffee, but really it&#39;s the chill out vibe that draws people to the cafe. Try to come on a weekday when things aren&#39;t as hectic, and you&#39;ll find yourself able to spend hours here, just lounging on a couch and flipping through last month&#39;s edition of Vogue. As previously mentioned, the coffee is decent - though if you want stellar coffee, then you&#39;re better off at neighbouring 40 hands. The Orange Thimble does serve pretty good ice cream though - try their sesame ice cream. It&#39;s served to you in a quaint white-blue china bowl - very reminiscent of your childhood. It&#39;s a perfect place for weekday brunch, and is a favourite among my group of friends

First time visiting and I had a pleasant experience. Service staff was friendly and good. Salmon miso dish had a good serving of salmon, mashed potato and some cheery tomatoes. Very comforting food. <br><br>Ordered a ribeye steak with mashed potatoes and carrots as sides. Do not like the mash potatoes sauce. Tasted a bit &#34;maggi&#34;aka instant packet thing. Do not like the lemony sauce in the carrots too. Anyhow, steak was grilled very well for medium rare. <br><br>Loved their $4.90 ice orange mint tea. A great thing to order on a hot sunny day!!<br><br>They serve their mains here after 4pm and that is when the weather gets cooler, the crowd starts to flow in and you can just enjoy the Holland Village vibe. Food overall is not the main draw but rather how the place makes you feel. I wouldnt mind turning up again.

text: Another cookie-cutter hipster cafe in Holland Village. I only stopped by for a quick drink and a chance to sit down and catch up on emails.<br><br>The passionfruit soda was quite surprising; I noticed it was taking a while to get my order through (and I was one of 5 people in the place mid-day) but once served it had a mix of fresh herbs. Nice touch.<br><br>What&#39;s lovely about their space is that you can sit out on the patio, inside, or on their second level, which has a cosy nook with a couch in it. You can also grab a hipster publication to enjoy during your stay.<br><br>Perhaps the food warrants an extra star, but seeing as I couldn&#39;t even remember the name of this place (and I visited 2 days ago) I&#39;d leave it at a-ok for now.

Just enjoying another wonderful time here... always so relaxing... We had a perfect coffee break (very good!) and I craved what I think it&#39;s the best dish for this hot Sunday: THAÏ BEEF SALAD!!<br>soooooooooooo yummy<br>Don and his team are so helpful and it&#39;s just always such a pleasure being around here!!<br>Highly recommend this place.

Had lunch with a friend here the other day. The all-day brunch menu has good variety.  I had baked chicken, which was a huge thigh and drumstick, with corn, mashed potatoes and mushrooms. Serving size is generous, for 15 bucks. <br><br>I was happy with our pot of tea, made from leaves and thick enough for multiple refills.

text: really fast service and situated in a really nice area! got a well portioned bowl of the truffle pasta with an ice latte. overall a little bit expensive, but everything else was really good!

text: Had breakfast here with a friend today and the atmosphere was very chilled and relaxed. The brunch menu was quite extensive and the food was tasty, but nothing too special (I had the waffle with scrambled eggs and bacon). The coffee was actually really very good, but one of the disappointments here was the service. For a morning service, when we were one out of two tables, the waiters were rather slow and unorganised, serving the food without bringing any cutleries, etc. with it. <br>It&#39;s a pity the wifi here is quite poor. It would be a nice place to hangout with your laptop for coffee and breakfast in the morning.

Breko has been open for business at Holland Village for as long as I can remember. I remember flocking here during the weekends while I was still in junior college to while saturday mornings away - that&#39;s a full 8 years ago! Food wise, Breko is decent. Do not come expecting michelin star worthy cuisine and you will not be disappointed. It serves the usual bistro fare - burgers, cordon bleu, sausages, sweet cakes. Nothing to write home to your mother about really. <br><br>The good thing about Breko is its informal atmosphere. At night, it becomes really lively, with customers occupying the alfresco tables, chatting and people watching. Oh, yes. People watching. Breko is fantastic for that. It is located beside and opposite the bar area of Holland Village, and it&#39;s fun to just sit there and judge the assorted crowd that flocks to these bars.
