text: The pancake stack was good but astonishingly tiny. 4 small, thin pancakes (about 8cm diameter each) for $7.50++ ($8.83 nett). A few years ago it was $5.90++ ($6.94 nett) ... with free-flow coffee included!<br><br>It&#39;s tastier than McDonald&#39;s hotcakes, but Mc&#39;s is only $4.60 nett, bigger (3 larger hotcakes), and usually found in more convenient locations. All things considered, I&#39;d recommend McDonald&#39;s over this place&#39;s pancakes. (Eh but if you are ang moh you should know that Singapore McDonald&#39;s is not as crappy as in the US.)<br><br>This Breko take bus or MRT to Holland V aredi still must walk so far in.

I was sceptical of this place set at the back of Holland Village. I was pleasantly surprised with how fresh the food was here. I had the club sandwich which was very fresh. It was quite weird though because I got my fried egg on top of my closed sandwich. My partner had the baked salmon with lemon sauce. We felt the sauce should have been on the side. Overall decent food for a great price!

$12 for a decent selection of 2 bottled beers... what&#39;s not to love? I had Stella Artois while my friend had Coronas. It was a pretty cool evening so we seated right outside on the pavement next to what is now a walking street, so it&#39;s pretty great for people watching.<br><br>Had the Chicken Cordon Bleu, surprisingly big portion with 2 sides (I chose mashed potato and pasta salad)  and fairly decent tasting as well. My friend adores the tictactoe fries (waffle fries really) which are pretty crispy.<br><br>Decent spot it you&#39;re looking for an affordable night out!

text: I discovered Breko café a couple weeks after moving to Singers. While wandering around the Holland Village area, my stomach decided it was time to eat and fill it with a beer or two as well. While walking down a cute road with many food and drink options, I decided to stop into Breko because of their 1 for 1 beer special for $12. Two beers for $12 in Singapore is a steal, seeing as drinking in this town can be quite expensive. Their food menu was pretty impressive as well. I decided to grab their fish fillet and waffle fries while my wife decided on a pasta dish. Both came out well presented and tasted good. We ordered a couple rounds of Corona&#39;s as well which went great with our food. Overall, the food was good and the beer special was awesome. We definitely plan on hanging out here again when in the neighborhood.
food was ok... not that fantastic. Ambience was quite ok as well. food proces were really reasonable and the quality of food wasen&#39;t too shabby.

text: Breko is a casual café in the Holland Village row of restaurants. They have an all day breakfast, sandwiches, salads, main courses and desserts. It&#39;s a nice casual place to get a meal and is reasonably priced. <br><br>They have outdoor and indoor seating. <br><br>I usually get sandwiches when I come here. The vegetarian sandwich is actually pretty good and is filled with avocado and fresh greens. I haven&#39;t tried their all day breakfast but they have things like pancakes and eggs. Looks good on the menu so definitely something Ill come back and try.

Salted Carmel latte and cappacino', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Salted Carmel latte and cappacino'}]
text: This place has got to be my new favorite coffee joint! I find myself craving their lattes...pretty pathetic, huh? Makes me a bit sad, but the coffee is THAT bomb diggity! <br><br>6oz has taken over what used to be Coffee Bean and has done very well! The place looks livelier and the coffee tastes much better. Similar to most &#39;Western&#39; coffee joints (I use the term &#39;Western&#39; to feel more as one with the locals), 6oz sells cakes, sandwiches, chips, etc. During lunchtime, they have gourmet sandwiches, aka fancy carbs + fancy meat. I haven&#39;t tried the sandwiches just yet, but I might buy considering the lattes are roughly $5, and if I pay $7 more for the &#39;lunch combo,&#39; I get a sandwich. Still a bit pricey in my book, especially considering the healthier option of Happy Salad upstairs. <br><br>My tip? Eat lunch at Happy Salad and have coffee at 6oz. I vote for that salted carmel latte-yummy! <br> <br>Espressos come in 6 oz and coffee in either 8oz or 12oz.

Royals has been my go to for the many years that I&#39;ve lived in Siglap. Also, our office tends to order delivery from them (yes, they do deliver that delish mee siam and they do birthday cakes too!)<br><br>Their specialty of course is the Nyonya Mee Siam which has a thicker and less spicier gravy. Ingredients are always fresh when I&#39;ve been here. I would eat this for breakfast, lunch and dinner if I could! <br><br>The cakes are also heavenly - chocolate banana and mint chocolate are amazing.<br><br>The rest of the food in my honest opinion, is average. But the Mee siam keeps me coming back.

Home comforts - ice honey lemon hits the spot on a hot day', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Home comforts - ice honey lemon hits the spot on a hot day'}]
text: I am in love. With Mee Siam. From this place.<br><br>I wasn&#39;t able to stomach a lot of spicy food as a kid - but I&#39;d happily sweat buckets and down iced water just to go through a bowl of curry/laksa/bakchormee... so perhaps I was destined to eat this.<br><br>This isn&#39;t incredibly spicy by any means, so don&#39;t expect mala madness. It&#39;s just super rich, super flavourful gravy on top on springy bee hoon, with tau pok and a boiled egg.<br><br>Simple, tasty win. At $5.90 a bowl, it&#39;s certainly not expensive, and when you see that they&#39;ve got a few kinds of nasi lemak for you to try when you&#39;re not feeling the noodles that day, you know you&#39;ll be coming back.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/R6uOO4TkdOockpmUGTsqLA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/the-royals-cafe-singapore?reviewid=5X14I0vKTmpjHRkUAKbmmQ&select=R6uOO4TkdOockpmUGTsqLA', 'altText': 'Photo of The Royals Cafe - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: The Royals Cafe dishes up a mean Nonya mee siam. The gravy is thick and offers some heat, and its edge is rounded off by the lime half that can be drizzled over. Prawns are fresh and bouncy, and goes well when slurped up together with the bee hoon. <br><br>Service can be patchy when the cafe gets crowded, usually on weekend afternoons. Tables are situated uncomfortably close together in a bid to maximise customer base, but serves as an off putting element. Though the restaurant supposedly closes at 11pm, the kitchen ends service at 9pm, which is quite a bummer. <br><br>Go there for the mee siam. Everything else is rather pedestrian.

Offering a range of cakes, breads and assorted dishes, Royals Cafe is a simple cafe serving western and local food at a reasonable price. Open from 7.30 am to 11 pm, they serve a great Mee Siam in particular. The cakes are not fancy but simple and reasonably delicious. There are also decent club sandwiches and soups available as well. It is quite a good place for a simple, no-frills meal with possibly desserts after. I&#39;d recommend the mango cake or the mint chocolate. It&#39;ll be hard to resist looking at the selection of cakes.

text: Meh.... How can you mess up a soy latte, it&#39;s just espresso &amp; soy milk. ): <br>I went to other coffee shops during my time in Singapore but was gravely dissapointed each time. It&#39;s probably my fault bc I just don&#39;t know where the great ones are, but it was 7 AM &amp; I didn&#39;t want to take my chances with not-so-great coffee. But then I came to good reliable old stbx, &amp; it was a huge disappointment. My coffee was bland and watered down &amp; if there was any soy milk, I couldn&#39;t taste it whatsoever. <br>All in all, I don&#39;t know why this place has four stars. Service was whatever as well. The two girls were sitting in the front at one of the tables &amp; looked disappointed that customers were arriving.

This is a good Starbucks conveniently located near the Singapore Art Museum and the Bras Basah MRT station allowing for a quick cuppa on your commute or before a day of sightseeing. The service here was good and quick.

text: Was surprised to learn that this was a Korean joint but didn&#39;t make much difference to the food they served.<br><br>Came here specifically to try their coffee which was ok for a franchise - ranked similarly to that or Starbucks or Coffeebean. Nonetheless, I simply loved their Green Tea Latte or the Caramel Latte which might be a bit sweet for some but a great pick-me-up for me.<br><br>Used to be opened till 2am but it was recently revised to 12am.<br><br>Usually I would choose to sit at the extended siting area outside but beware of student campers who would be there all day and deprive you of a coveted seat.
Decent cafe located near Tanjong Pagar MRT station. If you are a Korean language learner a casual group meets here every few weeks to practice Korean over snacks and drinks

text: I&#39;ve seen a million Tom n Tom&#39;s in Seoul and I THINK I saw some in Sydney also.<br><br>I usually go to Kopi Alley next door for my morning tea/coffee and a bite as it&#39;s dirt cheap and pretty good, but this morning I decided to try Tom N Toms. Hey it&#39;s a Korean chain, did not know that but makes sense. They play k-pop in the background and this place is usually packed when I walk by with students hanging out or reading. It was totally empty on a Saturday morning.<br><br>I ordered a large Americano (gosh I miss brewed coffee...why is it non-existent in Asia/Australia??? Long Black? No thank you!) and a cinnamon pretzel. <br><br>I waited 10 minutes, TEN MINUTES, there were 2 workers and 1 of me waiting in the WHOLE place. Errrr. I don&#39;t get it.<br><br>I like the idea of this place and the fact that it&#39;s right downstairs from my place but man they gotta get their coffee and service right or they won&#39;t make it.

The Bingsoo (Korean shaved ice dessert) craze has hit Singapore and Tom N Toms offers one of the most authentic bingsoo in Singapore as their ingredients are shipped directly from Korea. The Green Tea Bingsoo was delicious and filled with red bean goodness. The only problem I had with this place was the lack of open table as many students were occupying more than one table to study.

Toms n Toms Coffee is a Korean franchise cafe in Singapore. I love to travel there for late night coffee hang out with friends. Their coffee sections are not as much as Starbucks or Coffee Bean, but the environment is definitely less noisier than most cafes out there.<br><br>It can be rather crowded at times, and because of its increasing popularity, there are more people checking out Toms N Toms. I love their free Wi-Fi and their pretzels! The price is rather reasonable, and I just can&#39;t resist bread, or anything to do with flour for that matter. <br><br>Students, you can consider Toms N Toms to mug instead of hogging the tables at McD and other cafes.
Not the best service in town - Slow and inattentive.<br><br>P.S This was for 2 people behind the counter and for 2 customers - relatively quiet shift.

text: Was just exploring Icon Village when I accidentally found this big space at the other end dedicated to this coffee place called Tom N Toms Coffee. Turns out that its a Korean franchise. The place has got seating inside and outside. Except outside is also air-conditioned within an enclosed space!<br><br>Was there on a saturday and it was really nice and quiet for a weekend. The best thing is that it opens til late. There were a few students studying here when I was there, it is quite the perfect place to study undisturbed! <br><br>Their specialty here is the pretzels and they looked irresistible in the menu pictures that I ordered a stuffed pepperoni pretzel. The ordering system is interesting to say the least. You get this electronic tag after you order at the counter and make your payment. You sit down and wait for your tag to light up and beep and then collect your food and drink from the counter. It&#39;s pretty troublesome to go to and fro if you&#39;re seated out in the enclosed space, you have to keep opening doors. But I suppose that&#39;s forgivable if the food and drinks are top notch. But it&#39;s really not. The coffee I had was uninspiring, for a store that calls itself a coffee place, they&#39;ve got a long way to go. The pretzel however was quite a delight - it was served hot with the cheese all gooey and melting and the dough was soft. The only other thing I remember was how pricey the piece of dough cost!<br><br>Final verdict: Great for studying! Though I don&#39;t think the store is an advocate of it.

text: I always get my bread from this bakery! They have a pillowy white bread loaves that&#39;s so so good. Like, I didn&#39;t know a loaf of white plain bread could taste so good! Too bad I couldn&#39;t rave about their coffee too - it wasn&#39;t as good :(

I&#39;ve been to this Dimbulah two days in a row this week and just from day to day, I have to say, it&#39;s been pretty inconsistent.<br><br>Yesterday&#39;s cappuccino? Luxurious foam so smooth and dense that I raised an eyebrow as I took my first sip. Today&#39;s? Flat foam that was nothing like yesterday&#39;s.<br><br>The bean quality is without doubt, and the coffee is good. The barista is practiced and smooth, and she&#39;s definitely efficient. I just wish she was a little more consistent with the foam.<br><br>I&#39;ll probably still buy my coffee here because it&#39;s the nearest coffee place to my bus stop not named Starbucks... but let&#39;s just say there isn&#39;t much loyalty, and if the weather weren&#39;t so hot, I&#39;d be walking to Jewel a lot more. <br><br>Oh, and another warning. I pick up a coffee for my colleague who&#39;s lactose intolerant. Apparently the soy milk here is (like most places) pretty bad. If you&#39;re a soy taker, the walk to Jewel is worth it.

text: Starbucks are Starbucks are Starbucks, right? And this one seemed to be no different. Efficient handling of hordes of traffic, loads of seating and power sources, clean premises, happy staff, all the usual. Except something was missing. <br><br>Let me explain - there&#39;s a certain feeling of comfort I get when walking into a Starbucks. The layout is so ambiguously inviting that I could be in their flagship shop, or Beijing or Rio or Dar Es Salam and after 20 minutes of smooth jazz and mediocre coffee, I&#39;d know no different. I know exactly what I&#39;m going to get, assurance that I&#39;ll have a comfortable place to sit, free wifi...  <br><br>But what the whaaa - this location didn&#39;t have wifi. Delfi Orchard does, Raffles City does, so what gives Starbucks Capital Tower?

You just got downgraded to one star (which I&#39;m not sure I have ever done in all my yelp years) because you NEVER get my order right.  ICED Vanilla latte, not hard, right?  Yesterday was a macchiato, iced, the time before that was hot.  They always spell my name wrong, but I&#39;ve give them that, and never, now matter how many times I tell them warm up my muffin.  Sorry Starbucks, I&#39;m out! (throws up peace sign)

Waffles with hazelnut and coconut ice cream. $14.50.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Waffles with hazelnut and coconut ice cream. $14.50.'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/-3GoIKV48dUzzLOSFGy8ag/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/rabbit-owl-depot-singapore?reviewid=k4lc3YSVj_7F8wPfOiW-iw&select=-3GoIKV48dUzzLOSFGy8ag', 'altText': 'Photo of Rabbit Owl Depot - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Kudos to Yelpers Melissa Y and Majeed F reviews, we managed to order correctly. <br><br>The original crispy waffle was REALLY GOOD! It was crispy and light so you would probably want to have it all for yourself instead of sharing it. It did not taste too heavy or filling either. A perfect snack. The maple syrup could be more but then again, the ice cream would sweeten it too.<br><br>The hazelnut and coconut ice cream were so delicious. The hazelnut was like eating rocher chocolate and the coconut had tiny bits of coconut pieces. My friend likened it to the coconut ice cream at Chatterbox in Mandarin Orchard Hotel of a few years ago (not as good now).<br><br>The hazelnut and coconut ice cream were from the premium range so there was an additional dollar to each scoop. <br><br>You could also help yourself to iced water from the cooler in a corner. A nice touch.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/mPVfMkgAbu-NkvuTfmQfNA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/rabbit-owl-depot-singapore?reviewid=6DNkT4JarpyxXYdTvaJbKg&select=mPVfMkgAbu-NkvuTfmQfNA', 'altText': 'Photo of Rabbit Owl Depot - Singapore, Singapore. berry cheese with chocolate waffle $10.50', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'berry cheese with chocolate waffle $10.50'}]
text: Located just across from Bugis+ is this small little ice cream cafe. Rabbit Owl Depot turns one this week and coincidentally, it was also my friend&#39;s birthday so we decided to celebrate it over there with a group of friends.<br>I loved their decor, it is such a cute and heart-warming feeling, walking into Rabbit Owl Depot. <br><br>They have a wide range of ice cream flavours. All were great! It was so hard trying to pick a flavour or two for our ice creams!<br>Somethings to note about ROD,they do not use any preservatives for their ice cream, and essential additives such as stabilizers are kept to a minimum! Which means, you are consuming &#34;natural&#34; ice cream!! Enjoy!!<br><br>Despite the cafe being small and only able to accomodate 20 pax, the owners were very friendly and allowed me to make a reservation for 7 pax. They even helped me put the cake in the fridge and only when we were done with the cake, that they started to make the waffles. How thoughtful!<br><br>1. Waffle with Chocolate Banana and Hazelnut Rocher $12.50<br>Moving straight to the waffles, first up was the chocolate banana and hazelnut rocher. I loved the chocolate banana, it was like BJs chunky monkey, just creamier! <br>Everyone was blown away at how crispy the waffles were! I&#39;m sure I&#39;m going to get alot of them requesting to bring them back here! The texture of the waffles were very brown on the outisde and yet not burnt. On the inside, the waffles were mostly hollow, so you probably can&#39;t get full from the waffles either. <br><br>2. Chocolate waffles with Berry Cheese $10.50<br>The chocolate waffles were slightly softer and fluffier than the original snowflake waffle. The chocolate waffles were sweet with chocolate chips in them. It was a nice combination with the berry cheese ice cream which wasn&#39;t too cheesey and had the right amount of berry flavour without it tasting sour! I think Rabbit Owl Depot, has got it&#39;s mixture spot on!<br><br>3. Waffle with Wake-me-up and Hunny Bunny  $13.50<br>As a coffee lover, I was looking forward to the wake-me-up but it tasted a tad too sweet for my liking. But nonetheless the hunny bunny was a favourite amongst the group too! It was like a honey flavoured ice cream with an intense smooth aftertaste!<br><br>4. Waffle with Sticky Salt Caramel and Cookie Jingle $13.50<br>The salted caramel wasn&#39;t as salty as you would expect, instead I tasted more of the caramel than the the salt. Together with the cookie jingle, which was my favourite. The salted caramel&#39;s saltiness was enhanced! For cookies and cream lovers, the cookie jingle is for you!<br><br>Crispy snowflake wafflesI am still amazed at how deliciously crispy and yet savoury these waffles were! They sprinkle icing sugar over it for a slight added sweetness but the sweet aroma of these buttermilk waffles are addictive!<br><br>Quite a reasonable spend for about 7 of us to have a hearty spread of ice cream and waffles!<br>Overall : The ice cream were rich, smooth and didn&#39;t melt quickly. The waffles were super crispy and you will be amazed by their snowflake waffles! Their prices are reasonable and they have a comfortable dining area too!

text: Ok let&#39;s start with the positives :<br>1. Nice ambience and good for chillaxing in any weather :)<br><br>2. Crispy waffles that come in 3 flavours : choc, cookiebutter and original. If u must try only one- go for the choc lol...but I am a choc lover so... :)<br><br>3. Good variety of flavours which are split into two categories: premium and usual ones. <br><br>Now...The not so great :<br>1. Pricey. I ordered 2 flavours - one premium one usual - with the triple waffles ( small pieces )which came up to $18. <br><br>2. Staff was ok and doing what he needed to do but.... made me not want to ask him for more flavours trials lol... U know what I mean.... If he had been a bit more accommodating, I would have ordered more premium flavours actually... Also when I asked if the original flavoured waffle came with syrup, he just stated that it is on the waffle...and there was just one other customer who was done paying up so he wasn&#39;t busy till he could not have just offered more syrup or a smile. Lol! I think good service makes customers come back for more since there are so many ice cream shops we can choose to go otherwise.

text: Diagonally opposite the intercontinental hotel, great bitter cacao and hazelnut ice cream. Perfect for a hot humid (normal) day in Singapore ;)<br><br>There is little that compares to the quenching power of well made flavorful ice cream to cool you down! This place is still one of the best in town.

text: Walked past this unassuming place and, quite typically, the mister with the keen eye took notice of it. Decided to give it a try and wow.<br><br>Let&#39;s start with the aesthetics - small cozy place with cute round tables scattered about. Love the &#34;themed&#34; furniture with the pipe details. I&#39;m so over that array of mismatched furniture thing that seems to be all the rage. It&#39;s sloppy! There are little owl/rabbit knick knacks around the cafe that I find adorable. Again, that running theme which just shows careful thought. <br><br>We shared a snowflake waffle with ice cream. Yum. Yknow how it is with &#34;the basics&#34;. Anyone can make cakes, pancakes, toast etc. But the true test is to have it sans any &#34;taste boosters&#34;. The waffle by itself is already tasty. Drizzled sparsely with icing sugar and syrup (overkill with the sweetness and it&#39;d have been MEH) and the ice cream... Mm. Also appreciate how the waffles are a little on the crisp side, just the way I like them.<br><br>I&#39;d say the star is the waffles, but hey, the coffee is pretty good too! The flat white would&#39;ve been one of the better ones we&#39;ve had if they were a liiiiiittle less generous with the milk.

text: Was here for the new product launch - Chai Latte. Ordered and tried the croffles with strawberry and melted butter. <br><br>It was very crispy toasted outside and the softness of the bread can be tasted in the inside. The strawberries slices I will tell you are the freshness I have ever tasted (ever for now).<br><br>Really a great place to have a afternoon break anyday.<br><br>Just that it is rather cramp for large crowds.<br><br>Definitely to come by again!

text: went there on a hungry afternoon and had an original snowflake waffle taken away. <br>I&#39;ve always loved waffles and this could be one of the best I&#39;ve ever had! And snowflake is quite exclusive. <br>Although the portion isn&#39;t big enough, I cannot demand too much for $6.5. I also read from other reviews that there are syrups available. Guess not for takeaways :(<br><br>Will definitely come again and try other stuff!<br><br>note that the place is a bit small and busy - only two small tables left when I went at 4:30pm on a weekday. the cute decorations do win some points back though.

text: Stumbled on the place around the corner from my dinner and was glad I did. The idea of a croffle was brand new to me and became an instant highlight. Buttery, sweet pastry, with custom sauces and toppings. So good, and not too sweet. Sitting area (view from inside)', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Sitting area (view from inside)'}]
text: I never knew Liho had a cafe place; always thought that they were a &#39;grab and go&#39; kiosk kinda business.<br><br>Anyway, we were craving bubble tea and wanted a place to sit down. Luckily, we chanced upon this after walking past Starbucks and were plesantly surprised to learn that this quaint set-up belongs to Liho!<br><br>Love, love, love their decor; it&#39;s so simple and classic. Luckily, again, for us, we dropped by just after the dinner hour and there wasn&#39;t much people in the cafe. They even had an elaborate set-up for tea-brewing!<br><br>We ordered the Honey Milk Tea with Pearl. We weren&#39;t asked for the sugar level because most Honey drinks are already sweetened naturally. However, my daughter took a few sips and found it too sweet. I tried and gosh it was sweet! I brought it back to the guy behind the counter (he looks like an ah beng but was so gentle and soft-spoken! Surprise!) and asked if he could add more ice as it was too sweet. Without a word, he proceeded to add more ice and even top up our tea! I was shocked! He then passed me the cup and said that he added more tea &#39;on the house&#39; to balance the flavour. This is what I call excellent pro-activeness and good service!<br><br>The only downside (that&#39;s why my review is 4 stars!) was that they still give plastic cups/straws even though customers opted to dine in. They should, perhaps, consider glass cups and steel straws/or no straw policy.

text: Popped by for desserts since I was in the vicinity of the cafe and was craving for sticky date pudding. This is one of my favourite cafes for desserts. I&#39;ve tried most of the desserts on the menu and would highly recommend the sticky date pudding and chocolate blackout cake for hardcore chocolate lovers. <br>There&#39;s many outlets for PS Cafe but my favourite is the one at Palais Renaissance. It&#39;s extremely cozy and the ambience is perfect for chilling. I would love to spend more time here but had to leave for a movie date.<br>Would have given 5 stars if not for the slightly tardy service today.

text: This is one of my favorite places in Singapore. They have several locations. I&#39;ve been to this one and the one on Dempsey Road. Both are equally good. It is very consistent and they make a mean burger for those who enjoy burgers.<br>This spot is very low key and on the smaller side, but you have the option of sitting indoor or out. We picked indoor because my BF doesn&#39;t do well in the heat. We were seated immediately even though we had not reservation. It was around 1h30 in the afternoon.<br>We had Bloody Mary&#39;s to start and even though they were not as flavorful as we are used to, they were still very good. They used fresh tomato juice which gave a completely different flavor profile. It comes with a celery, cucumber and carrot stick and a green olive.<br>My BF had the PS. BURGER (wagyu &amp; us chuck patty, vintage cheddar,<br>wilted spinach, crispy smoked bacon, tomato &amp; crispy onions, toasted sesame bun &amp; chunky fries). He asked for no mayo or BBQ sauce and switched from the Chunky Fries to the Truffle Fries and holy cow were they good! You get a good amount of them too. It&#39;s kind of a signature dish for them.<br>I had the Caesar Salad with Poached Egg, Smoked Bacon, Baby Cos, Baked Croutons, Parmesan. I asked for dressing on the side and regretted it. It was fresh and light, but I think it would have been better with the dressing incorporated. The egg was somewhere between soft and hard, but very good.<br>For dessert, his eyes had caught on a Marshmallow Brownie Pie which not only ginormous, but delicious! It was so big and so rich he couldn&#39;t finish it!<br>Overall a great experience!

text: I never heard of PS Cafe until last week. My sister told me she and my niece went to PS Cafe at Paragon mall for breakfast and that breakfast cost her over $100. I like the two of them must have eaten a lot, lol!!<br><br>After my lunch at Sanpoutei today, I was taken to PS Cafe at Palais Renaissance. I walked by a display of cakes. They are not necessary the kind of cakes I like but still...<br><br>FOOD 3/5<br>I suggested we both shared the Flourless Orange Cake with Orange butterscotch sauce. It would be too much for me to polish that whole cake. The cake came with a scoop of vanilla ice cream. It was alright. Nothing to write home about. The Oreo milkshake was good, but is it even possible to mess up a milk shake?<br><br>AMBIENCE 3/5<br>My first impression of this café? There are so many steps in this place. It is crazy!! I should put a PSA here. This place is not wheelchair friendly. It is not friendly to anyone who has mobility issue. It was rather crowded when we entered the café. <br><br>It was a lovely place with lots of greenery. I wanted to love the place but.. the back of leather couch was leaning on the back of another couch sat by another patron. It was not the heaviest chair, so I was extra careful making sure my couch remained in place and not disturb the patron behind me. I was not comfortable throughout my dessert session. The patrons behind me were not as considerate as I hoped to be. <br><br>SERVICE 4/5<br>I took off a star since it was so hard to holler down a staff to take our order. Other than that, the staffs were nice and polite. <br><br>Would I return to this PS Café for anything? I doubt it. I have taken a good look at the menu, no wonder my sis spent over $100 for breakfast. The price is on the high end (think 5 star hotel pricing)and I am not sure if the food is good enough for that kind of  pricing. I may try it out one of these days. Then again, there are way too many places for me to visit. Maybe just one day...

text: This has got to be one of the best spots to chill out all afternoon. It&#39;s in the heart of Orchard but the green surrounding makes the place cosy but still posh. <br>Great to hang out with your girls or Sunday brunch. <br>Like any places, when it gets busy you&#39;ll be spending a lot of time trying to get the waiters attention. <br>Food is 5/5 always.

What ps cafe does well = portion sizes (think american) and ambiance. What it doesn&#39;t do well = value for money and exceptional taste. <br><br>I came here with a group of 10 and tried the Mushroom Wellington, famous truffle fries, and the Banana Mango Crumble dessert. I had heard so much about the truffle fries that I expected them to blow my mind away. They were decent but nothing exceptional.  This is how I felt about everything I agree at ps cafe.<br><br>Wouldn&#39;t come back here intentionally, but will settle if another group event ends up here. I like that they take reservations

text: I love everything about this place! Food is great, ambiance amazing and service is good (for Singapore standard...). Keep some space for their amazing cake selection!

PS Cafe is always one of the few cafe choice if I planning a brunch or dinner gathering with my friends.<br><br>Love the ambience and also the food, a must try is the Moroccan Lamb, as someone who don&#39;t eat lamb but this main is the only lamb dish I eat. Not to forget the chili crab cake as well.<br><br>Remember to save some space for their cake as well.<br><br>If on a weekend and you just want to get away from the crazy crowd at orchard and have a place to hang out with your friend this is really a good choice.
If one is looking for relatively inexpensive meal with good food, this is it.  Wide variety of choices and good deserts as well. Quality varies on locations.

text: This is such a beautiful space to spend any time of day in - it&#39;s definitely &#34;that kind of place&#34;. Opulent, secluded, sexy and alluring...but I just wish that the main meals were worth forking out big dollars for. Sadly, it&#39;s a case of - you&#39;re largely paying for the killer ambiance.<br><br>The Green Goddess Pasta ($26.00) was painfully under seasoned - it&#39;s a rather unique take on the traditional pesto sauce but not a dish that I would recommend anybody ordering. Even their famous Truffle Fries ($12.00) were awful today; cold, even before they hit the table and without the slightest hint of truffle, or salt for that matter.<br><br>The cocktails were the redeeming factor of our visit, I highly recommend trying the White Bouquet Sangria ($18.00) or the Green Apple Mojito ($16.00)<br><br>After this experience, I&#39;d say that PS. Ann Siang Hill or PS. Petit in Tiong Bahru are definitely better options. If you can stomach the subpar food, all PS outlets have  a vibe and decor that trumps many other cafes and restaurants. But when it comes to Palais, like I said - you&#39;d be better off sticking to late night drinks and desserts.

I had a salad and truffle fries here, and I must say their truffle fries are one of the best I&#39;ve had in Singapore for the price and portion. I&#39;m a huge fan of truffle fries and I order it almost every single time I end up in a restaurant with truffle fries on the menu. Seriously give the truffle fries here a try. <br><br>I had the P.S. House salad, and added the rosemary-honey dijon chicken. I think this was one of maybe like 3 times in my life I&#39;ve ever felt satisfied after eating a salad without craving a burger or something. The salad was well balanced and I love the dressing. The chicken was very well seasoned and surprisingly tender.<br><br>The food was excellent, but I must mention that the service was not fantastic. We put our names down on their iPad checkin system, but we waited for half an hour without being seated even though the place had a couple of empty tables. We went up there and asked a server how long more we would have to wait (we were the only customers waiting), and she said another half an hour in a pretty flippant manner and walked away. We got pretty confused then, since we were told that the wait was half an hour pretty much half an hour earlier, and now we&#39;re supposed to wait another half an hour? When she came back we told her our name was in the system, and only then she led us to a free table.<br><br>My friend ordered the same salad as I did, and told them to leave out the rocket. The waiter noted that down and said it was no problem. When the salad came surprise surprise it came chock full of rocket leaves. We called the waiter back and he said the kitchen premixes the salad, so they couldn&#39;t take it out. Well before I get started on a kitchen that premixes a $25 salad, if you can&#39;t take out the rocket at least let us know before you serve it and ask if we&#39;re still ok with having it.<br><br>I only took away 1 star because the food is good although it is pricey, but I really hope the service improves.

Perfect service, perfect portion size, perfect food. <br><br>YES.<br><br>I had the Portobello burger, and it was juicy and cheesy and sinful and... I pretty much wrecked my image by grabbing it in both hands and chomping down like a food starved lunatic. Unrepentant. That&#39;s the only way to really enjoy a burger in my opinion.<br><br>The truffle fries were a work of art.<br><br>Deducting 1 star because you can&#39;t possibly have ONE female bathroom and expect that to work. Nope.

text: Nice cosy environment. Service was attentive.  Don&#39;t kick a fuss when u ask for warm water only.  A unanimous 4 of 5 from my family of 3.  The miso Cod fish was done beautifully.  Son had the penne also done al dente.  I had a tomato soup and sandwich combo also was good enough for back to office lunch.  Coffee was served nice and hot.  One thing though it looks like a place for gather of the expat tai tai :).

text: The food isn&#39;t so cheap but the quality and quantity is huge. The truffle fries are nice and the dessert is rich although too rich for my tastes. I didn&#39;t try any main course. Venue is very classy.

Everyone had been raving about this restaurant so eating here was a no-brainer. It&#39;s conveniently located in Palais Renaissance so I stopped by after a haircut (there are several salon&#39;s here that are all excellent by the way), hoping for a quick bite. In short, the food was fantastic, but the service was terrible.<br><br>I have two pet peeves when dining out. My first has to be the impatient server. You know the kind: talking to you while not talking to you, looking boredly around the room while in conversation with you. This was the first impression we had as the server took our orders.<br><br>We stopped here for a quick bite with the intention of the meal being, well, &#39;quick.&#39; It was anything but. After we were seated and our orders taken, we were virtually ignored for an hour or two. Not just us, but the entire section where we were seated. A little odd, especially since it was barely even half full, and there were always at least five servers standing at the entrance talking to each other. And every time we would try to hail a waiter, it would take several minutes, despite there being no other tables being served.<br><br>My second pet peeve has to be specific inconsistent attention. What I mean by this is when you are virtually ignored for your entire meal, only to have a server on winged feet when paying for the check. Unfortunately, this was again what happened during our visit to this restaurant. As soon as I asked for the bill, the server speedily appeared, and remained hovering until it was paid.<br><br>To be fair though, the food was excellent. The burger had just the right amount of juices flowing with each bite, and every plate was picked clean. The smoothie I ordered tasted a little bland, but maybe I was just regretting not ordering the milkshake.<br><br>As we walked out, my girlfriend mentioned that the other branch she had visited of the same chain had much better service. Or maybe just service in general, especially considering the one here was virtually nonexistent. With that in mind, I would gladly recommend this chain, just not this particular location. And after skimming through some of the other reviews, one easily can find many examples of bad service and questionable management.<br><br>Good food, overall, but when you&#39;re paying high prices for such bad service, why bother? Especially when you really are spoiled for choice in the food heaven that is Singapore.
We booked for a table to Brunch and waited for 10 Minutes at The Check-In Desk.<br>Nobody there.<br>Goodbye PS Café, we dislike.

text: Beautiful interior, good food and service, and lots of dessert options - what else could you ask for in a good brunch spot?<br><br>I&#39;ve been to a few P.S. Cafe branches and this is certainly one of the most elegant outlets.  There is a lot of natural light, high windows, and bountiful bouquets at the entrance and in the restrooms.  While I wish we could have made reservations for brunch (for some reason, the person on the phone said I couldn&#39;t make lunch reservations), we didn&#39;t wait more than 15 minutes on Saturday for a group of 6 people.<br><br>The food:<br>Truffle fries = french fries + parmesan cheese + truffle oil<br>This is possibly my favorite item here and certainly one we get for the table every time. There is a great truffle flavor with a nice savory bite and bits of parmesan cheese.<br>Otherwise, there is a wide range of brunch and lunch options here.  I&#39;ve had everything from the large burger with egg and steak cut fries to the &#34;leftovers&#34; lasagne with tons of vegetables, basil pesto and mozzarella (the vegetables are mildly overdone).  The sandwiches, including the turkey and brie sandwich with cranberry sauce, are savory and have interesting and complimentary flavors.<br><br>I ALWAYS want to have dessert here because the desserts are beautifully displayed by the entrance.  I may not manage to save enough room for dessert, but I have enjoyed them when I did plan ahead.  The apple galette is light and mildly sweet and the profiteroles have a nice chocolate sauce.  I really like the toffee sauce on the sticky date pudding, though I have found the dates to be a little overwhelming at times.<br><br>I don&#39;t hesitate to come here, except that it gets pricey.  Entrees are in the 20s while desserts hover somewhere in the teens.  Expect to pay up when you&#39;re here, but also expect good food in a lovely setting.

text: I love everything about this place! Food is great, ambiance amazing and service is good (for Singapore standard...). Keep some space for their amazing cake selection!

Without a doubt, PS Cafe at Palais Renaissance is my favorite of the other locations. It&#39;s easy to get to in Orchard yet it is buried deep enough in a quiet shopping mall. I&#39;ve been here a couple of times during dinner when it gets really crowded but other times I&#39;ve never had to wait to be seated in the afternoons.<br><br>The owners of PS Cafe branched out from fashion and that elegance has translated into the interior decor of the restaurant. Dark wood interiors that incorporate big floral arrangements added to a semi-open kitchen and a row of delightfully tempting cakes housed in glass covers, you get the idea.<br><br>I&#39;m usually very predictable with my orders at PS Cafe and that is because I love the Portobello Mushroom Soup, Caesar Salad and Truffle Shoestring Fries. I&#39;m gladly boring for such good food.

text: I struggle to review this restaurant because as much as i like the ambience, the food is overrated and over-priced. <br>Basically, you&#39;re paying an exorbitant price for a serene, pretty setting. <br>The waitstaff is mediocre; they need to be better-trained. <br>Communications seems to be an issue here. <br><br>Overall, a great option to hang out with your GFs for a few hours for brunch, coffee or afternoon break.

One of my favourite brunch places in Singapore. Beautiful and classy decor, accessible location and delicious food. There is not much else a girl could ask for.<br><br>PS big bacon with eggs, eggs benedict and PS breakfast stack are my usual orders. And they never fail to satisfy my brunch cravings. Then of course, their famous truffle shoestring fries. YUMS. It will be polished up within minutes. So be prepared to order more than 1 plate if you are with other truffle fries monsters!<br><br>The possible downside is that you would probably have to wait for a table especially in the weekends. But hey, queuing is our national sport. So it is fine to embrace it once in awhile=)

Sophisticated interior, high ceiling and furniture that makes me feel like I&#39;m in New York/Paris/London.<br><br>I love their chicken in a basket (deep fried, really unhealthy but okay to indulge once in a while), miso cod, caesar salad with grilled rosemary dijon chicken and carrot cake with cream cheese. <br><br>Food is mostly decent, on the pricey side, but the atmosphere is always wonderful. Favourite catch-up place.
If one is looking for relatively inexpensive meal with good food, this is it.  Wide variety of choices and good deserts as well. Quality varies on locations.

text: Popped in for a quick lunch today. Absolutely love the interior and vibe of this place! Somewhat retro, yet very classy and stylish... I decided to check out their croq-monsieur and unfortunately have to agree with most reviewers; it wasn&#39;t that good... Of course there&#39;s always a risk in ordering that &#34;dish&#34; outside of Paris, but let&#39;s just say that the setting raised my expectations... Anyways, definitely a place to check out again to taste and enjoy the atmosphere, but maybe just grab a coffee iso a meal...

text: As 3 peter a good menu. The food didn&#39;t let down either. Service was decent. The greatest thing about this place, though,it&#39;s the ambiance.  It looks like a converted warehouse of sorts but can&#39;t be. I liked it.

There are several PS cafe outlets but the one at Palais Renaissance remains my favorite. It&#39;s the perfect place to hang out after a day of shopping and it&#39;s quiet (Harding is really noisy) and airy (unlike the claustrophobic Paragon and A.S.H outlets). There&#39;s a choice of outdoor seating which is a good option if the weather is not overly humid. It looks good and smells good. Boy do i love the lilies in the toilet.<br><br>The food at PS is not fantastic though the portions are huge. I like the crab tart (which is only served at Palais). Their quiche (varies from day to day) is a hit and miss-  dry tart and the tart to filling ratio isn&#39;t perfect (too much of the former). Their brunch menu is also rather forgettable. <br><br>So why do i keep going back? For the desserts of course! Their cakes are quite consistent and so far they haven&#39;t failed me when i have a sweet craving. I love the steamed apple pudding with butterscotch sauce and real vanilla ice cream. Tender juicy caramelized apple chunks on top of a warm brown sponge that soaks up that butterscotch sauce and neutralized with a fragrant vanilla ice cream- it&#39;s an explosion of taste and texture. This is only available at Palais as well (another reason to go there!). I don&#39;t like their sticky date pudding at Harding, too much of the date skin which really scratches the throat. Dates are also too sweet for my liking.

text: Ps Café in Palais Renaissance has a really sophisticated, yet chilled back ambience. It&#39;s a nice place to go to for a quiet and intimate dinner, and also a lazy brunch or lunch. <br><br>Expect the similar food to the other PS outlets, although the menu tends to vary a bit in the different locations. Prices are a bit steep here, and again try the cakes which a great. My favorite is the chocolate blackout cake. Its amazing but definitely one to share as its huge! Also try the key lime pie and flourless orange cake.

I love this cafe for its pretty interior that exudes class and sophistication with a slightly rustic twinge. I have tried a couple of their main meals there and would not deem this as a place of fantastic food. They do hearty portions but the taste and quality can be better. The one thing that I am a great fan of is their seared tuna salad. I love how japanese flavours are incorporated into this salad with the wasabi vinaigrette. The fish was fresh and well seared and the whole combination of ingredients made it tasty, fresh and light. I tried their chocolate cake once but felt that it was pretty run-of-the-mill and not worth its expensive price tag.<br><br>I would not actually visit PS Cafe for their food, but I would come back for a nice chilled afternoon for a cup of coffee to enjoy the wonderful ambience.

text: The good news is that the MRT drops you right off here.  I&#39;ve visited here during both the day and night.  The pretty lights are worth seeing at night. The outdoor vendors are open from late morning to early evening. There&#39;s always a trend. This time the trend is having your name carved on a good luck stone. Nice. <br><br>There are plenty of places to eat outdoors, if you enjoy eating in the 90 degree, high humidity weather, which it appears many people do. <br><br>There are beautifully painted murals down various side streets.

text: This is probably the largest hawker center around and a bit overwhelming.  There were so many selections and some stalls sell very similar things. There are a few with long lines (especially the Hong Long style roasted meats one).  <br><br>I came here with a mission to find the stall with clay pots and could not find it despite walking all over repeatedly. I settled for something else after 20 mins of circling.  They really ought to put a directory together or put it online in a website with a map. <br><br>I would recommend this place for any meal as you can surely can find something you like or want.

text: This food court is home to the famous Michelin-rated Hawker Chan, which serves the soy sauce chicken rice. There&#39;s also a host of other hawkers that have your usual food court selections. This is a very mainstream food court in SG- right next door to Buddha Tooth Relic Temple And Museum. Also, Jia Ji Mei Shi has good chee cheong fan- this is rice noodles. <br><br>Downstairs is all shops to buy your typical souvenirs- trinkets, knick knacks, cheap clothes (if you&#39;re Chinese, maybe you know of the Chinese granny clothes). You can also buy a red ornament to hang below your car&#39;s rearview mirror so that everyone who walks by your car will know that you&#39;re Asian. <br><br>If you have to use the restroom, you have to pay 10 cent toll like the old Singapore days. There&#39;s an aunty that collects at the front of the restroom. Anyways, this food court is pretty awesome. It&#39;s a great area to explore for tastes and sights.

text: Mysterious<br>Hot<br>Humid<br>Funky<br>Huge!!!!!!<br><br>walk in, downstairs in the large circular warehouse-y feeling place, cement everywhere: clothes and flea type articles for sale. Go all the way to the top, and the stalls are plentiful ! Go to one for the best popia, another for duck, another for Hainan chicken, and yet another for kaya ( coconut jam) toast.<br><br>It&#39;s def a trip coming here, not even quite sure how to get in. Not enough light, not enough water....benches everywhere. Buk kut teh, I know I went to the top stall : longest queue ( no brained).<br><br>Amazing amazing food all over Singapore.

text: After a day at Universal Studio, I wasn&#39;t ready to turn in early. We got back to the hotel around 8pm and I ventured out after I freshened up a bit. I was hungry so I scoped what is around and landed here. <br><br>A lady approached me and lured me into ordering from her food stand. I was actually looking to order my first bowl of soup but the curry rice won me over. For under $5 SGD, I got a plate packed full of carbohydrates, proteins, and fat. Though the curry was a bit watery but it had some heat and was quite delicious. The fried pork chop was tough as a rock but the over-easy egg took this dish to another level. I love eggs on everything! The fried chicken was juicy. The lady asked if I wanted fish, I thanked her but declined but she still threw some in... =/ I did not eat it because it looked slimy. It was steamed. <br><br>I enjoyed it. Her smile and talkative nature was definitely unique compared to the other folks working behind the counter. Nothing more comforting than a plate of curry rice. Oh my... I wish I was back in Singapore.

text: My first impression when coming to this particular hawker center was that it was extremely overwhelming and big. There were over 200 food stalls to choose from here. It was daunting to find what we wanted to eat. When we found a stall we liked a lot, we made a note of its exact location on GoogleMaps so we didn&#39;t have to find it again next time. Thankfully, one of these food stalls was quite popular and traceable on GoogleMaps (Lian He Ben Ji Claypot). <br><br>That being said, the food was pretty amazing here. The claypot rice took the longest time to come to us, since the stall made it as we ordered it. It was probably an hour before we were able to eat it. As we waited for the claypot rice, we ate various other items like their laksa, satay, and charkway teow (stir fried beef noodles). All were good. But, the standout was that laksa! Man oh man was that the creamiest laksa I&#39;ve ever had in my life. The broth looked more like a cream sauce with the huge amount of shrimp roe they placed in. The noodles had great texture, and close to spaghetti. It was perfect for all that creamy soup to coat around it. Every bite was heaven. Great shrimp, coconut, and lemongrass flavors coming through. It was quite possibly my favorite dish at this hawker center, and in Singapore overall. The satay was good, but it wasn&#39;t as aromatic as the satay at Satay by the Bay. I still enjoyed eating it while I gulped down my bottle of ice cold Coke Zero (it was so freaking hot, and there&#39;s no AC at all). The charkway teow had some great wok hey (aka flavor from the heat of the wok). But, I wished the noodles were bouncier and held their shape. They were just kind of soggy. <br><br>Finally, our claypot rice arrived, and they were huge. The stall didn&#39;t understand my brother, and they made double the order of claypot rice for us. Safe to say we were stuffed by the end of this dinner. Too much food! But, the claypot rice was amazing. From the rice, to the Chinese sausages, to the salted fish, to the chicken, it was all fragrant and delicious. Definitely pour that dark soy sauce all over this claypot rice and mix all the ingredients well. What&#39;s best is to combine some crispy rice that&#39;s created from the bottom of the claypot with the soft rice. It was yummy. <br><br>Definitely come here when you have a specific goal about what to eat. Be patient as well, since navigating this massive center can be exhausting. Please get some cold drinks as this place doesn&#39;t have AC, and you will wither way from the heat and humidity. You could go to the mall and get food in the comforts of AC. But, you can bear the heat and have some really delicious (and definitely more affordable food) at this Hawker Center. Come check his spot out.

text: After visiting a few hawker centers, this one is definitely one of my favorites. Conveniently located in Chinatown, this is a great place to stop by for a bite to eat after you&#39;re done with souvenir shopping / exploration in Chinatown. For the food, simply go to the second floor, and bam! You&#39;ll be greeted with food stalls upon food stalls and the delicious smell of various food wafting around.<br><br>As a tourist, I was pretty overwhelmed at what to eat and where to start. My suggestion to anyone who hasn&#39;t been to a hawker center before is to walk around first and observe the food prior to just jumping to a stall and ordering right away. Since the place was quite big, it did take some time for my friends and me to explore the different food stalls and making mental notes at which ones we wanted to try. Best plan when traveling with a group of people is to pick a general eating spot, split up, get whatever food you desire, and regroup at the eating area. The eating area itself is scattered around with tables and chairs. <br><br>For the food stalls, there was a huge variety that ranged from only fresh fruit smoothies / drinks to various cuisines like Chinese, Indian, Singaporean, Indonesian and etc. If you need food suggestions, simply go line up for food stalls that have huge lines. Most likely, these food stalls are either popular with locals/tourists, or the food is pretty cheap and tasty. I used this tactic and ended up with delicious food that I at first, had no idea what I was eating. <br><br>For food here, I highly recommend lining up for the Food Street Fried Kway Teow Mee. Simply put, it&#39;s noodles mixed with a spicy like sauce, seafood like taste and such. Not sure what else goes into it, but it is one tasty dish!! To find this stall, look for a long line (or at my picture). The wait is definitely worth it and it&#39;s cool to see the chef in action on making your meal. As for drinks, pretty much most of the drinks stalls have similar prices (price average around $1-3). As for another random dish I tried, the green bean rice dumping at the Jia Ji Mei Shi food stall was amazingly good. With its sticky rice texture on the outside, and the green bean taste mixed in with the meat and rice......man, this was so yummy and at the same, mad filling on the tummy. If you do order this dish, I highly recommend getting the sweet and spicy chili sauce with it. So good. <br><br>Overall, prices for most food stalls is pretty cheap (with a few exceptions on higher end seafood dishes) and you do get the option of picking your portion sizes that range from small to large. I spent roughly $5 that landed me 2 food items + 2 drinks and that alone made me go into a food coma. Make sure you bring cash since most places don&#39;t take credit cards.<br><br>After eating, I recommend checking out the first floor where it&#39;s like a mini clothing market that sells various clothes and small trinkets :)

Singapore heritage traditional prawn noodle with pork rib soup', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Singapore heritage traditional prawn noodle with pork rib soup'}]
text: During my trip to Singapore, besides trying the chicken rice, I have try something new and tasty, also regarded as heritage traditional food in Singapore called Prawn noodle. This store name is HEY ME! which caught my eyes as Prawn noodle in Chinese is called Hae Mee :) The soup itself is prawny and full of flavor without MSG, the prawn is fresh and crunchy, I added a pork rib for only $1 which the meat is so tender and fell off the bone. Forget about the long queues, HEY ME! is a must try when you in Singapore in Chinatown. 2nd floor at the Chinatown complex market.

text: Chinatown complex market and food centre. <br>#02-167. Don &amp; Udon<br>$5.50 for Gyu Niku Don. <br>Just a nice name, slightly overpriced and less quantity (they serve kids meals size) as main meals. Taste so so. Do not recommend as other Gyu Don elsewhere taste better and slightly more quantity to serve as lunch or dinner.

Chinatown Complex: grungy, unbearably hot, dirt cheap...and yet awesome food. <br><br>This is definitely a local&#39;s style food court upstairs in a sprawling ugly concrete building above a  market in Chinatown.  We went for breakfast a couple times since we were staying across the street and they have pretty much everything you could want.  Mainly there for Bedok chee kueh (google &#34;chee kueh&#34;, and then go try some) and it didn&#39;t disappoint. Look for the stall right by the escalators to the left.   <br><br>We also ran into an enthusiastic local, who told us the soy sauce chicken stall here is actually better than the Michelin starred one across the street, which was a nice little tip.  Satay available later on in the day, but the famous Tian Tian fish porridge stall way in the back is open early.  And popiah.  So much goodness in one place!  There&#39;s even a craft beer stall (this place is actually becoming hipsterfied?).

text: One of the oldest .. like all eateries in SG it gets real busy during peak times. Especially now that one of the stalls that&#39;s been there donkeys years won a michelin star.. being non singas I just love hawker centre food.. to all non locals... follow the pack. If u see a line it generally is pretty darn good!! tonight I ventured here in search of the Michelin star Soya Chicken rice... But was too late.. all finito before 5pm already! was on my own and scouted slot of things I wanted to try due to noticeable local popularity.... I ate ... <br><br>FUKIEN MEIN ... heard some loud crazy wok action and smelt the &#34;鑊氣&#34; ! Turned the corner and noticed a line forming decided to get into the action.. had this already at Lau pasat but this one was better. The noodles and gravy had that extra flavour due to more of the 鑊氣. <br><br>I was actually content BUT saw another line so I mosied up behind an uncle ... and raised my victory fingers when asked how many cus my mouth was drawing a long sip if the sour sop!! <br><br>2 X POPIAH... I would have to say one of the best so far... in SG if u want to ward off vampires eat their popiahs.. man they use a lot of garlic. But at this stall it was the right amount of everything. sauce garlic and the crunchy thingy bob<br><br>Soursop.. um watered down but still decent for $2<br><br>Chicken rice.. the line was getting crazy luckily I joined 5 min early otherwise would be waiting around corner. Again hmmmm chicken was good but rice was a let down.. <br><br>had to waddle out..

text: There was so much variety and they were cheap! Get something small from different stalls to try! I loved all the drinks/juices that I had got. Kumquat was my favorite! <br><br>This plate of food was only $7 and two people couldn&#39;t even finish!

One of the many hawker centers in SG. This one is right smack in the heart of Chinatown. Dining area upstairs and shopping downstairs. Plenty of stalls to choose from depends on your cravings.<br>Some has longer queue than the rest. Personally it&#39;s all the same for me.

text: It&#39;s not pretty, but it&#39;s very real. Especially the dining area. Very bottom floor is the wet market while the shops are street level, and hawker stalls are upper level. I&#39;m reviewing the hawker stalls. If you&#39;ve got friends who all have different tastes, this might be a good option. Everyone can buy what they went then regroup at the table.<br><br>Lots and lots of stalls mainly catering to the older demographic, which means some of these stalls have been around for a long time and are tried and true. Open air but densely packed (with both the hot stalls and people) so it can get really muggy and uncomfortable during peak hours. Just expect to sweat. Also, there are toilets somewhere in the middle, and I think it&#39;s ten cents for entry.<br><br>It&#39;s impossible to give an average rating of the food since there are so many stalls, which should ideally be individually rated, but overall, prices are very reasonable. Some stalls only open in the afternoon, so if you&#39;re coming for a particular place make sure you know what time they open (e.g., claypot place only opens after 3pm/4pm). My favorite is one of the herbal soup places. But I say go around and try what you want, don&#39;t necessarily join a queue just because you think if there&#39;s a line it must be good.<br><br>The wet market is worth checking out if you want to buy some fruits to eat back in your lodging. Prices for tropical fruits are way less than what you&#39;d pay in your home country. And if you ask, the vendor will cut off the extra twigs for you after weighing so you have less to carry and less to throw away back at the hotel.

This is great food court/hawker complex in Chinatown. It is a couple blocks away from the Chinatown metro stop but you will pass through active parts of Chinatown while traveling towards this food court. <br>Inside you will find a vast array of food stalls selling all sorts of traditional dishes that Singapore is known for. <br><br>Across from the food court you will see the famous &#34;Michelin star soya sauce chicken and rice&#34; restaurant. This restaurant is operates a standing restaurant and their original food stall is inside the Chinatown complex. The food stall inside the complex is half the price!  The chicken and rice is tender and delicious and a safe bet if you are warming up to eating at hawker stalls. <br>There are often lines so if you are set on this stall you may want to come during interim hours.<br><br>Many options to choose from that are affordable, authentic, and delicious.

text: Maybe I came on a wrong day... A lot of the stalls were closed during my late afternoon visit.<br><br>I found the set up a little confusing as one have to go around corners to get to certain areas and the alley ways are narrow with barely enough space to walk around.<br><br>I won&#39;t make a special trip just to come here for food but if you are in the area, not a bad place to just come and chill. At least one can get a ice cold beer from The Good Beer Company to go with all these street food!

I was super lucky to stay here for a full week and I loved every minute of it.  It&#39;s a lot larger than I thought and crosses over multiple streets so be sure to explore all of it.  More near outram station, they have a wet market on the bottom of the hawker station with food stalls upstairs.   Over in the People&#39;s Court side in the actual building with shops, there&#39;s a bunch of foot reflexology/foot massage places that charge about $18 SIN for about 45 mins.  That&#39;s on the second floor.  You&#39;re welcome.  The only reason this gets 4 and not a 5 is that this place can be pretty dirty.  Especially in the morning, after a night of happy customers eating and drinking.

text: Good amount of food options (like really tons of food options) and lots of seating. It&#39;s easy to find (only a few steps away from the MRT). There&#39;s also lots of variety. There are essential Singaporean foods like bee hoon and also Cantonese foods like chopped meat. I would definitely come back.

text: Tons of variety of food stalls, it&#39;s hard to pick one, but pick we did and had some duck and some other things that I know not what they were.  Delicious, way too many pigeons roaming about for me to be comfortable. There was also a lovely red dragon prowling round and a man with a drum.<br><br>Definitely a must see.

As a local who&#39;s been to many, many, many hawker centers, Chinatown is a pretty good one I would visit if I were around the area (and hungry lol), but probably would not make a dedicated trip just to visit (unless I&#39;m bringing friends who&#39;re visiting!), mostly because they don&#39;t have the Best of any of my fave hawker dishes. <br><br>It&#39;s located above the market and close to both Chinatown &amp; Outram Park MRT stations. The tables are color coded according to which area they&#39;re in - makes it much easier if you&#39;re trying to find a friend. <br><br>Everyone (or most people) would know about the newly minted Michelin newbie Hong Kong Soy Sauce Chicken, and if you don&#39;t you&#39;d likely see the line snaking across three rows of stores (estimated wait now: 2 hours at lunch time). Other fave picks: <br><br>1) An Ji - well known for its zichar dishes - the wait may be long but worth it! I particularly liked their fish sliced noodles soup with incredibly thick and fragrant soup (without tasting too milky). The beef noodles with gravy had wok hei and I loved the thick sauce ladled over it. <br><br>2) Zhong Guo La Mian Xiao Long Bao - check out the separate Yelp listing. Solid and affordable Xiaolongbaos at $5.50 for 10. Not sure if a better deal for xlb exists?!? <br><br>3) Food Street Char Kway Teow - It seems to be the only store specializing in char kway teow and its gooood. The lines are long at dinner or peak hours but decent for the rest of the day (of course, Outram Park Char kway Teow is just around the corner too). This is a more wet-style of frying. <br><br>4) Jin Ji Duck and Kway Chap - nestled in the corner near the red tables (and unfortunately, also a sizable population of pigeons sigh), recognizable by the newspaper articles hung on the store. They offer yam rice with braised duck, which is sadly becoming more rare. Their noodles (kway teow) have a chewy and perfect texture too, unlike what you usually get from any random store&#39;s kway teow, and I really enjoyed slurping down the bowl of noodles. The only grouse is that they don&#39;t give very generous portions of duck. <br><br>5) Tai Hwa Coffee/drinks store - more of a local haunt - many uncles and aunties queueing up here for their kopi! (And my parents first brought me here lol.) Also near the red tables. They make a mean cup of kopi C! Though other types of kopi are also popular: it just depends what you ordinarily order. It&#39;s thick and has a slight burnt taste, and is also very strong. Reminds me of the kopi at Suntec City food court (popular among the CBD crowd). <br><br>6) boiled soups - near the back entrance above the durian shop on the first floor. It&#39;s not often you find boiled Chinese-style soups like old cucumber or watercress. I&#39;m not a diehard fan of these soups but great if you&#39;re in the mood for some lighter fare! <br><br>Because carrot cake is my all-time fave hawker dish, the ones I&#39;ve tried from Super Mommy store and another one near the green tables are both pretty decent. Not the best, not something I&#39;d travel for, but authentic and satisfies the craving. <br><br>The best way to eat at a hawker center IMO is to split many dishes with friends!

They have recently revamped this street with with a glass canopy which covers the entire street, This structure protects hungry foodies from the elements, making a Singapore food crawl all the more enjoyable. Just like any hawkers center, you can move from stall to stall and sample all sorts of munchies and small meals to customize your own little repast. <br><br>I stepped up to a chicken and rice stand, for what was something like my billionth serving of Singapore&#39;s signature dish. I enhanced this selection with a nice selection of satay from a nearby hawker stall. Squid and chicken satay? Why yes, I don&#39;t mind if I do. Smith Street also has clean seating on the side of the street, and they seem to do a nice job of cleaning up the tables as soon as someone leaves.<br><br>However, as good as Smith Street is, it can get a bit sticky for it is outside after all, and unlike a hawker stand, searching for a toilet can be a bit problematic. Still, besides a cornucopia munching to be had, Smith Street is also lined with a number of souvenir shops and specialty items; purchase some Chinese herbs for some old school healing. All and all, Smith Street is a nice change from a typical hawker center.

text: Of the 5 hawker centres that I was able to go to, this one is my favorite. The food here is cheap, the portions are a good size to sample everything, but most importantly, the food is just amazing. Make sure to stop by Zhong Guo La Mian Xiao Long Bao for XLB and On Tap to wash down all the heavenly delicacies.

text: After 2 nights of meandering hopelessly around the dark, empty streets of Chinatown, we were elated one morning when we took an unexpected detour and stumbled upon the Chinatown Food Street sign.  Glimpsing red lanterns running all along the street, we thought we had struck gold.<br><br>Unfortunately, walking into the wake of shops and tourists revealed this place to be quite touristic with pushy vendors touting wares that I wouldn&#39;t buy.<br><br>However, the old-fashioned architecture was interesting to look at, and we discovered the Chinatown MRT at the very end of the street and made a mental note to come back for dinner.<br><br>I guess we came back too late on a Wednesday night for dinner, because all the stalls were pretty much closed.  The only one still serving food was a Japanese Korean place, so I got the chicken bibimbab for $4.00, while my bf got the kimchi udon with beef for $3.80.  He liked his meal, but I was a bit disappointed with mine.  The food wasn&#39;t very hot, and the rice didn&#39;t get crispy in the plastic bowl.

This huge hawker center in the midst of Chinatown is an excellent way to familiarize yourself with an essential part of Singaporean food culture. There is an immense number if different food stalls on the second floor so whatever type of Asian food you feel like it should be possible to find here. The environment is jot relaxing or nice but it does fee authentic and even when it is busy it feels fairly clean and orderly.<br><br>There are some excellent options for food and even for beer there are some good stalls. Well worth a visit both for tourists and people living here.

text: Of all the hawker centers I visited, this one was by far my favorite! Yes... I&#39;m a sucker for Chinese food, and being in Chinatown, well, this place has an unfair advantage. <br><br>I think what makes this place fun is not just the huge variety of food, but the fact that this multi story complex is also a huge mart for random souvenirs and goods. Just outside the food centre, you&#39;ll find more touristy things,a street of Chinese bakers, more Chinese restaurants, etc. I&#39;m a big fan!

We are in Singapore now during Chinese New Year so hoards of locals. The place is huge.  So many clustered stalls offering various local food, desserts, and drink.  One line must have snaked 20-30 people easily.  I never figured out which stall it was for.  And lots of stalls are closed in observance of the new year.  <br><br>It can be taunting. Narrow aisles and very noisy.  Food prep appears questionable and flatware, trays, and dishes also.  But it&#39;s another day now and I&#39;m fine.  <br><br>We walked around and around.  Ended up having chicken rice.  So so.  Chicken breast meat somewhat dry.  Rice somewhat hard.  Which stall?   Can&#39;t recall.  Sweet little couple runs it.<br><br>Take your food and find an empty table.  Communal ones too.<br><br>Public toilets available.  $0.10 Singapore.

text: Well I actually didn&#39;t know this place existed until a local friend dragged me through a dreary bottom level and up the escalator and ... this place is massive!!!! There must be about 150 stalls and seating for 500 people at least. There are corridors and alleys of hawker stalls that just wind all around the second level. We went on a Saturday morning around 10am and it was bustling with locals out for some quick cheap breakfast. The stalls don&#39;t sell expensive seafood type dishes like Newton Circus - but there is still a huge variety. $5 will get you a hearty meal.<br><br>This is definitely a local centre, not really a touristy place - it&#39;s a little more edgy and not as sparkling as some of the more touristy hawker centres. The tourists are plentiful at street level especially at the eateries along &#39;eat&#39; street but not many seem to venture up here. It was a good place to watch locals grab a quick bite and also head across to the &#39;wet&#39; market and do their weekly shopping.<br><br>This complex is a short stroll from the Temple Street exit of the Chinatown MRT station.

text: All I can say is that this place is huge, and while it is not my first encounter with the wonders of the Singapore Hawkers centres, it was one that I was drawn to simply because of the promise of two awesome beer stalls inside (the Smith Street Taps and the Good Beer Company). The ground floor is basically a huge market, which is effectively the extension of the rest of the markets in Chinatown, and in the basement is where all you do you food shopping, however if you are looking for a bite to eat it is on the second level where you head because there are simply so many stalls here you just do not know where to begin. Mind you, this is Singapore, so it isn&#39;t like your local food hall where you buy your lunch (or dinner) and one of the stalls and eat it, but rather you buy selections of food from the various stalls scattered around. One will sell Chinese, another Indian, another desert, and another drinks (including beer). You then take your purchases to one of the many tables and prepare for a feast. Mind you, it is quite loud in here, but the smells are amazing, and if you are here after six, make sure you go and check out the Good Beer Company (and Smith Street Taps).

text: I love coming to this street - though it can be a little bit commercial at times - with all the tourists, etc., but the standard of the food is still pretty authentic. There are quite a few options, when you dine in the evening, it&#39;s pretty cool and airy, and you get all the staples of Singaporean food fare. The MRT station is just nearby - so it&#39;s pretty easy to get to.<br><br>What I Love: The options for food here is great - I love the Drinks &amp; Desserts stall, the Fried Hokkien Mee, Char Kway Teow, Orh Luah and Ah Balling are yummy to the max. From the Drinks &amp; Desserts stall, I would recommend the Coconut Juice, Water Chestnut Drink &amp; Ice Kacang. The other Desserts are yummy too - but I always have the Ice Kacang there. There is a Seafood Stall that&#39;s really famous at the end of the street - it sells Ikan Bakar, Deep Fried Baby Squid, and quite a few other local delicacies. The City Satay stall is FAB!!! Gotta TRY!!! Hard to get yummy Satay in Singapore - so I do feel that they do pretty good ones.<br><br>What I Don&#39;t Love: Absolutely nothing!! :)

Best way to get there from city center is by MRT.  It&#39;s so hot outside and the indoor air conditioned walk way will take you through a series of interesting shops and advertisements and art work. China town is small but with over 200 stalls of hawkers on the second floor, there are tons of cooking styles to choose from.  If you&#39;re  with a friend, decide where you want to eat first, then look for a table and have one of you save the space and one gets the meal. During lunch time, it is packed qith people. If you are in the mood for shopping for souvenirs and such, there are tons of stores on the street level. The complex has a fruit and vegetable stands on the lower level too. It&#39;s not hard to find. From the Chinatown stop, head towards the Pagoda then follow the walking street lined with stands.

Went back for a late breakfast. Since it was Monday, more than half the stalls were closed but still plenty to chose, including those delicious peanut pancakes. Even better with coconut filling.<br>Now that I&#39;ve had a chance to compare, this is one of the larger and cleaner hawker centers. Inexpensive and lots of goodies with the main focus on Chinese food (duh). <br>Plenty of tables and breezy spots to sit and enjoy your food.

text: We had just touched down in Singapore from our 2.5 hour flight on Jetstar Airlines from Bangkok with not having had any type of water or beverage or even food except some bananas at 7am. It was already noon people. So hungry. So after we got into our room, changed, we headed straight out. First Maxwell Food Center was shut down for renovations. Bummer. Oh well keep trekking as closed shops would never deter a Yelper. So onward and outward dodging tourist after tourist, &#34;Out of my way, I&#39;m hungry!&#34; is going through my brain as I&#39;ve only one thing on my mind and that&#39;s &#34;get something yummy into my belly.&#34; We finally found our first set of food stalls on Smith Street and settled on #7. For a small plate of noodles for $5, it wasn&#39;t anything special. Three pieces of shrimp, a lemon, and watery noodles. Actually anything tasted good at that point. We should have just gone to the second level of the complex as they had more food and even cheaper options and probably better food. It&#39;s ok. I&#39;m here for 5 days. That complex is mine to conquer. Mwahahahaha.
Chinatown Complex is a hawker center right next to the Buddha&#39;s Tooth temple in Chinatown. Lots of great stalls here!
