text: A very welcome sight for the hungry morning person, wandering this hot and sweaty land, despite being a place offering hot salty soup and hot tea...because their food is absolutely delicious! They offer a very traditional kettle of water on a charcoal brazier for your gongfu tea set, and a very strong packet of loose tea, to go with their strongly flavored bak kut teh soup, pork innards, and other porky deliciousnesses. You can see how enthusiastic I am because I am making up words for them. The soup is more dark than clear, and tastes more of soy than pepper, but I like it this way. <br><br>It is on the first floor of Hong Lim Food Centre (and Yelp needs to update the address).

Very dark bak kut teh. Never seen a &#34;blacker&#34; bak kut teh before. Sometimes the stallowners face is also as black, if you are oblivious to your surroundings and block in the way of the trays of food she brings to you. So be conscious a little in this crowded corner of the hawker centre. <br><br>Some people love the soup because of the herbal taste. I do admit there is a sort of addictiveness to it. However the herbal-ness comes off real subtle for me and I tasted more dark sauce. I could be wrong. You should give it a shot at least once to see if this works for your taste buds. For some people, its a 5 star place in terms of the soup. <br><br>What is a let down for me is that the meat is not as soft as it should be. The fatty pork trotters is not really a tear-off the-bone kinda deal and below average in terms of tear-of-ness, while the pork ribs is also below average in terms of that. <br><br>Nonetheless this place is a sell-out during lunch time. The stallowners do have a rather good service in terms of reserving seats for you with their own tissue papers.

text: This review is long overdue. Wanted to rave about one of my favourite places in Orchard Road, but just didn&#39;t get to do it till now (excuses I know hahahahah). <br><br>So, here&#39;s the story. Celebrated my birthday at this cafe in May this year with my gal friends. 4 of us ordered a few mains and a dessert to share. I gotta say we were all very happy with the food. I especially love the 2 main dishes: Fuwa Fuwa Hoshino Soufflé with Porcini Rissoto Tomato Cream and Omu Rice with Shrimp &amp; Mozarella. Just writing about them and looking at their yelp pictures are making me hungry now. <br><br>Their dessert item, Double Pancake Soufflé Style is also recommended. It is so big I am sure it can feed 8 instead of the 4 of us. Love the service here! Definitely one of the few places in SG where you can enjoy good and cheery service at a mid-priced eatery. Good service is just super hard to find in SG #sadfactoflife.<br><br>I have been coming to this cafe chain over the years. My favourite outlet is still this Plaza Singapura one. After writing this review, I have the urge to visit it soon. Think I gotta make it real soon. #whydoeswritingreviewsmakeonehungry?

text: Located on the third floor extension of Plaza Singapura, is Hoshino Coffee, a popular Japanese chain of coffee shop. I wanted to try this so badly at Shibuya but time did not allow. So back here in Singapore, I decided to go all out and try it!! 7 soufflés ordered and here goes my personal soufflé buffet!! &#34;Gotta catch em all!&#34;<br><br>Now that is supposedly Spring in Japan, even though my Japanese friends told me it snowed last week and it&#39;s currently 6 degrees celsius in Tokyo, the Spring menu for Hoshino coffee includes this super pretty pink  strawberry soufflé pancake!<br><br>1. Hoshino&#39;s Spring Pancake Soufflé $14.50++<br>So after the waitress took our 7 orders of soufflés, all the 4 pancakes arrived at all table all at once! The strawberry ice cream was very smooth, it wasn&#39;t too sweet but the syrup they provided us was very sweet indeed! Use it sparingly over the soufflé, as it can drown out your taste buds and we had 6 more soufflés to try and we didn&#39;t want to kill our taste buds. The soufflé itself is alot harder than the normally fluffly soufflé. As it is a pancake, I would consider it more like a fluffier and slightly tougher version of a chiffon cake.<br><br>2. Pancake Soufflé with Chocolate Banana $13.50++<br>Lots of chocolate sauce going on here. When you order a pancake soufflé, you have an option of whipped cream of softee. We went with softee for all our pancake soufflés and we liked the softee. Japanese soft serves, you can never go wrong with them! The pancake soufflé don&#39;t have any fillings inside, unlike the hot vanilla soufflés.<br><br>3. Pancake Soufflé with Mango $13.50++<br>We decided to go easy on the syrup for this one, having tried the first Spring soufflé with syrup and the second one with alot of chocolate sauce. The softee itself isn&#39;t very sweet, as such you can taste the subtle sweetness of the soufflé pancake!<br><br>4. Pancake Soufflé with Matcha &#34;Ogura&#34; Bean Paste $13.50++<br>The most modest of the pancake soufflés, and my personal favourite. The matcha soft cream here tastes very similar to the one I tried at Tsujiri, it has a stronger bitter after taste than the typical sweet and sugar-ladden matcha ice cream. The bean paste is also very sweet, as such, be careful not to get a sugar-overdose trying to eat that on it&#39;s own! <br><br>5. Vanilla Soufflé with Chocolate/Custard/Matcha sauce $10.80++ each<br>All the vanilla soufflés arrived at our table just as we were done with the pancake soufflé!<br><br>You gotta pour the sauces into the soufflé and the soufflé was steaming hot as we sliced it open, and even as we dug in, each spoonful, you could still see it steaming!! It is a very hot dessert, and be careful not to burn your tongue!<br><br>Of the 3 sauces, my favourite was custard. It had the right amount of sweetness! The chocolate was abit too sweet for my liking and the green tea wasn&#39;t sweet at all!<br><br>and here&#39;s the bill for our exploration of 7 soufflés at Hoshino coffee!!<br><br>Service is pretty good here, there&#39;s a button for your to press and the waitress will come to you. The also provide you with a bag to put your things.

text: 1 star each for the 5 things that make it for me. (Service, cleanliness, food, price and &#34;will I come back?&#34;). This place hits all five. FIVE STARS!<br><br>Service was good, attentive and non-intrusive. I asked about the iced-coffee and the server was able to explain everything AND accommodate my special request. No fuss!<br><br>The restaurant was clean and well-kept. The menu was small, but had pictures for most, so can&#39;t go wrong there. Gordon Ramsey will have a fit, I&#39;m sure. &#34;NO PHOTOS IN YOUR MENU, ARE YOU STUPID OR SOMETHING?&#34; he&#39;d yell. But me, I like to see a preview of what I&#39;m ordering. By the way, since this is a Japanese coffee shop, there is a huge display of waxed facsimiles of most of the food available for you to ooh and ahh over.<br><br>Souffles! Savoury and sweet souffles! Pancakes of incredible thickness, but fluffy and light like a... souffle! Each pancake is almost 2 inches thick! The french toast was also very good. I had a savoury souffle, and even though it was topped with a huge souffle, the dish was not heavy at all.<br><br>Price was slightly high for some items, but reasonable for others. The coffee items have a refill option of $3 or so. <br><br>Will I come back? Yes, please!

text: I passed by this cafe many times and it was only until yesterday I finally get my first taste with a fellow yelper. The wait (20 minutes) was killing me but it was certainly worth it. Because my friend told me she probably won&#39;t be able to finish her portion, so we decided to share and trust me the mouthfuls of pancake I had (Chocolate Banana) wasn&#39;t enough to satisfy my stomach. <br><br>I was tempted to order another one but eventually I didn&#39;t since the sweet mango drink I had was enough for my tummy for that evening and that&#39;s how good it was. I didn&#39;t understand why the wait was so long but I glad I waited, it&#39;s one of the better places for pancakes. Soft and tasty is what I  remember from my few bites. Another thing is both of us seemed to be competing with one another to see who gets more bites of it. I ate it so quickly that I forget the primary rule of eating, that is to enjoy it slowly. I will order my own share the next time I come back. Good food means the staff will see more of me!! *evil grin* <br><br>The mango smoothie was nice, not too sweet like some other places and it went well with the cake. <br><br>Overall, this is in my list of recommendation especially coming from a big fan of the Land of the Rising Sun!

text: The initial wait was reasonable. Around 15 mins. Waiting for the food was abit slower. Service was kinda average. They had service bell on the table but they were kinda useless. It is much faster raising your hands and getting service. <br><br>The service staff serving our table had limited knowledge of English so asking her questions like &#39;do you sell the coffee beans&#39; needed another staff to help. <br><br>Food wise it was a hit and miss. I had the demi-glacé omu rice. The sauce was decent but the proportion of the rice to the sauce was inbalanced. I think they should give more sauce or reduce the size of the dish. <br><br>The dessert was a letdown. I had the creme brûlée. The dessert was not made on the spot since the crust sugar was cold on taste. <br><br>Price wise I find it a tad expensive.

text: The Food<br><br>1. Fuwa-Fuwa Hoshino Souffle ($15.80)  - My favorite! I tried this based on Angeline C&#39;s recommendation and she was right on spot. This was definitely a unique dish. It has an amazing, light scrambled-eggs-buttery flavor. My only complain would be there was too little meat in it (barely half a dozen small sausage cubes). <br><br>2. Omelette rice with beef sauce - Average. <br><br>3. Matcha souffle with softie ice-cream - I love the souffle but it was a bit wet towards the end when I got to the bottom of the bowl. Also, I would have preferred a stronger match flavor. The softie ice-cream was all melted and running when they served it which was a let down. <br><br>4. Pancake souffle - It tasted more like a sponge cake than a souffle but it was still worth a try. Interesting concept for a pancake. <br><br>5. Hoshino Pot Baked Curry Rice - served with eggs (a little more undercooked than the typical sunny-side up style), sausage and some brocoli. Good. I like the way the egg was wet &amp; runny :) They were more generous with the sausage helpings in this dish too. I think I saw a full sausage. <br><br>Overall, an interesting japanese fusion restaurant. I like the creative concepts of mixing up dishes like the pancake-souffle and the  Fuwa-Fuwa Hoshino Souffle (which was like a savory souffle crossed with baked rice). I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve tried this anywhere else so definitely worth a check out :) The queue gets pretty crazy at dinner time. Best to come  before the dinner crowd (6.30pm should be safe).

text: -casual, open air cafe in atrium setting, get a booth seating<br>-hand dripped coffee is headlined, so one has to try. Happy to say it is a lovely, concentrated cup of coffee with a rich, full bodied roast. I&#39;m a fan of the taste of coffee, I just don&#39;t want to consume a whole soup bowl&#39;s worth. <br>-lots of small, subtle touches that make the dining experience very enjoyable and, dare I say, Japanese. Ex. Baskets provided for your handbag, individual minijugs of cream and sugar syrup<br>-rare instance that I don&#39;t see often enough in Singapore; all the dishes arrived together, so we all eat at the same time. Why can&#39;t more places do this?<br>-shrimp, avocado and egg sandwich. Onions hidden inside which gives the sandwich a nice, subtle kick. The shrimp were nice and juicy. Great snack to have with coffee<br>-enjoyed the experience so much so, we extended the coffee into lunch and ordered pasta (spaghetti w/ eggplant, bacon, shimeji &amp; sausage; carbonara w/ yolk &amp; bacon) and rice (Demi glace &#39;Omu&#39; rice w/ mozzarella)<br>-well prepared Japanese style pasta, that is scrumptious. <br>-the western styled omelette rice was ok. You have to appreciate ketchup. Not that it was overwhelming, but it was very much there in every bite. The light, fluffy egg and half glaze couldn&#39;t balance out the tomato sweetness. <br>-overall a delightful experience, can&#39;t wait to come back and try other dishes

It&#39;s at least a 15 minute wait for a seat. And go with a person if you really want to try it. If you&#39;re alone, they prolly make you wait till there&#39;s a single table available even if there&#39;s a booth empty. Apparently the barista got me a booth and got himself a scolding from the waitress (aunties; can&#39;t expect must from them)<br><br>The service I must say is freaking lousy. The bell works perfectly fine, but they just don&#39;t come. Too busy I guess? But so many of them were talking amongst themselves without paying attention. Or should there be a better system to serve the customers?<br><br>I hope the food would at least wow me so I may not give a negative feedback about this place.<br><br>People watching is fun here though. Because it&#39;s crowded, the patrons do not suspect you staring at them. I do love the secrecy of this. And they kind of just release who they are from inside. If you&#39;re sitting at a booth, you can even watch people in other restaurants from other levels having food and what not.<br><br>Food wise. Well done. I loved it a lot. The cream sauce in the carbonara dish wasn&#39;t that thick that would stick to your tongue and even if it does after a few mouths, drinking a small sip of water would clear it up mostly.

text: Desert quite yucky. The pasta is ok and the coffee is normal, but sell at Starbucks pricing.

This place is odd. It is like they are trying to create a quaint Japanese-style Western ambiance like Maison but in the middle of an open floor of a mall, so it seems out of place.<br><br>$6 for the coffee is steep. The matcha green tea latte with ice cream was good, but there wasn&#39;t much ice cream because it was resting on big cubes of ice which went almost to the top of the cup. I would ask for it with no ice if I go back. These drinks were decent but in my opinion it would not have been worth waiting in the nearly omnipresent queue for them.

You know it&#39;s Japanese - the waiters all dressed up spiffily in that old-school &#39;western&#39; vest suit ensemble, woody earthy paneling... <br><br>I didn&#39;t have coffee but ordered the chocolate lava cake which was quite diving, warm and oozy and went well with the soft vanilla ice cream. Tried some of the green tea souffle as well which I enjoyed surprisingly - not a big fan of green tea but this one was not overly-teaish in taste and the souffle was of a good texture.

text: Seriously good! U wouldn&#39;t believe that the queue speaks for itself. I&#39;d thought, well, it could be that people are simply curious about what this 2 week&#39;s old is capable of. And when the line starts to form, more people just keep queuing without a single complain. It was a late lunch thingy after a movie show, I make my way to this little cafe joint speedily. This is like crazy, the snaking line - almost a L-shaped by now is still around. I have seen the same this morning at 11.10m (the outlet only open at 11.30am!) when I drop by to ask if I could make a reservation for 3pm but was turned down politely, which now I clearly understand why. I know this is what I have to eat despite still nursing my throat discomfort &amp; joined the queue - determined to know if they are as good as they claimed.<br><br>The interior is not entirely small but having a 3 separate dining space. The main hall sits most of the diners with wooden table and leather padded seats. It emits a brighter and casual feel, probably the area is not constraint by a stiff ceiling but an architectural glass rooftop in the mall that illuminates the stretch with a natural glow of sunlight. There are 4 booth seats which is most ideal for a gals-get-together session, I figured. <br><br>The menu was straight forward, without fanciful hard to understand dishes. Zoom right into my orders and wave for the staff, the lady clad in chef suit came to me (gosh, even one works in the kitchen has to take time to manage the hall during peak hours?).. aw.. but she was very well-mannered and patient when confronted with inquiries. In fact, no one was seen idling - all the wait person served with pride, promptly and in an unhurried manner. A remarkable service team.<br><br>I admit I felt a little uneasy when I picked that unfamiliar dish - Fuwa Fuwa. But the truth tells me that feeling has been unwarranted.The most raved about  &#34;fluffy savory soufflé&#34; seriously did not put to shame. Not only that it enticed me with its huge golden puffy bonnet but I was completely sold by its astonishing delicate flavors  This is one dish I wish I had on my last - cottony &amp; airy, formidable without a trace of deflating. It is no wonder that people called it the &#34;cloud&#34;, but I think it&#39;s me that&#39;s on Cloud 9 at every bite. Instead of baking it like an Italian classic with white sauce, this one has a tomato version in it. It was filled with incredible moments - spooning the whites like a mass destruction into that light feathery foam, trespassing to get to the bed of the baking dish. The gems hidden under these soft foams have never been so right. Tomato sauce infused - each grain was plump, tangy-sweet, not soggy. Its flavor was enhanced by strips of middle eye bacon and mushroom bits. Together with that eggy, Parmesan cheese soufflé, a divine marriage left unchallenged by the sweet version. Impossible not to eat, I think I can have 1 on every other day. <br><br>A couple of spaghetti dishes if you like, other than &#34;Omu&#34; rice (omelette rice) or sandwiches. I had the Lobster Bisque Soup Spaghetti. A french dish but cooked the Japanese way for a lighter taste. Instead of highly seasoned, this one prepared with tomato and finely chopped mushrooms comes with a milder liquidized cream but rich crustaceans flavor. I find the soup a little offensive (even while its still steaming hot) while my dining partner finds it delicious, so I guess it&#39;s a mixed conclusion. It was not entirely bad - at least the spaghetti is cooked the correct way, I guess I just didn&#39;t have the mood for such a sophisticated seafood thing today.<br><br>String along with others, I ordered a pancake soufflé, this time a more familiar sweet version! Not the plain ones but a more elaborate classic with a tropical touch. I have been advised to remind the kitchen to start preparing the soufflé when I was half way into my main course. It was like taking a number queue to a soufflé! I was asked to wait for another 15mins by the apologetic service staff. Not an issue at all, I said to myself because the end result was a light and airy inflated sponge that was unforgettable. The only negative I had was the fruits. Upon checking, I learnt that frozen mango fruits are used while the kiwi are fresh produces. I&#39;d prefer ripened fruits atop my dessert, not raw and crunchy. Worst, the mango has a weird over-frozen texture makes them taste rubbery. However, the homemade whipped cream was smooth. And pls do not leave the place without a cup of Hoshino blend.<br><br>Whaff that strong Hoshino caffeine scent right in front of me - that was one of the distinct characteristic while waiting in line. Carefully selected coffee beans were roasted over direct flame and then hand drip to a good-bodied brew. The blend has got a rather pale flavor  less rich as compared to Oriole&#39;s. Milder acidity but has a lingering smell. I guess the Japanese adores this light perfumery beverage. I am good for that 10g but if anyone wanted an extra brew, there is a 50% off for a refill.

text: Hoshino Coffee&#39;s casual vibe, trendy fare and wallet-friendly price points have made it a hit among the teenybopper set and the broke-by-the-end-of-the-month types.<br><br>I suggest getting the eggy souffle baked rice and although the menu alleges this as &#34;rissoto&#34;, it is really a term used loosely, and more regular Japanese rice than Italian risotto:<br><br>1) Omu Souffle ($16.80): tomato rice casserole dotted with broccoli and shrimp.<br><br>2) Fuwa-Fuwa Hoshino Souffle ($15.80): with mushrooms and ham bits <br><br>3) Matcha Souffle ($10.80): semi-collapsed by the time it got to our table. This was disappointing, and I much rather spent a few dollars more and get the fabulous ones at Laurent Bernard.<br><br>4) Ice Matcha Latte with Softee ($9.30): rich and robust. Much better than the souffle as a sweet finisher

After reading so much about the hype over this Japanese kopitiam, we decided to head over during a weekday evening. However, this trip made me realise how inefficient communication in the kitchen can actually hold up the queue and upsets diners even though this usually happens in Gordon Ramsay&#39;s Kitchen Nightmares.<br><br>Speaking of the food, the baked curry rice was delicious as the beef curry sauce was really thick and savoury. The soft egg yolk enhances the richness of the rice. It has been years ago since I had my Japanese curry rice.<br><br>The pancake souffle is nothing spectacular and was a little tad dry and less fluffy than a mc pancake. Hence had to rely on the brown sugar syrup to finish this although they gave us the maple syrup which we did not choose. The puny little salted whipped cream was definitely not enough to go with the pancake. But to pay for extra cream? Definitely no way. <br><br>Fortunately, the matcha souffle saved the day. Even though it did not rise to a considerable height, it was filled with sweet matcha custard and thus this warm pud was really comforting one to enjoy. The only dish that I would recommend one to try.<br><br>In short, this place is definitely not worth queuing so better to avoid peak hours. I think it is very adventurous or bold for a newly opened restaurant to offer so many soufflé items as they require long waiting time. However, this must be provided that the orders run smoothly without missing out or leaving out any item, only to have realized that the kitchen had left out the order after customers&#39; reminders.

Personally I didn&#39;t like their blended coffee.  It&#39;s more like a tasteless Starbucks roast. After I inquired, the cook did admit they don&#39;t use Mocha (which is unusual for a Japanese blend that I&#39;ve tasted in most coffee shops in Japan having lived there for 10 years). Certainly doesn&#39;t warrant the S$5.80 per cup.  The milk (not cream...ok, fine) was not even warm.  Looked forward to their Pancake Soufflé but was turned off by the 30 min wait requirement (which means I will finish my coffee long before it shows up). Had the French Toast instead which was nice.

text: Ok as I am still shock as the sticker price of hand dripped coffee, my husband wanted to try this place. As I was getting hungry to, why not see what is so special with pricey coffee. Well I totally put my foot in my mouth, this was amazing coffee, it was strong and had a seriously amazing after taste that I just can&#39;t describe, let&#39;s just say I didn&#39;t even really need to sugar or cream at all. Now what totally sold me on this place was their Hoshino Souffle blew my mind as I never had anything like it. It was tomato fried rice at the bottom with this creamy fluffy egg like whip cream topping. It put the Omu rice to the side and now not worst eating.  The teriyaki chicken sandwich was good too. The sevice was ok but at least here is a button to call them.

As with many Bucks in Singapore, this is a nice haven to duck in and do some work in a generally quieter environment.  Staff won&#39;t bother you and there are outlets if you need to plug in and charge.

text: For a cafe, TCC has a good menu with very cool interiors. I stayed at a hotel nearby and for a late night grub, it was very satisfying. <br><br>I had the creamy chicken pasta dish along with a side of fried wings with chilli sauce. No complaints at all!

CRAP SERVICE: SPILLED WATER OVER MY DINING PARTNER &amp; SEATED US IN SMOKING AREA WITHOUT ASKING FOR PREFERENCE FIRST! <br><br>SALTY FOOD. The mushroom soup and calamari were too salty. The only thing I enjoyed was the iced lemon tea and the garlic toast. <br><br>First off, I did not make a reservation and so was in the line for a table here. The waiter did not ask if I preferred indoor seating or not, he simply led my dining partner and I to a smoking area outside the restaurant. I am allergic to cigarette smoke and did not know that smoking IS permitted at this restaurant. I requested to be moved indoors, and we did get moved inside but I am irritated that they did not ask if I minded sitting in a smoking area. <br><br>Secondly, a clearly inexperienced waitress was pouring out water for my dining partner and spilled it all over her lap! The only thing she did was apologize and then run away, leaving her colleagues to deal with the mess!! HOW RUDE! <br><br>Another waiter offered to switch the wet chair for a dry one and asked if there was anything they could do. I said no, there&#39;s nothing you can do but provide a new pair of shorts for my dining partner! 10 minutes later, no dry chair was exchanged with the one made wet. I had to ask for one. <br><br>The waitress who spilled the water did not come back to our table nor say anything about her mistake. She was laughing and talking with her colleagues. This was New Year&#39;s Eve night, and this lousy visit spoiled our mood for the night. <br><br>We REGRET sitting down at this restaurant and wish we went to Privé across the street. It was raining and TCC had blinds to block the rain from splashing their customers sitting outdoors but didn&#39;t lower them, Privé did. <br><br>I will not be patronizing this restaurant again. This was a very crappy visit.

Good food and drinks. A small meal, drink, and dessert for one person can easily cost $60, which seems to be the norm around Singapore. The location is curbside, in he middle of shopping mall. There is shelter from rain.

I love the TCC at the International Building simply for its round-the-clock service. It&#39;s convenient for everyone especially tourists who are looking for some late-night grub. Sometimes you want to pull an all-nighter studying for an exam or rushing a deadline and there just aren&#39;t enough 24/7 places in Singapore so TCC is a perfect choice for me when I decide to stay out.<br><br>TCC has an extensive menu. From the regular coffee or cappuccino to quirky but innovative drinks like Chocolate Affogatto, Frosty Baileys, Almond Creme Brulee Lattee and the Azuki Freeze, chances are you&#39;ll find something you fancy. Some may find the drinks on the pricey side but with such innovative drinks that you can&#39;t find anywhere else, it&#39;s worth the price.<br><br>There&#39;s also a wide range of food choices from salads, to pasta and baked rice, and mains like ribeye steak and pan-seared seafood. With so many to choose from, it&#39;s hard to decide!

What makes this TCC different from the other 100 or so branches is the adorably unique interiors! They&#39;ve taken the &#34;Connoisseur&#34; quite seriously and built a french-chic rendition of a coffee cafe. <br><br>Its conveniently located right on Orchard, next to Isetan at the International Building so its the perfect location top pop by for a quick drink on a day of shopping or after the movies. The fact that its 24 hours makes it even better!<br><br>The food is as per TCC standards, Western with a slight Asian twist. The drinks were to die for and the desserts extremely decadent.<br><br>Great to stop by for a cappuccino  and do some light people watching!

Marco Marco has an open, inviting atmosphere. Historically, I&#39;ve been pretty judgemental about Italian restaurants in Singapore, which in my opinion, usually lack tradational authenticity. But suspending my benchmark of a real Roman ristorante, Marco Marco does a great job. Certainly the best $18-$20 Italian-style pizza I&#39;ve had in Singapore. It&#39;s a great value for a pizza or pasta fix.

text: Ollella is a bakery which offers choux pastries. It is located at Farrer Park which is quite a distance away from me. But the shop offers delivery with a fee of $5, which sounds quite reasonable as it was about the same as the amount I would need to spend on public transport to get to the place.<br><br>It was easy to select the items online on the website and payment was done with credit card. I had forgotten about a request which I later sent through the feedback form online through its website. My request was answered within the same day. The ordered items was delivered right on time and packed in boxes.  <br><br>Vanilla/Chocolate Choux Tart ($45/ 6 inches)<br>The classic flavors of vanilla and chocolate make this the perfect tart for any occasion. Adorned with a heap of cream filled chouquettes, the sweet tart base is lined with luscious vanilla or chocolate pastry cream. Finished off with a drizzle of rich chocolate fudge sauce. Enough to serve 4 to 6 pax.<br>The tart was topped with a small hill of chouquettes, which were easily pluck off with fingers. The chouquettes were filled with milky cream but did not taste jelat. It did not taste too sweet too.<br><br>Vanilla Choux ($4/ 5cm)<br>Plain craqueline choux, Madagascar vanilla mascarpone cream, Madagascar vanilla white chocolate ganache, Vanilla streusel<br>It looked the plainest among all the pastries, but I felt it tasted the best. In a single bite, the vanilla bean liquid filling flowed out like lava, which I was caught off guard. Seldom can find places which used real vanilla bean, which gave such a nice earthy taste.<br><br>Choux Pastries with Pearl Sugar and Almonds   ($3/ 10 pieces or 60grams)<br>Plain Choux Puff with Sugar and Diced Almonds<br>Packed in a resealed brown paper bag, the choux pastry was light and crispy in taste, with nutty texture. At $3 I felt it was the best deal.<br><br>Complete Choux Platter (All 8 Flavors) ($24)<br>Complete platter- 8 flavours of 3cm mini choux<br>(Vanilla, Apple Cinnamon, Lemon, Raspberry, Matcha Azuki, Tiramisu, Dark Chocolate, Boozy Brownie Sundae)<br>A mixture of its regular choux pastries in mini sizes. So cute.<br><br>Overall the pastries were quite yummy.

text: Ollella is a new cafe in the Farrer Park/Little India area that serves freshly made varieties of cream puffs. I came by here on a Sunday afternoon and found the location to be about a 8 minute walk from the Farrer Park MRT station. <br><br>I was greeted by a glistening showcase of choux pastries. Paralyzed by indecision, I decided on the first item on the menu , a tactic I often use when I am overwhelmed by choices. I devoured the classic vanilla puff, savoring every bite that was filled with crumbly pieces of goodness with a fine balance of cream that was not too sweet. <br><br>The cafe also has a unique relationship with the Pourover, a coffee vendor that sells, you guessed it, pour overs! I had already had a cup of coffee a few hours prior and had to pass this time around, but hope to return in the future to try the coffee with another cream puff flavor.<br><br>This is a good place to come with your laptop as the WiFi is strong and the seating abundant - at least until word gets out!

text: Starbucks with a sea view...<br><br>One of the nicer Starbucks outlets in Singapore, this one has a nice view of the ocean, some outdoor seating and a laid back vibe.<br><br>This one is located in the newly opened Parkland Green strip mall a little further up the road, and should not be confused with the Starbucks at the former Big Splash complex at 902 East Coast Parkway.<br><br>It gets pretty crowded on weekend evenings, and I think it won&#39;t be long before most people discover it... before then, I&#39;ll be hangin&#39; out here...

text: Dazzling Cafe is a well known chain from Taiwan, known for its toasts and mochi stuffed waffle. It has 2 outlets in Singapore. The cafe was beautifully decorated in fairytale look.<br><br>Cafe Latte (Single Shot) ($6++)<br>Topped up $1++ to Rainbow-nize the drink. The drink looked quite pretty but lacking of the coffee taste.<br><br>Lobster Cold Capellini ($27.90++)<br>Cold Capellini, marinated with extra virgin olive oil, sea salt, white pepper, chives, poached lobster tail in butter, mentaiko mayo, basil powder, salmon roe, micro herbs<br>I like that the mentaiko mayo was served separated so one can adjust the richness of the dish to one&#39;s liking. Rich and creamy while refreshing.<br><br>Chicken Cutlet with Honey Mustard ($19.90++)<br>Served with scrambled egg<br>Marinated chicken thigh breaded with bread crumbs, topped with scrambled egg and arugula<br>The scrambled egg was quite creamy while the chicken was juicy inside.<br><br>Pandan Gula Melaka Mini Toast ($11.90++)<br>Salted gula melaka ice cream, custard, condense milk, chocolate sauce, pandan crumble, crushed peanut, red current, strawberry, coffee wafer stick, kaya toast cubes <br>The crispy toast was quite yummy on its own. Although not as prettily decorated as the main sized version, but it tasted not bad and the serving was just nice for one to finish comfortably.<br><br>Overall the food was not bad although prices were on the high side. Service was a tab slow. One needed to ask a couple times for the iced water to be served.

text: It&#39;s always very underwhelming when a cafe puts too much emphasis on presentation and sacrifices taste. The cafe decor and food presentation looks great, but the waffles I ordered was rather average. I also ordered a cafe latte. Looked good, with nice milky foam and served with a caramelised biscuit. But again, the coffee itself was not good. The coffee aroma was  weak, so ended up tasting more milk than coffee. <br><br>This would be a good place to bring a date who is not a foodie, but very into cute places and trends. <br><br>Upon 5, I rated this place a 3 because:<br>-1 star for taste<br>-1 star for revisitability

Ambient is good, foods not bad, was quite impressed by the &#39;Scallop and Parma Ham&#39; presentation.<br><br>However, everything got turned down by the lousy service! A staff would rather clean the table instead of taking our order, we have been waiving our hands but no one could be bother to attend to us. Ice cream was served with no spoon, when we were trying to get one from the waiter who was walking pass us, he pretended did not notice and just walked away. <br><br>I always believe good foods matter, and good service matters more. Hope they will really look into this issue.

text: I appreciate this boba place. Conveniently located just up from the Kovan MRT. It&#39;s located in Heartland mall and satisfies my boba cravings for the most part. <br><br>Its nice that you can choose your sweetness level and ice amount. And their tea flavor choices are of great variety. <br><br>I also like that their pearls are included in the price of the drink. Although the pearls are pink which was a little odd in the beginning for me but they are always made with a good texture. Not too soft and not too hard like some places. <br><br>The people working are pretty nice too. <br><br>Love their earl grey and green tea drinks. Simple yet flavorful! <br><br>Pudding is good too. Not overly sweet like some other places. <br><br>Tip: cash or ezlink. Yes, how convenient that you can pay using your MRT card :) <br>Tip: it&#39;s outside of the exit of the cold storage. Next to the subway and near the toast box on the first floor

The Pantry Cookery School as the name suggested is a cooking school but thats not the only thing they have there. I don&#39;t come here for their cooking class but for its farmer&#39;s market.<br><br>When I was staying in New York, I looked forward to the days where there is a Farmer&#39;s Market and I can get my fresh apple ciders and other delicious eats.  Well, farmer&#39;s market isn&#39;t exactly very popular here since we do have the wet markets that we can go to get our local (or malaysian) produces.  There is a popular farmer&#39;s market which is held in the pantry cookery school  on 1st and 3rd Saturday of the month. I look forward to getting my fresh Portabello mushrooms and other yummy treats.  Like they always say &#34; &#34;early bird catches the worm&#34;, do go there early as some of the produces may run out. <br><br>Usually, we will grab breakfast at its cafe. Great place for family outing with kids.  They have an outdoor trampoline and a play set to entertain the kids.  The only downside to this place is that the parking is limited. You might have to park somewhere else in Dempsey and take a short walk there.

text: They&#39;ve  changed their name! Now called Carrot Sticks and Cravings. The address is 75E Loewen. Go through the red gate at the end of the parking lot. First building in the left.<br>Not a tourist destination since it is in the middle of a preschool environment. <br>However, really worth the effort to hunt down. A very healthy menu <br>Pastries are to die for, so save room, or take one with you.

text: Really crowded place! Well, I guess it was thanks to the fortnightly farmers&#39; market that is hosted there by them. Anyway, bf ordered the all day breakfast set - unfortunately they had run out of sausage! Would&#39;ve liked to try it. <br><br>Anyway, four stars for the breakfast set ($16.50), which included 3 slices of toast (sourdough I think!), mushrooms (would&#39;ve liked to have more!), roasted tomato, extra bacon (since sausage had run out), and scrambled eggs! Everything was actually done really well, except that I might&#39;ve liked some ketchup hmm.. Haha. And in the bf&#39;s words, the bacon was the good quality sort which is kind of ham-like with some fat (as opposed to a lot of fat with little ham).<br><br>I also decided to have their fruit and nut granola/muesli with greek yogurt and honey ($16.50) on a whim. What kind of granola costs $16.50?! As we were to discover, it was a HUGE bowl. My jaws ached chewing it.. I&#39;m more used to (and definitely prefer) yogurt + granola on top, rather than granola with a smattering of yogurt.  Ratio was certainly not there.. However, the guy at the counter was very nice, provided me with a takeout box when I asked for one (to remove the tons of granola which I was pretty certain I wouldn&#39;t be finishing).<br><br>Large slices of quiche sat in the display looking pretty inviting, comes with salad and a side (you can pick from the display too - there was a quinoa side that looked pretty gd!). Also, $4.50 scones looked fairly yummy.<br><br>Nice outdoor seating, the shopfront itself is pretty small so only 4-5 people can squeeze in to order at one go.

Aiyo Olio.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Aiyo Olio.'}]
text: Beautiful, hip space in the little India. Definitely a nice to spot to have coffee, hangout and chat amongst friends. However, the food leaves a lot to be desired... <br><br>I ordered the Aiyo Olio, spaghetti tossed in oil with garlic, chilli padi and a moderate serving of bacon. It was &#34;ehh...&#34; Nothing special. It was so simple, I could probably cook it. I tasted my fellow Elite&#39;s carbonara and unfortunately, it had the same unsatisfying taste. <br><br>Overall, I would give the food two stars and the space four stars, which averages to a three star review. Fortunately, OMB&#39;s branding and design is quite impressive. The shop sells cute pillows and bags that reference everything bacon, which would definitely have some appeal to SG&#39;s hipster community.

text: Ordered a carbonara ($15) here on a Sunday afternoon during lunchtime. It came pretty quickly, and water here is self-service. <br><br>I seasoned my carbonara with lots of powdered Parmesan and chilli flakes. Without seasoning, it fell flat. I had a taste of another Yelper&#39;s Aiyo Olio, and it lacked salt. For a few pieces of bacon and spaghetti, I feel the lack of value here. I expected at least two bacon rashers with each pasta dish. <br><br>Would not return, except maybe for an iced tea and with a laptop/book on a weekday afternoon.

text: I added this business to Yelp so I guess I might as well go ahead and review.<br><br>They do a nice sizeable latte Dimbulah Select (single shot) for $4.70. I&#39;ll go for that rather than the standard latte (double shot) which is $5.50 as it&#39;s my second coffee of the day by then and heck coffee is already expensive as it is. Decent crema and art, very pleasant staff although when I ordered beans to be ground for my friend who doesn&#39;t have a grinder, they said I would have to collect the next morning. Then I went in the morning and it wasn&#39;t ready..<br><br>Haven&#39;t tried their food but saw people eating plates or pasta that had healthy portions. I&#39;ve also tried their piccolo ($4.20) a few times and that&#39;s always been a very solid effort.<br><br>Bit unusual, you order at the counter and they serve you at the table. No wifi sadly although they provide...actual newspapers (GASP!!). Tables currently very spaced out, it&#39;s new tho..if they get more crowded it would be good if they had more seats. Nice solid wooden tables, nice touch.<br><br>Definitely one of the better coffees in the area, without the crowds. Please leave me a seat ;)

text: It is my first visit to SG&#39;S biggest CBTL at Marine Cove yesterday, even though I have been to Marine Cove numerous times. The previous times that I visited Marine Cove were always for McDonald&#39;s (which I will cover in a separate review another day).<br><br>Badly needed caffeine and brunch yesterday afternoon, and didn&#39;t really want to have hawker food, so decided to come to Marine Cove - to get my caffeine fix and have my much-needed brunch at CBTL. Was lucky to find an empty table indoors (I need my AC! lol) as it can get pretty packed on Sunday afternoons.<br><br>This Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf outlet is definitely BIG! It can house 40 pax indoors easily; and outdoors, it can accommodate at least 20-25 pax. It offered the usual CBTL fare, and I had a pretty satisfactory Tuna Sandwich with my Latte -  the latte was alright, nothing spectacular.<br><br>What I really like about this new CBTL outlet is that they have a cosy ambience and nice decor (cool lamps), varied seating arrangements (sofa, normal height tables, tall tables etc) and best of all, they have a Children&#39;s corner where kids can play in while their parents sip their coffee/tea in peace. <br><br>I will definitely be back again soon because this is the nearest cafe for me in my vicinity which is so close to the beach.  And, I love the beach! Love going for my evening walks at the beach!

text: It has been a long time since I truly felt touched by honestly good food.  <br>The moment I bite into the Kale and Mushroom, the cacophony of flavours simply exploded in my mouth without warning. Sweet, spicy, tangy......how can this humble looking sandwich taste so fabulous? I could not suppress my excitement and wanted to find out what magic has gone into this sandwich. <br><br>&#34;It&#39;s Chilli flakes that we&#39;ve infused into the olive oil and that tang comes from the clots of lemon milk juice cream you see on top of the mushrooms.&#34; answered the owner Traveen in a slow-paced Norwegian accent. Chilli flakes and lemon milk juice? WOW. <br><br>This brilliant inspiration can only be found here at Smor, Singapore&#39;s first Scandinavian Deli that is opened by food enthusiast twin brothers Traveen and Tarun Gulrajani. They were so captivated by the concept of Smorrebrod (which means &#34;butter bread&#34;) during their 3-month tour of 12 Scandinavian cities that they decided to bring it to Singapore, elevating to an artisan level with quality ingredients all sources from Scandinavia. <br> <br>It is not only the quality ingredients that make this worth. Like the Kale and Mushroom, the Crunchy Bacon is piled onto buttery and crisp toasted brioche bread that doesn&#39;t turn claggy with the moisture of tomatoes. Topped with side eggs, wilted baby spinach and shavings of emmental cheese, this warm open-faced sandwich is a great breakfast choice that tickles one&#39;s fancy.  <br><br>These sandwiches worked amazingly better than most cold pleasure-less wraps as they are prepared fresh upon order. The warm versions easily gain the upper hands as our palates acclimatize to the heat but the cold sandwiches are seriously not bad either.  <br><br>Instead of mundane ingredients like cream cheese and capers, the Smoked Salmon has a lovely acidic-sweet kick coming from the horseradish and dill-infused sweet mustard dressing which I mistaken to be honey at first. <br><br>Some might find the Norwegian hand-peeled shrimps to be tad salty but if you factor in the tangy lemon mayonnaise and the sprinkles of chives, it&#39;s a simple, refreshing yet addictive combo.  These voluminous seafood filling are stacked onto gluten-free light rye bread is resilient enough to avoid saturation from the extra moisture, yet still soft enough that it doesn&#39;t wear out the muscles as you chow into it.  <br><br>This is probably also the only place in Singapore where you can discover a fair range of Scandinavian chocolate snacks, savoury produce like caviar or coffee. I bought the Jaffa Nougatine bar ($2.50), some really good milk wafers at only $2.50 and the Shuffle Toffee Biscuits, the sinful combination of snickers, Mars and Toackers that are worth the calories.  I have posted the Shuffle Toffee on my instagram here<br><br>Was it by chance that we managed to pick all four choices that were delicious? I seriously doubt so. Yes, the price of $6.90 for one sandwich, $12.90 for two and $17.90 for the Viking meal of three might seemed a little pricey or not satisfyingly sufficient for a meal. But trust me, a regular meal of two sandwiches are more than enough to fill you up. Moreover, if it&#39;s such a wholesome meal prepared with healthy ingredients, passion and sincerity, why not?  I seldom say that I will return to try the place but this I shall unabashedly say that a return is a must.

Italian restaurant in Fusionopolis popular for its set lunch (salad/soup, main (pasta, fish, etc.) and dessert. The food tastes ok / average - though generally the pasta is better than the fish / meat dishes. Pretty good value for money considering the portion

text: Dazzling Cafe is a well known chain from Taiwan, known for its toasts and mochi stuffed waffle. It has 2 outlets in Singapore. The cafe was beautifully decorated in fairytale look.<br><br>Cafe Latte (Single Shot) ($6++)<br>Topped up $1++ to Rainbow-nize the drink. The drink looked quite pretty but lacking of the coffee taste.<br><br>Lobster Cold Capellini ($27.90++)<br>Cold Capellini, marinated with extra virgin olive oil, sea salt, white pepper, chives, poached lobster tail in butter, mentaiko mayo, basil powder, salmon roe, micro herbs<br>I like that the mentaiko mayo was served separated so one can adjust the richness of the dish to one&#39;s liking. Rich and creamy while refreshing.<br><br>Chicken Cutlet with Honey Mustard ($19.90++)<br>Served with scrambled egg<br>Marinated chicken thigh breaded with bread crumbs, topped with scrambled egg and arugula<br>The scrambled egg was quite creamy while the chicken was juicy inside.<br><br>Pandan Gula Melaka Mini Toast ($11.90++)<br>Salted gula melaka ice cream, custard, condense milk, chocolate sauce, pandan crumble, crushed peanut, red current, strawberry, coffee wafer stick, kaya toast cubes <br>The crispy toast was quite yummy on its own. Although not as prettily decorated as the main sized version, but it tasted not bad and the serving was just nice for one to finish comfortably.<br><br>Overall the food was not bad although prices were on the high side. Service was a tab slow. One needed to ask a couple times for the iced water to be served.

text: It&#39;s always very underwhelming when a cafe puts too much emphasis on presentation and sacrifices taste. The cafe decor and food presentation looks great, but the waffles I ordered was rather average. I also ordered a cafe latte. Looked good, with nice milky foam and served with a caramelised biscuit. But again, the coffee itself was not good. The coffee aroma was  weak, so ended up tasting more milk than coffee. <br><br>This would be a good place to bring a date who is not a foodie, but very into cute places and trends. <br><br>Upon 5, I rated this place a 3 because:<br>-1 star for taste<br>-1 star for revisitability

Ambient is good, foods not bad, was quite impressed by the &#39;Scallop and Parma Ham&#39; presentation.<br><br>However, everything got turned down by the lousy service! A staff would rather clean the table instead of taking our order, we have been waiving our hands but no one could be bother to attend to us. Ice cream was served with no spoon, when we were trying to get one from the waiter who was walking pass us, he pretended did not notice and just walked away. <br><br>I always believe good foods matter, and good service matters more. Hope they will really look into this issue.

text: Unlike its other themed cafe counterparts, the Charlie Brown cafe actually provides GOOD (I repeat, not decent or average but ABOVE AVERAGE) food. Cutely adorned with Peanuts posters and statuettes, this restaurant is perfect for a get together with friends to chill &amp; reminisce about one&#39;s childhood. <br><br>The beef risotto is especially yummy; rice grains were perfectly infused with a savory tomato stock and the beef slices were the right degree of doneness with a pinkish core. The fried rice with wings had a pleasantly Asian flavor. When eaten with the garlic chili, each bite sure packed a punch! I would advise against ordering the crepes as they were rather pathetic both in appearance and taste. <br><br>To conclude, feel free to order the mains but get your dessert fix elsewhere.

text: i don&#39;t think you will go out of your way here for your caffeine fix.<br>but if you do visit kim keat palm for some of their ever so popular hawker fare then this coffee stall is worth a try.<br><br>there is a constant line forming and i can guarantee you 90% of them are regulars.<br>just stand in line and see aunty work her magic.<br>she glances up, prepares a cup or two, glances further down the line and prepares yet another few cups.<br><br>when her eyes caught mine, she asked for my order(because i am no regular:(), which i duly placed, and she preps my cup.<br>then her eyes moves beyond me, scanning the people in the queue behind me and preps their cups without any need to ask for their orders!<br><br>it&#39;s amazing how she remembers all the orders of her regulars and there are many.<br>just as i ponder, yet another regular walks up with an empty flask, places it on the counter and walks away sans communications.<br><br>my only reservations about this mute ordering system is for people who don&#39;t always drink the same drink. <br>i guess the onus is on you to voice out that non-regular order when her eyes catches yours?<br><br>come for a good, old fashion, traditional coffee that only requires coins, not notes!<br>come join the line and awaken to a new year 2019!

text: Our first time to try charlie brown and happy to say we are not disappointed! <br>I ordered beef lasagna and i love it. They did not get stingy with the sauce. Charlie&#39;s fried chicken is good too. The chicken is juicy. <br>We also ordered Charlie&#39;s combo(consist of fries, shanghai roll, chicken cheese balls, sausage? And fish fingers) it&#39;s great for sharing. <br>I suggest you avoid tomato risotto with grilled chicken (if your expecting strong flavour), its too bland. Its rice is cooked in tomato without a hint of seasoning. <br>If you are going to watch a movie after better inform them of your movies timing so they can tell you how long you need to wait for your order or if you need to go to another restaurant. Their price and waiting time is reasonable. Their staff can be more friendly but they are not that bad (smile and ask nicely)

text: The craze about snoopy has come back again and yes recently I had watched the Charlie Brown movie and it had kind of encourage me to visit their theme Cafe in Cineleisure after such a long long time. For those who are unaware, there are two Charlie Brown Cafes in Singapore and the other one is located in One KM Mall.<br><br>Charlie Brown Cafe in Cineleisure is located at 4th Storey in one corner. Be greeted by the simple and cool looking snoopy in its shades at the doors.<br><br>Hospitality from Charlie Brown Cafe is not too bad as you are greeted by snoopy and charlie brown with a menu in his sincere look.<br><br>In its theme cafe, you get to watch their cartoon programs from the television, plush on the sofa, and you can even enjoy kinds Charlie Brown related toys, stationery off their display shelf.<br><br>Snoopy and Charlie Brown! Take a Selfie Here!<br><br>If you notice, you will see Charlie Brown&#39;s face right at the doorstep on the cement screed flooring.<br><br>The best thing about chicken wings is that they have to be served hot, golden on the outside and juicy on the inside. The signature wings fit all of that.<br><br>Signature Charlie Wings - $10.80<br><br>Nothing beats my all time favourite choice of Pizza for I&#39;m an absolute Hawaiian Lover. Just right that their Hawaiian Pizza is one of their recommendations. Its thin crunchy crust was baked to perfect edges, charred and spreaded with juicyturkey hams, pineapple cubes on a tomato base mixed with mozzarella cheese. Yum Yum!<br><br>Hawaiian Pizza - $12.80<br><br>Crepe on the other hand was quite normal, folded with nutella chocolate wrapped inside and served with a scoopy of cookies &amp; cream ice cream.<br><br>Snoopy&#39;s Chocolate - $9.80<br>The crepe for this had snoopy drawn out of their chocolate powder. <br><br>Overall, it was quite entertaining dinning in a Theme Cafe like this. I don&#39;t mind coming back again for their mains.

text: As the old Cartoon / Comics used to say &#34;Oh dear, Charlie Brown&#34;. Oh dear indeed. <br>Having first opened at 313 Somerset, I&#39;ve constantly found myself looking at the menu, without ever being tha roughly impressed by it. <br><br>Today though, we had the chance to try the Cineleisure branch as they were the few places that were still opened, without being a fast food joint. <br><br>We decided to share a Charlie Brown Chicken Rice. Described as &#34;Best of Best!&#34; on their menu, the Charlie Brown Chicken Rice will get you gasping &#34;Oh Dear&#34; louder than &#34;Wow&#34;.<br><br>If this was their best of best (yes, it&#39;s already wrong grammatically), I would hate to try the rest of their food. <br><br>According to the description , it&#39;s a Juicy Grilled chicken leg, topped with a sunny side up egg and served with fragrant rice. <br>Now firstly, the egg&#39;s on the rice so it should technically be &#34;Grilled juicy chicken leg served with rice, topped with a sunny side up egg&#34; <br>English aside, if their deciding to change the menu, they could get ride of the Juicy Grilled in the description as well. <br>To describe this Chicken leg as juicy would be like describing Justin Beiber as the best singer / song writer in the world. <br><br>Here, in front of me, sat a big piece of chicken leg, that was so overcooked, the meat was flakey to the bone. If a piece of breast meat turned out a little dry, fine, it&#39;s a delicate piece of meat, but do they have any idea how long they have to cook a chicken thigh before it dries to the bone? With every cut of the knife, I was hoping it would get better as it reached the bone, but all I saw was flakey dry meat after flakey dry meat. <br><br>Secondly, the chicken cannot be grilled, seriously. Maybe it was grilled as you prepared for dinner service but upon ordering, it&#39;s clear that it&#39;s been nuked in the microwave and fried in a fryer. I&#39;ve had plenty of grilled chicken in the past, but never have I ever come across a chicken&#39;s skin that crispy, solely from a grill. <br><br>At $13.80, I could have gone down to KFC and gotten more satisfaction from a 3 piece meal......with change. <br><br>And the sunny side up egg? It was fried under such intense heat that the base became rubbery and the edges so crispy I could use it in Taohu Telor. <br><br>Charlie Brown should really start looking into raising the standards of food or this Cineisure Leisure outlet will leave everyone looking at an empty unit going &#34;Oh dear, Charlie Brown&#34;.

text: We had Lunch at Charlie Brown Cafe, Another theme cafe that serves value for money yummy food. They also cater to student meals at $6.90 and set lunches at $8.90 with top up for sides etc. Although they have no Peanuts decorated food. Food presentation definitely wasn&#39;t there at all. For the food, Would definitely come back again. Price wise value for money, not overpriced and affordable even without using the vouchers.  We had two Fave Vouchers which made it even better with drinks and lava cake dessert.

text: So I read the review and was interested in the French food without the crazy crowds.  It took me a few minutes to find the place in a mall called Cavanaugh Connect.<br><br>Instructions are order the food then find a place to sit.  I ordered a fish dish called Out Of The Blue which was made up of fried halibut and fries.  I did not see that they had coca-cola on the menu but they had it in a fridge.  So I ordered one.  I found a seat but I noticed that there were high back arm chairs but they were occupied.  At the ordering area there were a lot of various confectionaries and desserts to choose from.<br><br>It took about 12 mins for my food to arrive and I was guessing all of it was made fresh.  The fish was lightly breaded and tasted amazing. What made it were the fries which were twice fried.  The fries retained their crunchiness and taste even after 10 minutes.  A sign of the thoughtfulness of the food.  Only drawback was the price.  Maybe making the dish smaller and less expensive for lunch would be a better way to go.<br><br>I will definitely return but not too frequently.

text: Hidden gem in the quieter part of Orchard Road. The setting and ambience were a nice respite from the usual crowdedness of malls. I like the walk in concept where we get seated by ourselves and order directly at the counter. It&#39;s also easy to help ourselves to the jugs of warm and iced water. The big armchairs were very comfortable. My friend ordered mushroom pasta with cream and cheese while I had a set meal that came with soup of the day and ice cream. My main dish was crabby patty with truffle fries and mango salsa. The charcoal bun had the right amount of softness and the patty was flavorful. The truffle fries were addictive and the mango salsa was a refreshing touch! Thoroughly enjoyed the meal and the waitress had to tell us to leave because they were closing at 9:15pm. Haha.

4 Twinkle Stars indeed.   Was there early about 11:30am Wednesday so not that many people which is a goos thing.   Overall for food i got to say they do pay enough attention to its execution i.e Pasta - Al Dente ,  Fries Crispy , Coffee with Art . For 24 plus plus frankly is lot of food amd we struggle to stay away after the lunch as my usual lunch is a salad.   oh yes one more very important thing - the lunch set comes with ice cream even if u top up for a cuppacino just to be clear.   I did hiwever need to asl for it as the staff seem to have forgotten - i think :).

text: This isn&#39;t a regular Starbucks, but a Starbucks Reserve store, that means they have a different bar with a couple more coffees on offer. There are a couple more drink choices with a different menu. My favorites the Butterscotch Latte and the Shakerato affogato.<br><br>This store is constantly crowded ever since the PLQ mall opened, and it&#39;s hard to find a seat especially on weekends. <br><br>Yes, I know it&#39;s a Starbucks, so it&#39;s not exactly batch roasted craft coffee. But when you need a consistent caffeine (and/or sugar) hit, Starbucks is fine.<br><br>(P.S. It&#39;s takeout only now during the circuit breaker, and the reserve bar closes early at 9pm)

text: This Killiney Kopitiam is one of the closest location near my hotel, so I decide to come here to have breakfast before I start my first full day in Singapore.<br><br>Located inside Sim Lim Square, somewhere in Sim Lim Square, a six level building with a range of many varied electronic supply and service shops. On a weekday morning, the place is kind of quiet. As usual, as a tourist I circled around in circles for awhile before I could find my breakfast!<br><br>Coffee with condensed milk, kaya toast and soft boiled eggs are all A-OK.<br><br>I think I would just go to another Killiney&#39;s location instead of this particular one.. as I really hate getting lost in a maze of electric shops!

text: I was surprised to learn that all pastries and bread are produced in-house and they were well above the average cafe standards, if not pleasantly satisfying. I urged anyone to try the Blueberry Yoghurt Tart ($6.50), which is no flouncy haute tart but one of a silky-textured, gelatinous filling with hints of tart. Surrounded by a crumbly digestive fortress wall which caused a mess on a plate that anyone would be happy to clean up.<br><br>The Spicy Surimi Crab Sandwich ($8.50) was an unexpected triumph. Between two slices of warm, fluffy sesame brioche, generous heaps of shredded crab smothered in light mayonnaise were piled neatly on fresh lettuce. There isn&#39;t much of the spicy kick, but the tangy mayo juices kept us working through to the final crumb. <br><br>Instead of the Strawberries &amp; Custard ($5.800 that owned a slightly clumpy cream, the Chocolate Trio ($6.50) is one to order. Dominated by white chocolate and milk chocolate mousse, the cake did not fit quite into the concept of &#34;trio&#34; but it was unexpectedly lighter than it looked, with a superbly crunchy Feuilettine base that would appeal to anyone. <br><br>Served warm and fluffy, the Cinnamon Melt ($2.80) was less dense than most of the sugar laden American swirled brioches and filled with fresh crunchy walnuts. A pity that the icing frosting did not melt into a sticky gooey pool. There are plenty of lemon tarts but few is as delicious as the Tangy Lemon Tart ($4.80). There is a sweet tart vibe to the creamy filling within the crumbly shell, baked to a nice chocolate-brown shade. Definitely goes well with our matcha latte ($5.40)
The iced tea is pretty good here.  Nice place to sit and relax indoors from the heat.  Free wifi for the roaming challenged.
Another overpriced and not too great tasting sandwich place in this area. Avoid, although the service is surprisingly friendly.

text: Tucked away coffee shop in the Serangoon suburb.  All the locals hangout here on the weekend.  The chocolate, the cakes and the savouries are of superb quality.  They make a proper flatwhites which is hard to find in Singapore.  Service can get patchy as they get busy during the weekend.  They also showcase their decorating cakes which is very entertaining for children.  Recommended esp if you are in that area.

text: Another cafe tucked away in a neighborhood. Ambience is whimsical and nice. The decor is pretty sweet, especially the clear roof ceiling at the back of the cafe, the fairy lights and the adobe walls. Came here twice on a weekend night and a morning. There was already a crowd so we had to queue a little. Tried their breakfast menus as well as their deserts. Both were good, but nothing great in my books. Price is reasonable of course due to the quiet location.<br><br>I have to commend their staff, particularly a male staff wearing black frame glasses, couldn&#39;t get his name. Excellent service, always with a smile and cheery attitude! Also orders were quick.<br><br>Would definitely come back again, likely shooting for non-peak times again.<br>Not sure if we caught a one-off experience but the quick service was a plus.

text: Visited Wimbly Lu a couple of times has made me a fan of this place. <br><br>Love the carbonara with bacon, the creamy white sauce taste homemade, poached egg is well-cooked, spaghetti is Q, portion is just right. <br><br>Love the waffle with chocolate ice cream. The waffle may look simple and plain, but that&#39;s the beauty of it. It is perfectly crisp on the outside and soft and airy on the inside. Goes really well with a scoop of chocolate ice cream. One of the best waffle I&#39;ve ever had.<br><br>Love the hot chocolate (70% dark chocolate). Rich and creamy and taste like a bar of dark chocolate. <br> <br>Love the chicken nuggets. Crispy on the outside and juicy and tender on the inside. <br><br>Overall, service and ambience is good, menu is well categorized for easy ordering. Just hope that they show a list of food photos on the menu so that those who has not been there before, know what to expect and order from the menu.

text: Reasonably priced cafe food and great service. We ordered the following: waffles with salted caramel ice cream and maple syrup, truffle fries, banoffee pie and iced and hot honey lemon for beverages. My verdict: nothing worth mentioning except the banoffee pie was really good! text: Nice place with good interior decor. It&#39;s a nice rustic look. However, the long waiting queue and cramped up seating arrangements is a put off. It seemed as those as they are squeezing as many pax in the restaurant with little room of comfortable space. <br><br>Food wise, the waffles are really nice. But the rest of the desserts are unimpressionable.

text: Love the ambience. Drinks were well made, specially like the iced chocolate and mocha drink. <br><br>One of the staff was really friendly and nice. However, i find most of them pretty inexperienced. <br><br>They had 4 choices for &#39;soup of the day&#39; which really should be soups of the day. We had the mushroom soup and it was quite pleasant. Beef cottage pie was not available so we thought of going for more desserts since there was a rave about it here.<br><br>Waffle is a must; come early for it so that waiting time won&#39;t be long. When asked what was &#34;eton mess&#34;, the staff said &#34;choc cake&#34;, and what was &#34;blackout&#34;, she said &#34;choc cake&#34;. Could have been a little more specific and professional in this. In the end she recommended the blackout which was a total disappointment because it&#39;s just a very moist chocolate cake.<br><br>Price is on the high. For the service and the quantity of food (the $5 chicken nugget comes with literally 5 piece of chicken karaage), i will only return if i am seriously craving for waffles. Else, nah.

text: &#34;Just go for the desserts, skip the real food.&#34;<br><br>That&#39;s what I heard about Wimbly Lu. Well what happened was we had dinner at Fat Cat, and then we hopped over to Wimbly for desserts! A friend on Instagram also recommended their Orange Flour-less Cake, and someone said their Waffles are good. My neighbour told me about their molten lava cake and smores pie, which is then what we ordered. Chocolate overload!<br><br>The molten lava cake was not as sweet as I expected though, which is good. Still gave me a sugar high (ok perhaps it was the smores pie) but the chocolate quality is detectable to be better than average. With the smores pie, it is a layer of granola crushed bits, with a huge chunk of chocolate, and molten marshmellows. Super decadent. super sweet.<br><br>The place itself is very whimsical and nice. I really liked the decor, especially the ceiling fairy lights and the adobe walls. It was quite packed on a Sunday night as people lined up to sit for some coffee and desserts. The noise level is a bit high, but that&#39;s expected.

text: Reasonably priced cafe food and great service. We ordered the following: waffles with salted caramel ice cream and maple syrup, truffle fries, banoffee pie and iced and hot honey lemon for beverages. My verdict: nothing worth mentioning except the banoffee pie was really good! Not overly sweet with generous amount of banana and the digestive crust was nicely salted, so all together was  pleasant!

I heard good things, so I went... and ehhh I think it was all right.<br><br>First impressions are GREAT. It&#39;s a BEAUTIFUL shop - vintage VW Beetle out front, great shopfront, and stepping in, you see the dark brown brickwork, and the greenhouse-style roof at the back... it&#39;s pretty gorgeous.<br><br>Menu-wise one should remember that this is a chocolate shop. I wouldn&#39;t look at anything else, especially if the store itself says so. I&#39;ve had a friend rave about their spicy hot chocolate (and he&#39;s a dude, so it must be pretty good). I... liked it, but I didn&#39;t think it was all that.<br><br>The gang and I had a raft of other desserts too, and I was particularly looking forward to the clafoutis - cherries in a chocolate tart? Heck Yeah! When it came though... it was kinda thin and dry; perhaps their interpretation was a little different?<br><br>This spot gives me a &#34;style over substance&#34; feel, but when so many friends are in love with it, I&#39;ll have to give it another try. And hope they&#39;ve fixed the clafoutis.

I love this place, they make the most awesome desserts. Try their home made ice cream with waffles, it&#39;s probably as good as it gets anywhere else in Singapore. There&#39;s also a great ambience to chill out with friends.<br><br>However, on weekends, do note that if your party is small you may get shifted around as larger parties come in and they need you to give up your seat. Didn&#39;t happen to me but the waiter did give advance notice in case it happened.

text: Tucked away coffee shop in the Serangoon suburb.  All the locals hangout here on the weekend.  The chocolate, the cakes and the savouries are of superb quality.  They make a proper flatwhites which is hard to find in Singapore.  Service can get patchy as they get busy during the weekend.  They also showcase their decorating cakes which is very entertaining for children.  Recommended esp if you are in that area.

The interior reminded me of the castle of Edinburgh with the exposed brick walls and natural light from the ceiling. Very vintage and yet homey. There are little nooks and crannies to be explored such as the kids section under the stairs. I think it&#39;s the perfect corner to take off your inhibitions along with your shoes and sit cross legged on the mat. You can do that while enjoying a yummylicious dessert.<br><br>There&#39;s quite a selection of sweets but Wimbly Lu place quite a large emphasis on their chocolates. Caught sight of the Root Beer Float Cake, which has a slice of moist chocolate fudge cake soaked in root beer and ice cream and good ol&#39; choc fudge. It&#39;s a dessert in a dessert! I don&#39;t know why this didn&#39;t appear on my table but then again it&#39;s really lousy judgement on my part for letting S do the ordering. :P Heard that this is pretty awesome. I think it&#39;s only $6.50.<br><br>Skip the mains, go for desserts straight.

Located at Jalan Riang, Wimbly Lu was certainly a hard place to find for someone who did not know the area well. It is perhaps easier to identify their adorably vintage signature car parked outside which is quite hard to miss. I was brought there by a friend who had raved about the place and their waffles.<br><br>The place was not big but very cosy and comfortable, with quite a nice homely feel to it. We went there in the day but I was told by my friend that it was gorgeous at night with the lights and an open area so I would have to go again to witness it for myself. The staff were extremely pleasant with huge smiles and an ever-ready attitude, which made it a very delightful experience indeed. The happiness of the staff seemed to be rather infectious as it made me feel rather happy too despite the rain outside.<br><br>I ordered a chicken baked rice which seemed to be more of an eastern take on chicken baked rice, without the creaminess that most baked rice dishes have. In fact, there was no sauce, and it was simply a slightly sweet chicken and mushroom rice, reminiscent of claypot rice, baked with a layer of cheese that was likely some form of cream cheese instead of the usual cheddar or mozarella. Although it was not the best baked rice I&#39;ve had, it was quite an interesting take on chicken baked rice and went rather well together as a whole. We also had their famous waffles with cinnamon icecream, and though the ice-cream was far too grainy, the waffles were wonderfully fluffy on the outside and crispy on the inside.<br><br>With the stellar service I received and yummy waffles, I would be more than glad to go back again to verify if it is indeed as lovely as my friend had described at night.

text: I dropped by Wimbly Lu one evening with the parents as I was craving some sort of a chocolate cake. As I live around the area, wimbly lu was probably the closest cafe for me to get a nice cup of coffee and cake. I have heard raving reviews about the place from some friends who have been there a couple of times. My parents were familiar with the area so we found the cafe quite easily. However, I believe it might be pretty difficult for most people to get there by foot as it is located in the private housing estate quite a distance from the nearest MRT station (Serangoon MRT). <br><br>The cafe is easily identifiable by their signature red car parked outside. The decor of the place is lovely, and great attention is put into the display pieces and ornaments placed around. Walking in, antique looking shelves line the wall, giving the place a touch of vintage. The rustic red bricked wall on one side, coupled with the beautiful lighting gave the place a homely, yet romantic atmosphere. I had their Rootbeer cake, which essentially was a piece of dark chocolate cake infused with root beer, topped with a chocolate root beer syrup and served with vanilla ice-cream. The chocolate cake was alright, and I could taste the hint of root beer with each mouthful. However, the chocolate did not come through sufficiently, which was pretty disappointing as what can be worse in a chocolate cake than not tasting the chocolate. That said, the chocolate syrup was divine. The chocolate was thick, but not too heavy, and the root beer flavour combined with it brilliantly. The vanilla ice-cream was slightly icy, but otherwise went well with the cake. I also had a flat white, which was pretty good!<br><br>The service at Wimbly Lu was brilliant. The service staff were attentive and patient, answering my questions about their various desserts. <br><br>Overall, this cafe is a pretty awesome find and I will definitely be back to try more of their offerings (especially their waffles, which I heard is pretty good).

really good desserts at this small store in a surprisingly hipster part of serangoon - I live near the area and never knew this place even existed (except for all the posts floating about the blogosphere on this place and its cajun neighbour). I didn&#39;t really know what to expect, actually - I tried to come with tempered expectations in case it didn&#39;t actually live up to the hype - but came away liking it quite a bit.<br><br>it&#39;s a small space (so be prepared to wait), but gorgeously furnished in kitschy retrovintage furnishings and what I feel is rather old-school american - which also leads me to ask: have you also noticed that hipster places in singapore take on a vintage persona from history that never quite happened to us? I feel like this place could fit in fantastically in seattle, but here seems a little like an isolated microcosm of american fifties-style coffee shops.<br><br>and the food? pretty good, really. we had two waffles  - both of which came warm, crisp outside with soft insides. I think this ought to be a sure-order; it&#39;s a rather large portion as well. we also had a bread pudding - served with crème anglaise - as well as a still molten chocolate lava cake. I think the latter was more impressive - the chocolate was sufficiently dark<br><br>well-worth a return, and especially so after dinner at the fat cat.

text: Located near Paya Lebar MRT station, there is a cafe at the second level in this hotel, which most people do not know. It offers a daily lunch set from $8.90++. The set comes with a choice of main where one can select from a selection of 8 choices, a choice of soft drink and a dessert of the day.<br><br>Gyuniku Don<br>It is actually beef rice bowl. Tender, thinly sliced of beef with eggs simmered together in a sauce , topped on plain rice. It kind of remind me of Oyakodon (親子丼) - Japanese rice bowl dish, in which chicken, egg, sliced scallion, and other ingredients are all simmered together in a sauce and then served on top of a large bowl of rice.<br><br>The dessert of the day turns to be better than what I expects. It is a yummy mousse served with honey comb ice-cream with crumbles. It is delicious.<br><br>If that is not enough for you, topup $3.80 to help yourself to the soup and salad on the buffet counter. <br><br>Overall great service, great food and great deal to enjoy. Also can enjoy free wifi here!

text: Greyhound Cafe <br>Paragon<br>Singapore<br><br>My favourite cafe!<br><br>A queue at 12 noon on Saturday. <br><br>Chicken wings not as good as those in Bangkok.<br><br>Tom yam koong with large prawn which is better than river prawn at Ping&#39;s in Bangkok. Shame on you Ping&#39;s!<br><br>Fried rice with crab - very nice.<br><br>Thai iced milk tea - good, not overly sweet like in Bangkok.<br><br>Overall good but I think it costs a lot more than in Bangkok.

I went there with 2 other friends and shared the mushroom pad thai and vegetarian tom yum noodles. Total was $32 including gst. Prices are kind of high for regular thai food, but if you consider the location, and you see yourself surrounded by high-end luxury brand stores, I guess it&#39;s still reasonable orchard rd standard.<br><br>The pad thai is good, but the tom yum soup is a little too sour, too much lime added I assume. Overall, I&#39;m still very happy they have a vegetarian section in their menu! If you want to know why I didn&#39;t give them another star, it&#39;s because they don&#39;t provide tap water T.T (even though I told them I really don&#39;t mind). So remember to bring your own water or get ready to pay $3 for a bottle of water.

text: 1 of the Coffee Bean in town which is opened 24 hours.  I hope YELP can make the necessary changes needed for this location of The Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf.  When the Dining period is opened to the Public, as usual this location of Coffee Bean is packed to the brim.<br><br>Located inside a Hospital to begin with...  all in all, I have good experiences here.<br><br>May return when needed.<br><br>YES it is OPENED 24 hours..<br><br>Definitely GOOD in my books.<br><br>My favorite item is definitely the SPICY Chicken Puff.  From all the chocolate or mocha beverages to even purchasing the Pineapple Tart for Chinese New Year, I do not mind returning.<br><br>Added Bonus, to my acknowledgement, ALL locations of The Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf is Halal Certified by MUIS.  Overall 3.75 STARS!<br><br>As of P2HA, NO dining is allowed.  ONLY takeaways or to go orders plus, food deliveries options..  Hence plan accordingly.
