text: So what can one say about a coffee stall in a market.....Hmmmm......<br><br>It is located in a corner of Ghim Moh Hawker Centre.<br><br>It sells cold drinks that you can grab yourself from a fridge.<br><br>They also sell cigarettes up to a little more than S$12. OMG! How can anyone afford to smoke nowadays?<br><br>I spy lime juice with sour prunes.<br><br>Of course, there&#39;s the usual coffee (with condensed milk and sugar), coffee C (with evaporated milk), coffee black, coffee kow (thick), coffee pok (more diluted than usual).<br><br>Normally, I would just order coffee but everyone else likes coffee C. Surprisingly, I like their coffee C as the C taste is not too strong.<br><br>Best coffee in Ghim Moh Hawker Centre!

text: Ventured into this cafe by chance since the nearby Starbucks was packed. It wasn&#39;t crowded on Labor Day and they offer desserts/cakes and tea as well.<br><br>Their Pancakes and cakes are pretty good and they serves the pancakes on hot cast iron pans straight out from the oven. Mostly fruits toppings which my son likes. The servers there looks rather new and I can&#39;t really say if this place is recently opened.<br><br>The Mango pancake set we ordered came with a drink: coffee or tea can cost $15.80. A slice of their cakes cost around $7.80 so you be the judge. The Pink Rose buds tea we ordered came in a pot and they&#39;ll refill the hot water.<br><br>All in all.. a nice little place for rest your legs after some shopping, eat some sweet stuff and get going again.

text: The family celebrated Father&#39;s Day or perhaps Grandfather&#39;s Day without our usual Teochew fare but at a zichar stall very famous for its Bee Hoon. Of course, it&#39;s not the long-queue Sembawang Bee Hoon but the Chao Da Bee Hoon(Burnt Vermicelli). <br><br>Though we ordered the largest at $18, I felt it was not sufficient for 6 people as claimed. No wonder the boy who took my order said the large portion is not big and he could easily finish up the entire thing by himself.  Despite arriving early, the noodles took ages to be served but it was worth the wait. <br><br>With crispy bits of pork lard on top, the plate was gone within seconds. I did not have enough of it, and peeped over to look at nearby tables to check out the portions. It seemed that one could get more by ordering 3 small size at $6 each rather than 1 large one at $18.  <br><br>The Stir Bak Choy,  ($10) with crispy whole dried shrimps was not a boring at all. The greens were not loaded with MSG, though it was not very healthy with that golden pork lard that I happily mistook as dried shrimps several times. Not a bad mistake I guess.  <br><br>But with only 5-6 deep battered prawns at $20, skip this mediocre and overpriced Salad Cream Prawns to save your wallet a hole.<br><br>Another dish which we would not order again is the Thai Pig Trotters ($22). We could not figure what exactly was very Thai about this except maybe the sauce, which was just plain sweet and nothing else. The meat was tender but the crackling was not as super crunchy as Simpang Bedok&#39;s version.  <br> <br>But the Thai Hot and Sour soup or put it simply Tom Yam soup ($7) was very shiok! (perhaps better than many Thai restaurants). But the use of coconut milk and curry powder inside the soup did not find resonate with Old Ma, who still prefers the one at Seafood International. Well, try it and be your own judge.  <br><br>The Seafood Beancurd ($14) is napped in a sauce of light brown hue, topped with fish slices, sweet green peas and cuttlefish. The egg tofu encrusted in a brown case was more colorful than plain silky tofu. <br><br>The Salt-steamed chicken ($12) was very much loved by the elderly. Marinated with chicken wine and steamed with ginger, strips of black fungus and wolfberries, the chicken pieces were not exactly smooth but penetrated with flavours. Not sure if the plate was brimming with collagen or chicken oil, but it must be some good chicken essence.  <br><br>In short, the food here does not come cheap to me, but some dishes are indeed worth coming back again. Parking is an extreme hassle and avoid coming here on empty stomachs as waiting time might stretch a little. Best dish of the day? Definitely the Chao Da Bee Hoon:)

text: Came here with a super motley crew - two tables worth of us met of a mega hazy night to feast... And feast we did. We ordered with our eyes (which typically, and true to form, were wayyyyy bigger than our bellies), and couldn&#39;t finish a single dish, even though they were all delicious.<br><br>Signature Chao Ta Bee Hoon, a crispy pancake of... Bee Hoon, was tasty ad certainly fun to eat, but matched with/against a very tasty fried rice? We struggled valiantly, and almost finished them both. The prawn paste chicken was tasty too, as was the hae chor, but the omelette was more greasy than tasty, so that paste longer than most things. The pork knuckle they didn&#39;t do justice to - overfried and over seasoned, it fared the worst on our table, and we had to send it over to our friends&#39; table for assistance.<br><br>Bill comes, an for the amount of food that kept coming and coming ad coming, I was surprised to see us pay only about $20 a head. Decent, but next time I come, I&#39;m ordering judiciously. My gym trainer will not approve anything else.

text: This tze-char is famous for their chao-ta beehoon. The beehoon is fried to resemble a crispy pancake on one side. Very pretty!<br><br>We tried a couple more items and they are all good. <br><br>The pork knuckle is beautifully crisp on the outside and succulent inside. The skin crackles and they serve it with a tangy sauce, thus called Thai Pork Knuckle. The meat is good enough on its own that I didn&#39;t even dip the sauce. But my companions all enjoyed the dip.<br><br>Prawn rolls (Heh-chor)  were very good. Soft inside and very flavorful.<br><br>Seafood homemade beancurd - very soft and topped with some random seafood. The beancurd is very soft, almost like soya beancurd.<br><br>Note: Can&#39;t remember what else we had, but we enjoyed our dinner. One of the better tze-char around.<br><br>Parking can be hellish since it is Little India with lots of construction. The place is exactly across the street from the Wanderlust Hotel.

Be sure to come at off-peak hours, especially if you are in a big group - our group of 8 was lucky enough to snag a seat after 10 minutes, but otherwise seating is rather limited in this small coffee shop. <br><br>Yong Kee Seafood restuaurant is famous for its traditional chao tar bee hoon, and boy did it not dissapoint. The burnt bee hoon was served rather like a giant omelette, coated with a mix of egg and crispy rice flour coating the vermicelli to give it a delectable crispy flavour. Definitely the restaurant&#39;s signature dish. Also of note was the fish head curry, which, while not overtly spicy, was just the right amount of tantalizing. I did feel, however, that the fish was slightly over cooked, and the dish could do with more sauce (or &#34;zup&#34;), as many love to drench their rice in curry. Our group also ordered a fish soup, prawn paste chicken as well as prawn dish, all of which tasted rather average. Portions were also kind of small for the price we paid (about $12 per pax). <br><br>All in all, it&#39;s worth checking out if you&#39;re in the area or after a long day of IT shopping at the nearby Sim Lim towers. Order a large chao tar bee hoon and save your calories for worthier delicacies!

text: Always great food, even after many years.  Value is good too.  Pork trotter and prawn salad are our favorites.
The best red velvet cake in Singapore! Glad I grabbed the last slice before the store closed. Can&#39;t wait to try their other cakes. Auntie at the shop was also very nice.

Ok i admit i am a little hook with their kueh salat especially.  Also tried almost all of their offerings.  I got to say overall the cakes are very nice.  Things are certainly more expensive but really u pay for what u get.  The only thing i would hope for the counter staff should be a little patient and not be too pushy to get the order in.  Do a little bit more of a soft-sell and guide the customer to a selection instead of &#34;come on! Make up your xxxx mind as i got a lot of customer to serve!&#34; and in reality there were no one waiting.

text: I wish i had a faster metabolism. It&#39;s not fair. <br><br>Everything looks sooo good! There are so many things I want to taste here but haven&#39;t yet because I need to fit into my bridesmaid dress in 2 months and I have to pace myself. <br><br>Provence is famous for their fluffy wassants. Yes, they&#39;re soft and fluffy, but I personally think they kinda lack in flavor? They just tasted like soft plain bread to me. <br><br>The milk pan, though, was another story. Yummmm milk pan!! The softness, light fragrance, and creamy custard fillings.. one milk pan is really not enough!<br><br>Even if you&#39;re watching your figure, go get their milk pans! <br><br>Note: i think the address listed on yelp is the old address, they&#39;ve recently re-opened at raffles holland v.

Matcha cream bun ($2) - 3.5 stars<br>Filled with a matcha cream and some red beans. Not too sweet and it&#39;s pretty soft and fluffy. The matcha flavour was evident but, for better or for worse, it barely had the bittersweet flavour characteristic of matcha. I&#39;m not blown away but I&#39;d get it in a pinch.

text: Provence is a cute little bakery in Holland Village. Although it&#39;s a French name, it&#39;s a Japanese inspired bakery with lots of interesting kinds of bread here. <br><br>The best thing is the wassants here. Its so amazing. They are like tiny little crossaints but a completely different taste and flavor. Its soft, sweet and light and they have custard or chocolate flavor. Hard to explain unless you try it, but its very very good. <br><br>I also like their prepared sandwiches here. You can come and sit at the café and they also have a nice balcony area where you can grab a cup of coffee and watch Holland Village go by.

text: So here is the problem I have with coffee in Sigapore. Ask for an espresso which comes in a cup for a long black or cappuccino. So of course it hardly lines the bottom and goes cold fast. The coffee it&#39;s self was not too bad and at $2.80 what do you expect.  This place looks cool and has potential. There is however nothing French at all about it as the name may mistakenly lead you to expect. Nice vie form 2nd floor was the highlight and a nice place to read. Shame. I left . Dissapointed. Not the worst place so I gave it a 2nd star but that is all.

Bread Talk and its many clones have desensitised Singaporeans to what a bakery can look like, and while I&#39;m not claiming that Provence is the standard to live up to, they sure have it nailed.<br><br>The place reminds you of the countryside, with its brown baskets and tables. The variety of bread displayed is also unlike the plethora of floss buns and cream sticks or whatever we&#39;ve become so used to seeing. <br><br>My favourite is definitely the wassants: light, fluffy, and best of all, cheap! It&#39;s very tempting to just buy a dozen of those and gobble them up.<br><br>I&#39;ve never tried the drinks from their cafe, but am making it a point to do so soon.

Provence is what a bakery should be - the moment you step in, the aroma fills you with joy, the bread await you with golden smiles and your brain goes &#34;Bread is healthy right? What diet?! Wha..&#34;... Tadaaa! You decide to live in the shop forever. <br><br>Okay, I exaggerate. But Provence - a Japanese-styled bakery with an apparently French name, does hand-made bread very well. The fluffy ones are soft and fluffy, the sweet ones are melt-in-your-mouth. <br><br>My favourites include:<br><br>- Brazilian Cheese Bun - This small and round unassuming bun is *toing*toing* chewy and fragrant with every bite.<br>- Cinnamon Bun - I wish this was a sofa, so I can lie in the warm and sugary sweetness of it all. There is NO resisting this bun.<br>- Custard Bun - My colleague&#39;s mom buy these in bulk. The custard is full and oh-so-smoooooth.<br><br>Provence is much NOMS. I particularly like this outlet, there&#39;s a homely cozy feel to its décor, perhaps I should sit down one day to have a cuppa.

The one thing I really enjoy from this Japanese Bakery would be their Pizza bread -  basically your regular margherita pizza without the basil but with more Japanese flavor infused like Japanese mayo and cream cheese. If you&#39;ve had Japanese mayo or Japanese bread with the egg mayo like stuffing, you will know what I am talking about. The mayo is rich but not overpowering like the western mayo. The prepacked sandwiches here are also one of the best I&#39;ve had in Singapore. The ridiculously priced prepacked sandwiches at 7-11 should be replaced by these!

Their wassants (baby croissant-shaped buns, in plain and chocolate) were once all the rage and would sell out in a blink of an eye. They&#39;re a lot more available now, but why bother when there are so many other tasty things to eat? I really like their milk buns (rich custardy filling) and orange bun. There is also a selection of sandwiches and hot food (though I&#39;ve only had breakfast) for you to nom on site too.

It doesn&#39;t get any more Japanese than this. Provence, a unique Japanese style bakery and cafe replicates with ease the same look and feel you get when you&#39;re on holiday in Japan. Bread is a big thing in Japan, and they&#39;ve adopted the same mentality when it comes to baking their bread here as well. Each piece of bread is handmade from scratch and the quality has not dipped before. It has remained constant over the years since I first had it. Even with the opening of Maison Kayser and Paul, Provence still manages to hold its own against these two bread heavyweights.

text: Provence has become more well-known in recent years, with more branches in Vivo City and in Orchard, but nothing beats the Provence at Holland Village. As a small shop on its own, it allows customers to sit in and consume their breads while being able to enjoy the general peace and quiet that graces Holland Village most of the time in the day. With a welcoming setting that is both brunch-or-snack-friendly, diners can enjoy their coffee or morning chat where the smell of bread helps put one on the right track to start the day. Highly recommended: Black sesame pizza($2.20) and Milk Pan($1.50). The black sesame pizza is bursting with tomato sauce and mayonnaise, and the pizza delicious enough to make you want to throw your diet plans out the window. The Milk Pan is full of cream, and if you fancy milky food, this will be a hit with you. There are many other delights that I have not yet tried, but which seem equally appetizing. Drop by during opening hours: Mon-Fri 9.30am-8.30pm, Sat-Sun 8.30am-8.30pm.

If I&#39;m at shunfu and craving something sweet, I&#39;ll head to this place for my Western chocolate dessert fix. I had the cheescake brownie...ooohhh yeaaaaa...that&#39;s some good stuff! And I believe for about S$3 and I had a chocolate muffin for about S$1. Good prices, good variety of muffins and also very tasty! I&#39;m so sick of the uber sweet muffins and cupcakes back in America, which is why I love the taste of Western desserts made here in Asia, not even just in Singapore. Less sweet but still a good impact of flavor.<br><br>I have definitely seen long queues here but I tend to come to Shunfu on weekday mornings when I&#39;m off work, and no queues. Deliciously cheap baked sweets at Shunfu guys!

text: The muffins here are big and nice. Appearance wise they are not very attractive but don&#39;t let it put you off. I had the chocolate chip muffins. The top is filled with chocolate rice and the bottom is filled with chocolate chips which I prefer. The muffins have a homely feel, like what you would find at the place of a friend who loves baking. Good option for the health-conscious as the taste is not too oily/greasy.

This is supposed to be the best of all Chocolat N Spice since I heard that Shunfu mart is the original place for this bakery. However I am met with disappointment. The double chocolate muffin is so-so. Chocolate chip muffin was a little cold, while the best of all is definitely the Banana walnut muffin, with chunky bananas inside.<br>Don&#39;t think this is a place you should specially drop by to try but if its on the way, sure.<br><br>I sure hope that their standards will live up to their reviews here, and not be diluted because of its many stores now.

text: I was at shunfu market one morning when I noticed a long queue at one of the stalls. I approached the stall to take a look at their offerings and saw a nice display of pretty looking cakes. I got in line, not knowing what to get but found out from one of the ladies in line that they were famous for their muffins. <br><br>With muffins of a price range of $1.20-$1.40, it is probably one of the cheapest ones available in Singapore. The aroma was pretty enticing so I tried their mocha muffin. I also got their blueberry cheesecake.<br><br>I don&#39;t think the long queue is a good representation of the quality of their food. The mocha muffin was mediocre as there wasn&#39;t a good coffee flavour. It sort of just tasted like &#34;rotiboy&#34; coffee buns. The cheesecake was disappointing. The cream cheese had a powdery, slightly dry texture and the base was a vanilla sponge instead of the usual biscuit base. The sponge did not go very well with the cheese and made it taste more like a vanilla cream cake then a cheese cake. <br><br>Overall, they do not do great cakes, but for $1+ for a muffin and $3.40 for a slice of cheesecake, I guess you can&#39;t be asking for too much.

Great assortment of tasty muffins! I used to go to the market for char kway teow (also highly recommended!) when this store popped up. The store owner was really friendly and the muffins were really good.

text: Over the course of several days in Singapore recently I was on a quest to get a hold of the best ice cream in town. After a bit of research, I narrowed my options down to:<br><br>Apiary<br>Creamier<br>Lickety<br><br>Time for a heads up review.<br><br>Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?<br><br>All three of these spots have comparable atmospheres, with Creamier coming out on top, Apiary being a great neutral iteration of a contemporary ice cream shop, and Lickety being maybe the weakest of the three just by a smidge in that they don&#39;t accept credit cards, which was frustrating. <br><br>Apiary: Star (1)<br>Creamier: Star (1)<br>Lickety: Star (1)<br><br>Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?<br><br>Prices are comparable across the board at each of these shops. Apiary was the priciest at $7.50 for two smallish scoops, Lickety was $4.50 for a single scoop, and Creamier was $3.80 for a single scoop. Good pricing.<br><br>Apiary: Star (2)<br>Creamier: Star (2)<br>Lickety: Star (2)<br><br>Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?<br><br>When it came to flavor and consistency, there was a clear winner here in Creamier, which had a fantastically smooth, creamy, and flavorful Salted Caramel. Lickety and Apiary were both good, but Apiary, the weakest of the three, was over frozen whereas Apiary was good but not great. <br><br>Apiary: Single Star (3)<br>Creamier: Two Stars (4)<br>Lickety: Single Star (3)<br><br>Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?<br><br>Maybe surprisingly, I wouldn&#39;t be excited to come back to any of these ice cream spots, but maybe that&#39;s because I&#39;m simply so spoiled by the stacked Los Angeles ice cream scene. <br><br>Apiary: No Star (3)<br>Creamier: No Star (4)<br>Lickety: No Star (3)

Triple with a cone!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Triple with a cone!'}]
text: One of the top two ice cream places in Singapore I&#39;ve been to so far. The texture of the ice cream is how ice cream should be IMO - dense with strong flavours.<br><br>The Apiary - 4.75 stars<br>My favourite flavour of the three we got. The subtle honey fragrance was interesting <br><br>Pistachio - 4.25 stars<br>The pistachio flavour was rich and not artificial. The best pistachio ice cream I&#39;ve had. But for me pistachio is still a gelato flavour and I like the dense stickiness of good pistachio gelato.<br><br>Caramelised strawberry - 4.5 stars<br>Tastes pretty much just like Haagen-Dazs strawberry, which I think is excellent. I couldn&#39;t taste the &#34;caramelised&#34; bit though, and it wasn&#39;t as unique as say the apiary or the morello cherry sorbet.<br><br>Morello cherry sorbet - 4.75 stars<br>We sampled this and I really liked it but it didn&#39;t go well with the other flavours we picked so we passed. I&#39;d definitely get it another time.<br><br>Whiskey pecan - 4.25 stars<br>Sampled this as well. They used just the right amount of whiskey! Unfortunately I was a little sick of pecan since we had a tray of pecan sticky buns the other day.<br><br>Service - 5 stars<br>The line takes a little while because they&#39;re so generous with letting you sample flavours. Thank you!<br><br>I&#39;ll have to come back earlier in the day to try their caffeinated flavours and waffles.

What a great little ice cream spot! I went here with my friend who is a chef because of the never before experienced flavors they have. Honestly I can&#39;t remember the name of the flavors but I remember choosing two I had never heard of. One was black!... and it was awesome. The price was decent as well. The place is tiny so going with a large group might not be possible. I&#39;d definitely come back and recommend it for folks chasing new flavors. Singapore has got it all dude!<br><br>Not so humbly submitted,<br>Michael C.

text: fantastic uniquely flavored ice cream in singapore. perfect for a hot hot day! apiary is a bit hidden and only recognized by a little sign. <br><br>i&#39;m not a huge fan of ice cream in the states because they&#39;re too sweet and sticky -- even the gourmet ones. what i liked about apiary is that they keep the unique flavors but with LESS sugar so that you&#39;re not overwhelmed with sweetness. <br><br>small space but comfortable for groups of 4 or less.

text: It was either here or on Google that I read that the black sesame and the blue pea milk are a must...and yes, hands down - love! I think I&#39;ll have to come back tomorrow night to try the other flavors since I only ordered those two flavors.<br><br>Rich flavors, and not overly sweet...amazing!

We came here one evening after dinner and were amazed at how many people were getting ice cream on a Friday night. I would have thought bars would be a much more popular destination. Nevertheless, we managed to snag a table just as a group was leaving so, lucky us!<br><br>We ordered a waffle with 3 scoops of ice cream to share. While I did not love the waffle, my friends did - I like my waffles crisp and light all the way through. This was a little dense and slightly undercooked in the middle which made it feel chewier and more substantial.<br><br>What I really enjoyed were the ice-creams! We got Pistachio, The Apiary, and dark chocolate. They were a little on the sweet side, but what is dessert without sugar anyway? My favorite was definitely the Apiary - it had a milk base with honey and vanilla, and also honeycomb. Yum on all counts!! The pistachio was fragrant but a little too sweet for me. The dark chocolate was heaven but I&#39;m not a huge chocolate person.<br><br>I would go back to try their black and white sesame ice creams. Yum yum.

text: Craving for some dessert after your dinner around outram area? Scout out this gem amongst the shady looking bars along Neil road! <br><br>I love that apiary has many craft flavors and they rotate often. My favorite is definitely black sesame, featured in my post. Not too sweet, just the right amount to end the night. It was pretty funny that the cone was sweeter than black sesame when I tried it another time, so that&#39;s probably not a combi you&#39;d want. Other interesting flavors are uji matcha, blue milk, Ferraro roche. <br><br>In general, apiary ice cream is the smooth kind. So if you like more texture in your ice cream, they have very few flavors with nuts and crunch added. <br><br>There are some tables around for you to enjoy your dessert and hang out with friends. Probably enough to fit 15 or so people so it does get a little crowded on weekends. <br><br>Bring your cash or nets. No credit cards accepted here!

text: Seriously, this place has the most amazing ice cream. Move aside, Island creamery! I haven&#39;t raved about ice cream in a long time. They also serve ice cream with waffles. Waffles are light and fluffy and freshly made. The flavors are very intense, robust, not too sweet yet creamy. You can really taste the actual flavor in the ice cream!!! And it packs a punch! <br><br>It was so good I had it after lunch and after dinner on the same day. Trust me, you won&#39;t be disappointed. <br><br>Flavors I tried that was incredible : pistachio( my favorite!) Ferrero Roche, black sesame, strawberry ( they roast the strawberries before making it for the intense fresh strawberry flavor)! And oh yes, speculoos cheesecake!!! <br><br>Coupled with the clean environment and friendly staff, this is 5 stars without a doubt.

In a cacophonous city where noise assaults you from every angle and people bumping into you unapologetically, one constant and likely thought that most introverts harbor in their mind is whether there is a quiet corner to take shelter.<br><br>This Starbucks seems to be that place. The decor is Victorian nestled in a  Hoity Toity neighborhood away from the typical Breadtalk group infested malls. If you climb up to the second level, find yourself a corner the bothersome city and time-sensitive to-dos seems to melt away as you sip on your favourite Starbucks beverage (Mine&#39;s Hot Green Tea Latte). <br><br>Today I met up with a friend here. We chose this place because it was quiet. I could sense there was a lot of weight on his shoulders and he wanted a listening ear. <br><br>In the bid to forget about my tragic love life, I tend to lose myself to work and slowly drift away from friends. But 2015 seems to have sparked a little something in me at least to be a better friend especially for those who have been there for me through my ups and (lotsa) downs. He is one of them. <br><br>It has been a couple of months since i last saw him. He looked better physically, in the midst of going through a physical transformation. The geeky muscle type, one that will drive more than a few hearts aflutter. In a way he reminds me of him.<br><br>He started about how he found love in the past 3 months in an unlikely place. And they have been progressing well getting to know each other better until he found out that this new love of his has a God sister who is overly possessive. She has been making my friend&#39;s life difficult mostly with negative opinions of the relationship as well as cannibalizing his time so the 2 lovebirds can&#39;t meet as much with what little time both of them have.<br><br>I experienced the emotions that my friend poured out as I slowly sipped on my latte. Indignant at the difficulties he had to fight through and catching the happyness as he describes the lovely things they do together and feeling sorry as he blames himself for the turbulence in his love life.  <br><br>I wanted to help in a more substantial manner beyond just listening to his relationship woes but realized that there is nothing much I can do beyond giving him a listening ear. And in times like this. That&#39;s all that is needed.
Venti soy green tea latte ($8.10)<br><br>Ran out of toilet paper, some power outlets don&#39;t work, and gets crowded, but overall a pretty nice place to study.

This is my two hundredth review, so we&#39;re going to be all dramatic and have pretty LIBERAL USE of FULL CAPS.<br><br>A friend once commented that I use full caps in every review I write, and looking back, that&#39;s basically true.<br><br>Amidst the LUSH greenery of the Rochester area... okay before I go further I have no idea why I typed lush in full caps. It was kinda superfluous wasn&#39;t it. It&#39;s not like the greenery there is all Botanic Gardens or Bukit Timah Nature Reserve or anything. Definitely didn&#39;t need the cap lock.<br><br>So amidst the not-so-lush but definitely not sparse vegetation of the Rochester area, is THE nicest Starbucks in Singapore. I believe the one at the Delphi Orchard comes in second, though I will note that I have yet to experience the special Starbucks store near Fullerton. The one that&#39;s billed as the 100th Starbucks store in Singapore or something like that? Anyway. This Starbucks. Is. NAAAAAIIIIISEEEEEE. It&#39;s like got this colonial aura thing going on with the white wooden and black trim. Even though it&#39;s pretty near various schools it&#39;s generally not too crowded when you head over in the afternoon, and it&#39;s got everything you expect a Starbucks to have.<br><br>You have your coffee bagels Wifi overly-sweet-desserty-things students-studying couples-canoodling middle-aged expat working on a laptop... it&#39;s EVERYTHING YOU LOVE ABOUT STARBUCKS but somewhere NICE. and AIRY. AND OPEN. <br><br>What&#39;s there not to like! <br>The only thing I don&#39;t get is why they don&#39;t open 24 hours or at least till late. It&#39;s got this great location. I&#39;d DRIVE there to chill (much like what people do for the Holland Village branch)... SO WHY THEY KEEP CHASING ME OUT SO EARLY. :(<br><br>#YUdunwanmymoney

Probably my favourite Starbucks branch in Singapore for now (until I check out the one at Marina Bay, maybe). Was here on a sunday afternoon in search of a place to do some studying and this fit the bill! (Apparently the sound of a cafe enhances productivity... there&#39;s even a website somewhere that simulates that for those who can&#39;t actually be bothered to make the journey.<br><br>Be warned: this place is PACKED on a sunday afternoon, with people studying. <br><br>Drinks-wise... it&#39;s Starbucks, how different do you expect it to be?

text: What sets this Starbucks cafe apart from other coffee joints? It&#39;s housed in a grand old dame of a colonial house. It feels more relaxed than cafes in the malls downtown - more like you&#39;re hanging out at a close friend&#39;s place.<br><br>This cafe is just 10 minutes away from Bouna Vista MRT station. I headed there to study with some classmates for our final exams one evening last year when it was newly opened. We quickly realised that it is a nice place to hang out at night. There are ample seats littered all around the cafe, so we had no issues getting chairs and a table. And besides coffee and the usual spread of cakes and sandwiches, this branch also serves entrees like pumpkin soup and pastas too! However, we dropped by after dinner and were too full to try those out. We just ordered hot chocolate and java to help us stay awake while we mugged. <br><br> Guess what? It closes at 11.30pm, so it&#39;s another cool chill-out option for the owls.

Service has much room for improvement. <br><br>That said, the layout of the place is exquisite and very well done. A great place to relax (partially owing to the fact that this branch is not as crowded as the others around Singapore) and catch up with friends. <br><br>That being said, the baristas here were not very attentive and got my order wrong TWICE - even after I expressed my dissatisfaction at the first mistake.

text: I really enjoy reading with a coffee in hand at the local starbucks where I know I can get a good frapp. I was really disappointed with the Starbucks at Rochester Park, Singapore - it&#39;s really dirty. The cups aren&#39;t taken away when people leave and there are coffee stains on the white walls. It&#39;s such a shame since the area is quiet and there is a great man-made waterfall located right next to the Starbucks.

This is by far my favourite Starbucks in Singapore.<br> <br>Its undeniable that the building looks stunning- colonial house in an unobtrusive shade of white, red roof, outdoor patio and their signature classy wooden chairs and tables. The store is large, spacious, the tables are far apart, and couches are aplenty on the upper level. Perhaps because its located in a fairly inaccessible area, I&#39;ve hardly ever had any problems finding a seat in the restaurant (though a seat with a power point would be more difficult). The most crowded I&#39;ve seen it is usually on Saturday afternoons, which happens to also have the most interesting mix of people- parents drilling children with assessments, couples, students, sometimes even tourists who happen to be in the area.<br><br>My favourite place to sit would be at the outdoors patio on level two. They have to rows of tables, one running closer to the railing and the other parallel to the glass partitioning the indoor area. Even though it does get abit hot closer to the railing, I prefer to sit there because sometimes its nice to take it abit of sun and it doesn&#39;t feel as claustrophobic as having to awkwardly lean against the glass. Since most people opt for the couches, its also almost always possible to get a seat in the area.<br><br>Drinks wise, the standard is not so superior/inferior that it becomes possible for me to identify Starbucks branches by the drinks they make. So I would say its pretty average. During their busier hours, service can get a little tardy, especially on the upper floor. Don&#39;t be too surprised if you have to clean after the person before you in order to make some space for yourself.

text: Located in a refurbished colonial house in the Rochester Park area stands a quiet and modern chic outpost of Starbucks. The location is spot on, the surrounding greenery gives the outlet a sense of serenity and the outdoors, and thanks to the area not being so forested, you don&#39;t have to worry about mosquitos even if you&#39;re seated outside. You can either choose to sit upstairs on the balcony or outside in the al fresco areas, but do note that it is a non-smoking joint. Smokers will just have to get up if they want to do so. <br>Starbucks Rochester is also one of the few outlets in Singapore that not only offers coffee, but food like soups, pastas, sandwiches and lasagna as well. The baristas that I&#39;ve seen so far seem to be the crème of the crop as the drinks and coffee art generally look and taste much better, compared to other outlets.<br>Getting there is easy as it is just a 2min walk from Buona Vista MRT and if you drive, there&#39;s ample parking in the public carpark just a minute away. You can park along the road next to Starbucks, as there no markings on the road, but recently, they&#39;ve placed some cones there, so park at your own risk!

beautiful space, friendly staff, and none of that hipster business attached to getting my drink. <br><br>and no pesky students hogging tables (this was Wednesday lunchtime). all win. <br><br>p.s. an earl grey soy latte is almost embarrassingly hippie, but delicious (especially cold).

The store is large, spacious, the tables are far apart, and couches are aplenty on the upper level. Perhaps because its located in a fairly inaccessible area, I&#39;ve hardly ever had any problems finding a seat in the restaurant (though a seat with a power point would be more difficult). The most crowded I&#39;ve seen it is usually on Saturday afternoons, which happens to also have the most interesting mix of people- parents drilling children with assessments, couples, students, sometimes even tourists who happen to be in the area.<br><br>My favourite place to sit would be at the outdoors patio on level two. They have to rows of tables, one running closer to the railing and the other parallel to the glass partitioning the indoor area. Even though it does get abit hot closer to the railing, I prefer to sit there because sometimes its nice to take it abit of sun and it doesn&#39;t feel as claustrophobic as having to awkwardly lean against the glass. Since most people opt for the couches, its also almost always possible to get a seat in the area.<br><br>Drinks wise, the standard is not so superior/inferior that it becomes possible for me to identify Starbucks branches by the drinks they make. So I would say its pretty average. During their busier hours, service can get a little tardy, especially on the upper floor. Don&#39;t be too surprised if you have to clean after the person before you in order to make some space for yourself.

I am not a huge fan of American coffee especially coffee that comes in small, medium, large. Besides the good location, Starbucks is not usually where I would like to have my coffee considering the fact that it is pretty expensive as well. This outlet at Rochester is peaceful which is great for catching up on work or for having a quiet conversation over the weekend. There are 2 floors including alfresco seating so there is plenty of space. The only drink that you can find at Starbucks that is unique would probably be their green tea latte. Although on the sweet side, this drink can be quite a treat and a good alternative to hot chocolate. Overall its the location that makes this Starbucks stand out, nothing more!

text: Located in a refurbished colonial house in the Rochester Park area stands a quiet and modern chic outpost of Starbucks. The location is spot on, the surrounding greenery gives the outlet a sense of serenity and the outdoors, and thanks to the area not being so forested, you don&#39;t have to worry about mosquitos even if you&#39;re seated outside. You can either choose to sit upstairs on the balcony or outside in the al fresco areas, but do note that it is a non-smoking joint. Smokers will just have to get up if they want to do so. <br>Starbucks Rochester is also one of the few outlets in Singapore that not only offers coffee, but food like soups, pastas, sandwiches and lasagna as well. The baristas that I&#39;ve seen so far seem to be the crème of the crop as the drinks and coffee art generally look and taste much better, compared to other outlets.<br>Getting there is easy as it is just a 2min walk from Buona Vista MRT and if you drive, there&#39;s ample parking in the public carpark just a minute away. You can park along the road next to Starbucks, as there no markings on the road, but recently, they&#39;ve placed some cones there, so park at your own risk!

text: Yakun is a unique Singaporean place to grab an economical breakfast. This historical breakfast chain started from a single coffee stall in Singapore and has spread across Asia since. I was excited to try some of their kaya  menu items, since kaya (a coconut based paste) originated from Singapore. We ordered some original kaya butter toast and some stuffed kaya egg pieces. Both were delicious! the kaya butter toast was grilled on a charcoal grill, and the butter slice goes along SO well with it (except that it has a million calories and is artery clogging...oh well). The server also flattened the bread so that it was crispy, and cut off all of the crust. Yummy yum with a cup of their legit milk tea. I would definitely recommend to anyone who drops by Singapore to not miss out on this local delight!

A local joint for simple kaya toast, which is a singapore thing.<br><br>Guess im not a fan of the thick white bread and sweet kaya paste...i guess it works for young ones, but its too carb-y for me<br><br>They do have eggs and various drinks too

text: A terrible place for lunch; the waiters and the cooks inside in the kitchen are uncoordinated. I waited for my lunch for 30min; the roast beef sandwish was a piece of rubbery meat, and the fries were cold. I had to remind them of my ceasar salad, and it came as some lettuce leaves with already made ceasar sauce from a bottle, and they didn&#39;t even mix the salad! Not to forget, the bread for my roast beef sandwich was hard to bite on! They have no clue how to make a roast beef sandwich!

BBBS has been my watering hole and neighbourhood pub in this area for some time now. The casual concept of having a good and cheapish bar with very decent Indian and Western and Asian food clearly works for them -- at one point, I think they have the best burgers in Singapore. This is no longer so but they certainly built up a reputation for having more than decent pub grub with affordable beers, that they&#39;ve now expanded to two other locations (one in Robertson Quay, one in Katong).<br><br>The Bukit Timah BBBS is still my favourite. It&#39;s set in a leafy residential neighbourhood near Sixth Ave. Seating is outdoor and non-airconditioned, but you don&#39;t usually need it because there tends to be enough of a breeze to sit outdoors. As you kick back on large wooden tables and chairs you start to realize that this doesn&#39;t really feel very much like Singapore. It&#39;s got a nice vibe that reminds me of being on holiday in somewhere like Thailand, but of course that could just be the effect of too much beer :)

text: Located along Bukit Timah road, this bar is a great place to have a drink and catch up with friends. Often crowded but not too noisy and somehow you&#39;ll always be able to find a seat. Food to try here include the garlic naan and curries which are a great pair with your beer or cider however you like it. If you&#39;re not in the mood for Indian food, try the escargot instead or even spring rolls with spicy dip. The only set back here is Bar Bar Black Sheep is a cash only place so do come prepared as there are no Atm&#39;s in the vicinity! A great place for drinks after work on weekdays!

Have not been since it moved to this location. Is the food better, the same or otherwise? Visited it before when it was in Little India. Food was alright, but it was reasonable value for money, in its old location... Not sure about this since it moved.

no other coffee can keep my eyes open, i repeat, no other coffee can keep my eyes open except for ya kun&#39;s coffee. best local coffee ive had evahhh! gives you e strength to fight back when u r attacked by e &#39;zzz&#39; monster.<br><br>e silky barley is pretty good too. it&#39;s made with not just barley but also dried beancurd skin (fu chok) simply loves. e only two drinks i order from here.<br><br>other than e usual kaya toast, i like to go for the peanut butter kaya toast. love peanut butter! e saltiness and e sweetness of both peanut butter + kaya goes well together. a must try for all peanut butter lovers.<br><br>i frequent ya kun at least 2-3 times a week to satisfy my caffeine addiction. &#39;nuff said.

text: This location is closed. This review is for their new PoMo location around the corner on Prinsep St.<br>Set A lets you taste the complete home-style Singaporean breakfast: kaya toast, 1 hot coffee (your choice), 2 soft-boiled eggs. The new place is small but nice and bright. Staff is friendly. Service is prompt. I would go back! Yummy!

text: This is my go to Prata place (I live down the road). Im a sucker for the Banana Egg Prata in particular. As I sit in my chair writing this review, I feel bad for telling the owner that I had gotten my change for my SGD50 payment when In fact I hadn&#39;t after checking my wallet 10 mins later. The owner jokingly gave me a hard time when I asked for my change again, but of course he kindly gave it to me after I emptied my pockets. Haha.<br><br>I guess I was enjoying my Prata so much that I had a brain freeze! Haha. I would give these guys five stars anyway for the food, but would give these guys six since they didn&#39;t give me a hard time at all, rather they were so nice about it.

A definite go to for delicious parathas... but save your $$ for any other dish. Their noodle and rice dishes have such an off putting fishy smell that I&#39;d likely never try again <br><br>Would not go out of my way to come here, but it&#39;s next to home and open 24 hours so it works for my paratha needs. Go for the egg&amp;onion or banana!

text: Fayidha is important in the Whampoa and Balestier neighbourhood because it&#39;s the only 24hr prata place in the area, and that makes it a great end-of-the-night place for that one last stop before you head home. The shop occupies a nice large corner space and there are many tables all around the place, so you won&#39;t have to wait very long in the rare event that it&#39;s so crowded you can&#39;t get a seat.<br><br>The food isn&#39;t mind-blowing but it&#39;s decent for a prata place with the usual prata menu and also a nasi padang counter. The standard of the prata varies with the cook. That means if you come here often and are observant enough, you&#39;ll learn to recognise and know if the cook manning the prata station has got the chops. But it&#39;s never crap so you can be assured of having a satisfying prata. They also do murtabak if you&#39;re really hungry. The fish curry that comes with your curry and murtabak is really good. The different gorengs--maggi, mee, beehoon, kuay tiao--are also decent. And if you want something really substantial, there&#39;s a nasi padang counter<br><br>But the absolute best thing about Fayidha is this: It&#39;s got the right balance of sleepiness and bustle that makes it a great place to just sit in and chill and daze and watch people doing their thing and the traffic roll by. <br><br>It&#39;s rarely empty but it&#39;s never overcrowded. You might have to stretch a bit to get the attention of the waiters but it&#39;s not infuriating. I think that&#39;s all you can really ask for in a good neighbourhood kopitiam.<br><br>Oh, and since it&#39;s an Indian-Muslim establishment, keep track of your religious occasions and public holidays and don&#39;t go there searching for prata when they&#39;re bound to be closed.

text: 24 hours near Balestier, I&#39;ve had many a late night after dinner snack here with my good mate who lives round the corner and a few breks too. The prata - kosong, egg and prata bomb are all good solid efforts. The kosong/plain has a nice flaky crisp bite to the outside with that soft fluffiness inside. I asked for less oil the latest visit this New Year&#39;s Day and all my friends that I&#39;d brought for the first time said the prata was yummy, good crisp and fluffy texture (and not like some places that are crispy but are more like deep fried with overused oil) and looked almost healthy as it had no excess oil! Friends also commented that the fish gravy they serve with was so savoury and nicely balanced with a tinge of the sour. The teh here I keep forgetting is just the right amount of sweetness..I need to remember not to order less sweet next time!<br><br>Nice touch, all our teh tariks had clearly been genuinely tariked as they had a full layer of froth on.<br><br>I&#39;ve also had the prata bomb once at  my good friend&#39;s insistence..ok we shared and I really could have eaten one by myself. It was a perfect dessert for a late night chat (with more teh).<br><br>I haven&#39;t tried their other food. Really hits the spot for classic light textured prata with yummy fish gravy and a solid tasty teh tarik 24 hours!

text: The food here is below average in Singapore India food standards. I would not go out of my way to come and eat again. Not much to say about the cafe...

I&#39;m a simple woman with simple tastes, and I come here for one thing only- plain roti prata and teh halia!<br><br>I actually discovered this place during my tai tai days, when I was looking for a place to grab breakfast that wasn&#39;t embarrassing. (Read: the Golden Arches.) I wanted to check out Three Wombats Cafe, but they weren&#39;t going to be open &#39;til later. I figured I would walk down Kim Keat Road to see if there was anything else, and thanks to my curiousity, I found Fayidha!<br><br>To be honest, I can&#39;t explain the difference between plain pratas from other establishments, but just trust me when I say the prata and curry here is better than the one you get at the kopitiam at Tan Tock Seng Hospital. Just sayin&#39;.<br><br>Prices are affordable and I love how they&#39;re open 24 hours. They also have a TV that was showing a football game the last time I was there; not sure if it&#39;s always sports or if they change it up every now and then. They were operational during Chinese New Year Eve, but I&#39;m not sure about 1st and 2nd day. I would heed the advice of the other reviews which mention that they&#39;re probably closed during Muslim holidays and other public holidays. <br><br>Not a place to go out of your way for, but if you live in the Novena/Balestier area, it&#39;s a decent establishment to frequent.

text: This is the only 24 hour Indian Muslim food stall in Balestier; the rest of the late-night food options are predominated by Bak Kut Teh and other more Chinese-styled food options. <br><br>However, whilst I do have a hankering for prata from time to time, this really isn&#39;t the best place for it. Despite being open for 24 hours, they tend to run out of curries before the night is over. I love my fish curry, and egg prata with dhal just doesn&#39;t taste the same! <br><br>The maggie goreng is not bad, but it can sometimes be overcooked. <br><br>In short, not a great place for prata after-hours, but for those living in Balestier, this is your only choice.

text: There&#39;s not many places open for breakfast at 8am in Novena, particularly places that accept credit cards. I was running low on data on my international roaming, so I did the unthinkable and went to a cafe without checking it out on Yelp first. Luckily when I connected to the Wi-Fi at Old Town White Coffee, Yelp told me I made a good choice. The Wi-Fi is fast and free - hurrah.<br><br>My Singaporean friend tells me this is a Malaysian chain of cafes. I opted for the kaya toast which comes with soft boiled (extremely soft) eggs, and toast with your choice of kaya or peanut butter for $7. I got some hot teh and was set up for a hearty breakfast. Service was friendly, and the food came out reasonably quickly. Definitely one to stop in at if you need an early breakfast and you&#39;re in the area.

text: Old Town White Coffee...<br><br>I went here coz you are a Halal Certified establishment.  That ALONE is an added bonus in my books.<br><br>My 2nd trip here.  Last year was with my Cousin In Law and our good friend for Late Breakfast and Early Lunch on a PUBLIC Holiday aka National Day.<br><br>This time around it was on Tuesday for Lunch.  Time was about 12:15hrs ish.  Thankfully I managed to get seats.  This time around it was outside aka &#34;patio&#34; aka along the walk way of the Mall etc.<br><br>My mother opt for the Fish Ball Noodle Soup and we shared the Fried Wantons Dumplings.  I like the Fried Wantons Dumplings coz its FRIED to order and comes out HOT!  As for beverages I opt for the Ice Chendol.  Our Lunch or I would say, my Dining experience here is doable.  None of the items I had stood out.  Disappointing dish or I would say the Beverage aka Ice Chendol I had.  Too diluted and the chendol DO NOT taste authentic chedol at all for my personal taste bud.  Perhaps they get their chendol factory made.<br><br>Especially during Public Holiday, do plan to arrive early if you want to dine in.  This establishment tends to be packed to the brim.  This is also my observation during LUNCH hour on a Weekday.  *SIGH*<br><br>You pay your order inside at the counter.  The staffs are so-so.  NOT the friendly or accommodating type.  *DOUBLE SIGH*<br><br>May return BUT NOT in a hurry.  Hence this GENEROUS 3 stars review.  Actually its ALMOST 2.5 stars at best!

text: Look somewhere else! The staff, especially the cashier who I assume is at a managerial level, are condescending and make you feel like they couldn&#39;t care less if you are there or not. The food is overpriced when compared to similar breakfast joints like Wang Cafe or Toast Box. Look at the size of the prata! I was so disappointed I walked out without finishing my meal.

I tend to be quite generous with my stars, but I really can&#39;t bring myself to give this place any more than I have. <br><br>Bad service, slow service, and very irritatingly, you have to ring a bell for service. And considering how bad and slow service was, that Bell was ringing incessantly. And I don&#39;t mean by me, it&#39;s one Bell that keeps ringing regardless who presses it. <br><br>For a place with &#39;coffee&#39; in its name, you&#39;d expect it to have good coffee. But no, what they have is almost like the instant machine type you get from vending machines. Not something freshly brewed. <br><br>The Javanese noodles I had wasn&#39;t too bad, but for what you pay, I&#39;ll look for something else next time.

It took me a while to warm up to the Old Town White Coffee chain. I didn&#39;t know much about it, no one ever recommended that I go there, and with it&#39;s presence all over the place I thought it would just offer sub par food.<br><br>The first time my husband and I tried Old Town was actually in Malaysia. We took a weekend trip to Penang. It was a Sunday and a lot of the hawkers were closed. Long story short, we were touring the area with a rickshaw driver and got extremely hungry. Our knowledgable driver spoke highly of this place and recommended that we eat there.<br><br>I forgot what we ordered, but we were impressed! And the prices were affordable! So when we came back to SG, we knew we should visit again.<br><br>Luckily, this outlet near our place satisfies our craving each time. Our favorites are the curry chicken dish (which they say isn&#39;t spicy but trust me, it has a decent kick to it) and the BBQ chicken noodles. I fell in love with chendul in Penang, and they do offer it here, so one day I hope to give it a try.<br><br>If we&#39;re not in the mood to eat outside or to walk to our favorite hawker, we always end up here. The comfortable environment and affordable prices make my husband and I huge fans. Watch out, Nik T- your dukedom here is in danger!! ;)

text: waitress: xi mut milk tea?<br>me: yes, please!<br><br>m: xi mut milk tea???<br>w: yes, it is!!!<br><br>unconvinced, i took a sniff!<br>xi mut milk tea it was!!<br>wow, the colour of their tea is indeed power!!!<br>so much so i mistook it for coffee, my bad.<br><br>xi mut means silk stockings.<br>someone in malaysia must have been desperate and used his wife&#39;s silk stockings when he ran out of the good old coffee sock!<br>hopefully it was a brand new pair and not otherwise.<br>anyway, that is my version of how it started.<br><br>if you are in a rush, this is not the place for you.<br>at old town, their philosophy is to take life at a leisurely pace.<br>they take their time and recommends that you do the same.<br>so if you wanna lepak, then this is the place to be.<br><br>even their soft boil eggs take 8 mins to be ready!:)<br>be patient, says the aunty.<br>as long as it comes out perfect, says me!<br>the accompanying dark sauce is of the thick consistency type, which is good.<br><br>their coffee has a good head to it, ala teh tarik.<br><br>their curry mee which i asked, and they accommodated, to be replace with their ipoh hor fun was yums!<br>a lot more ingredients than i remember it back when i patronized their outlet in bukit timah.<br>bean sprouts, long beans, fish cake, chicken, char siu chicken, tau pok, and bean curd skin.<br>curry was lemak and not too spicy.<br>hor fun was smooth as silk(not stockings).<br><br>kiss 92 fm was playing in the background.<br>nostalgic indeed.<br><br>free wifi is available in the form of old town white coffee, wireless@sg or from tully&#39;s coffee opposite.

text: Stayed at a nearby hotel. Needed coffee and a light breakfast in the morning. Walked in to Old Town just because it was the first place I saw. Kaya butter &amp; toast was on the next level of flavor. Do yourself a favor and skip starbucks next time.

Haha, but that&#39;s just me. <br><br>Bingsu wise, the ice is nice and &#34;dry&#34;. Its mind-boggling how ice can be so dry. But, I still prefer the bingsu from nunsaram. <br><br>Despite this, it still deserves 5 stars

text: Over-hyped and overpriced but still a decent spot to try a current fad dessert. <br><br>Adding to its schtick, Nunsongyee Korean Dessert Cafe opens 24 hours a day sans a 20 minute pocket where they reconcile the earnings. Note that&#39;s when an already steady flow of customers turns into a longer line waiting to place their orders. I believe this happens around 11pm if I&#39;m not wrong?<br><br>It&#39;s a decent bingsu but not necessarily worth the markup. It is shaved ice/snow after all. Staff behind the counter take themselves too seriously. We split the &#34;premium&#34; black sesame bingsu and the injeolmi toast. I found both to be oddly a little dry on the palate. I do appreciate that they&#39;re not too sweet for desserts. Try it if you&#39;re curious and wanting late night sweets but it&#39;s not worth the dedicated run here just to try it.

text: The outlet takes over the space of the well known Ritz Apple Strudel store. The branch is the 3rd outlet after Burghley Drive and Tanjong Katong. The outlet has 3 floors of dine in area, as well as, alfresco dine area. The washroom is at the second level. Those with kids would prefer the second level which has finely shaved ice to play with. The outlet is open 24 hours and there is free wifi available. <br><br>After placing order at the first floor counter, one would be given a pagar, which will light up when the food is ready for collection at the first floor.<br><br>Pat Bingsu ($12.90)<br>The shaved ice had a very finely texture which simply melt in the mouth. It did not taste too sweet. I like the crunchy fragrant toasted almond slices. If you prefer a sweeter taste, there is syrup at the counter to help yourself to.

Nunsongyee (snowflake) is a relatively new Korean dessert cafe that is situated in the busy streets of Bugis, right across from Toast Box at Bugis Junction. You will find this 24 hours 7 days a week bingsu shop!<br><br>They specialise in authentic Korean dessert, mainly Bingsu, and things like toast and even spicy rice cake. You can pick from a variety of Bingsu like Pat Bingsu, Oreo Bingsu, Cheesecake Bingsu, or go for premium bingsu like sesame bingsu, coffee bingsu and strawberry bingsu! The snowflakes bingsus are priced at $14.90 and below, whereas the premium bingsu are priced at $18.90. Though there is no GST or service charge, I still feel that these are premium prices, despite the humble beginings of Nunsongyee at Burghley Drive.<br><br>The queue for the payment wasn&#39;t too long but the queue for the tables were crazier. The korean lady at the cashier would ask everyone in line if they had a table. If you didn&#39;t have a table, she wouldn&#39;t take your order. There are lots of steps to climb, take note! There&#39;s two floors of dining area, all of which is air conditioned. <br><br>Nunsongyee doesn&#39;t waste any space on the ground floor, on the ground floor you have a tiny cashier with a menu board and that&#39;s it! So figure out what you want and make payment. You will be handed a buzzer that is rung when your order is ready.<br><br>Only on the ground floor, you have an al fresco dining setup. On a non-hazy friday cool night, it was perfect. It took us 30 minutes to find a table for 6! Despite them being open for over a month now, the bingsu craze is still on-going!<br><br>1. Cheesecake Bingsu $14.90<br>Their versions of bingsu are made of milk, thus they do not use the term &#34;shaved ice&#34;. You can immediately taste the milky goodness in your first mouthful. The cheesecake bingsu came in a reasonable portion size. The bingsu was completely covered by the toppings of digestive biscuit crumbs, cheesecake and vanilla ice cream. A small cup of condensed milk came with the bingsu.<br><br>The ccup of condensed milk made the bingsu have an even stronger milky after-taste. This was something that I could appreciate in comparison to the coffee bingsu which had a bitter after-taste. The ice cream was very smooth and creamy. The cheesecake bits were slightly soury and they were quite dense despite their small cube sizes.<br><br>2. Coffee Bingsu $18.90<br>The coffee bingsu came dressed in almond flakes and a small serving of legit coffee to be poured over the bingsu. The coffee itself wasn&#39;t warm, so it didn&#39;t melt the ice cream or the shaved ice. I liked that we had ordered both a sweet bingsu aka the cheesecake bingsu as well as a bitter bingsu aka the coffee bingsu. Both had contrasting tastes and everyone enjoyed them both!<br><br>I love the texture of the shaved ice, it&#39;s as smooth as snow!! The portion here is actually the same as the non-premium bingsus. Either ways, each bingsu is meant to be shared with at least 2-3pax.<br><br>Almost all of of the bingsus here at Nunsongyee come topped with a dollop of vanilla ice cream. Interestingly despite dining outdoors on the ground floor, the ice cream didn&#39;t melt immediately as you would&#39;ve expected. The ice cream lasted quite a while, before getting annihilated  by our spoons.<br><br>This is like a dream come true for those who have sweet cravings at any hour of the day, or need an alternate late-night hangout place to drinking joints.<br><br>The prices at Nunsongyee are a bit high especially if you opt for the premium bingsu and add toppings.<br><br>Besides bingsu, Nunsongyee also offers a menu of Signature Toast ($8.90 to $12.90) and Korean Rice Cake ($6.90 to $8.90), as well as beverages of Coffee, Tea and Smoothies ($3.70 to $6.90).

Black sesame.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Black sesame.'}]
text: The most important thing you must know about this place is that it opens 247, and it has free wifi. <br><br>My virgin bingsu experience was here on a Thursday night. I note that our order was taken at 2318hours, and only received at 2345hours. Bit of a long wait, but totally worth it. <br><br>Before I tried it, I never understood the hype. The ice here is so finely shaved, and powder-like, doesn&#39;t melt easily, not overly icy, and milky. We got the black sesame bingsu, and the blueberry bingsu. I preferred the black sesame, which came topped with lots of black sesame powder, and red bean paste. The bingsu itself wasn&#39;t very sweet, and you can customize the sweetness with the sweetened milk they provide. <br><br>The blueberry bingsu had a generous amount of blueberries, painstakingly arranged nicely (guess that&#39;s why they took ages). But I felt it was a bit bland. <br><br>Would return. Great for a late night dessert run with great friends.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/DMSokWMZdyx2sNXfxhfLmw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/nunsongyee-korean-dessert-cafe-singapore-3?reviewid=3yyENxqEcc6R40sX7d5RFw&select=DMSokWMZdyx2sNXfxhfLmw', 'altText': 'Photo of Nunsongyee Korean Dessert Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. Cheesecake bingsu', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Cheesecake bingsu'}]
text: In quick succession, Korean shaved ice arrives in downtown Singapore.<br><br>Nunsongyee (&#34;snowflake&#34; in Korean) now opens their third store at Bugis, after recently opening their second store in Tanjong Katong.<br><br>They serve &#34;patbingsu&#34; (red beans with ice), basically the Korean version of &#34;ice kachang&#34; with azuki beans. Red beans are the traditional topping, but you can choose from other flavors such as &#34;cheescake&#34;, &#34;oreo&#34;, &#34;black sesame&#34; and &#34;injeolmi&#34;, chewy korean rice cake (tteokpokki) coated with shaved bean/peanut powder. With the help of a special machine, the ice is extremely fine and flaky with generous toppings. I generally like the cheesecake and oreo flavors. The quality of shaved ice is rather similar to the ones I&#39;ve had in Atlanta, LA and other Korean-owned establishments in the US. <br><br>The main thing about this store is that it&#39;s open 24 hours! There are three levels in the building, formerly occupied by Ritz Apple Strudel. The outdoor seating area is on the first floor, and the second floor of the building has a special glass walled room with shaved ice falling to the floor, in case you&#39;d like to have your own snowball fight one degree north of the equator.<br><br>The only warning that I have to administer, is that your wallet will be taxed S$15-18 for shaved ice. It&#39;s a little pricey considering the local versions of the same dessert cost $2-3 at a food court or hawker center. I guess that&#39;s the cost of the interior decor and that little slice of Korea when you enter the door. I&#39;ll only come here occasionally. <br><br>I&#39;m also wondering how long the K-dessert fad will last. Like the apple strudel before it, it&#39;s won&#39;t be long before Singaporean stomachs move on to the next big thing...

text: Got a chocolate and banana bingsu. Shaved ice was smooth and fair but could have been more milky. Chocolate powder and banana adds a lot more flavor to the plain shaved ice. The ice cream on top helps too. Generally a pleasant experience.<br><br>However, for the price of $13.90 this desert falls way below expectations. Would recommend if you happen to have some money to waste on frivolous and pretentious food.

text: I guess it&#39;s good based on their number of customers. We waited around 15 minutes to get a table and 20 minutes to get our food. Coffee was OK but way overpriced. I would recommend this place to anyone who wants to try something new. It&#39;s cool but it&#39;s not my kind of dessert.

text: Admittedly, Ultra Bake breads aren&#39;t as tasty as Imperial Bakery BUT they do taste like there are less additives and have a much more Western spin to bread baking. I recommend their raisin cheese and golden sand. You really won&#39;t go wrong with those two! <br><br>This place also offers the BEST tasting coffee in the area. It&#39;s thick, flavorful and only 80 cents! If you&#39;re not going to stop by to try the bread, then I highly recommend the coffee!

text: This is a new joint the block replacing my old favorite Java Kitchen.  Since it looked clean and nice, we went in for some dessert and damn!  Their oreo cheesecake is to die for.  And a tiny Oreo on top to make it extra cute.  And their hot chocolate?  Perfect to end the night.  <br><br>I highly recommend it

You&#39;d never expect a cafe to be located in a kitchen appliance showroom, but yes, it&#39;s here in an industrial building a short walk away from Paya Lebar MRT.<br><br>I&#39;m here for the coffee (double shot, of course) and occasionally the lunch items. Good choices are the Yakiniku Beef Striploin Rice Bowl, Grilled Salmon or Chicken at wallet friendly prices. They offer pastry and bakery items as well.<br><br>Been a regular customer since they opened in 2018 but the crowd has since picked up and it gets a little noisy inside. It is recommended to arrive outside lunch hours.

text: This is my all time favorite milk tea place, forever. I&#39;m from America and I studied abroad in Singapore and Koi was a life-saver. It felt like getting a reward every time I came to Koi. Clementi was definitely the easiest place to get to from NUS so I came here quite frequently. My favorite drinks are the mocchiatos and passion fruit green tea with aloe and ai-yu. Koi is where I fell in love with ai-yu, which I can&#39;t get in America, it just doesn&#39;t taste the same. I usually get 0% sugar because the aloe vera and ai-yu have enough sugar to make the tea sweet. <br><br> I guess Koi is just a very common tea cafe among Singaporeans but it was amazing to me. I&#39;ve tried all the other chained cafes but I always just kept coming back to Koi. <br><br>I remember during the week before finals at NUS, I probably went to Koi at least 5 out 7 days of the week. I totally miss it now that I&#39;m back in the states. I hope Koi gets moved to the states!! I would be their first customer :D

text: Bubble tea was a bit of a fad for a while.  While there&#39;s still a very steady following , it certainly is no where near the fevered frenzy that it inspired 2 years ago. <br><br>In my mind there are only 2 chains worth comparing: Koi and Gong Cha. <br>I find Koi&#39;s &#34;red tea&#34;  brews more robust although they both use some amorphous creamer powder for the milk tea.  This is undoubtedly the rendered residue of a mixture of palm and coconut oil.  It sounds disgusting, but it tastes really good.  I know, I know, you&#39;re wondering how I can sing the praises of the offerings at Indie coffee joints like Nylon, then say what I just said about non-dairy creamer with tea...well, there&#39;s this part of my brain that is 7 years old and that has just discovered that when you spoon Coffeemate, you get the same high as scarfing down a much more expensive Mars bar. That&#39;s the part of my brain that makes me crave Koi. <br><br>My recommendation: milk tea with no sugar with grass jelly.<br><br>They recently moved to the other side of this block of shophouses to the &#34;next&#34; block which is 443.  The new address is Blk 443, Clementi Ave 3 #01-67. Singapore 120443.

text: Decided to stop by here to try out the Gong Cha Matcha Milk Tea (Limited time) on a Saturday evening. Seating was pretty limited and during peak hours, you might have to wait for seating.<br><br>This is an open concept cafe and they have two types of seating plans - normal small group seatings or high chairs seating (communal). The modern layout matched with the high ceilings that the mall have offered.<br><br>The Matcha Milk tea was pretty good even though it came in a higher pricing. On the lid, there is a sticker which tell you various ways of slurping the tea. I didn&#39;t notice it at first so I stirred my beverage and slurped it. Will try the other two methods next time. I enjoyed the beverage very much. Was expecting it to be thick and milky but it gave a smooth aftertaste. And the pearls (boba) were chewy. Definitely a great addition to the Matcha Milk Tea :)

text: This is my 3rd Singapore trip. While looking for something new to do, pops up the Gudetama Cafe in my search! And of course,  I had to go check it out. Its inside the mall on Temasek Street. You&#39;d see it immediately as soon as you enter.<br><br>The Cafe looks so cute! My favorite Egg is on the walls, on the tables, everywhere! Place your order on the tablet. Confirm your selection and wait for your order. I got a self tanning pizza and a strawberry Lazy drink.<br><br>Although not so fond of the drink, the pizza was great! It was too much for me, I brought the left overs which they packaged in a very cute Gudetama box!<br><br>I also saw a Facebook post saying the Cafe will be closing come November.... too bad.... but I am glad I was able to visit!!!!

text: If you come here, expect ONLY the novelty and i guess the pictures you can take. The food is nothing special and in fact, subpar and way overpriced. text: I have to applaud Gudetama Cafe for decking out their restaurant with Gudetama everywhere: in the ceiling, as a stand alone statue, Gudetama stuffed animals and pillows, wall and booth decorations, table decorations, cup decorations, and food decorations. There&#39;s plenty of Instagram worthy spots in the restaurant to take pictures. <br><br>But, with this theme cafe, the food was just mediocre for how expensive it was. We ordered their chocolate mango roll, passion milk chocolate mousse, and their passion fruit tea. Only the mousse was worth it. I could taste the passion fruit and chocolate, and the mousse itself was creamy. However, the mango roll was quite dry in texture, and the passion fruit tea didn&#39;t taste like the described fruit. It tasted fruity and bitter at the same time, which wasn&#39;t pleasant. I drank it all because I paid for it. But, it wasn&#39;t worth the money. We would&#39;ve ordered their savory items. But, the prices for these dishes were even more ridiculously expensive. Service was also nonexistent from the staff. <br><br>Overall, I would come into this cafe/restaurant with the expectation that you will take wonderful pictures of Gudetama, and you will eat mediocre food. Just stick with ordering the desserts, as you won&#39;t break the bank as much as ordering their entrees. Unless, you find the entrees cute enough for the price for picture taking. Then, enjoy.

text: Let&#39;s be honest, you are here for the novelty factor.  <br><br>The food is halfway decent so that&#39;s a plus.  There&#39;s also a impressive amount of effort put into making each food dish into a Gudetama.  <br><br>My advice would be to get a small dish and or drink just to check it out and then eat your real meal at one of the many many delicious hawker stalls.

text: Such a cute and adorable cafe!<br><br>I came here during my vacay in Singapore and came across the cafe in Suntec City Mall... and I said I must visit here!<br><br>I ordered the Eggcited Cajun Chicken with Waffles for my entree, the Strawverylazy drink and for dessert, I got the passion milk chocolate mousse.<br><br>Food was amazing! The chicken and waffles were flavorful and crispy, the drink was refreshing and the dessert was sweet to perfection!

Such an adorable cafe. Granted yes it&#39;s expensive, almost 25 bucks a plate of breakfast food but you really didn&#39;t come here for the food, did ya? Great photo spot and apparently you can also make reservations as we saw multiple people come in with reservations. It&#39;s located right in front of the entrance of Suntec City Mall - the mall is huge so ask for directions if you get lost!<br><br>They also have desserts to go and also cute little trinkets you can buy to go home if you so want to. The place is adorable for pics once again!

text: A cute place to stop by if you&#39;re a Gudetama fan. The dishes they served were all fun and tasty, but definitely at a price. <br><br>Wouldn&#39;t say anything was prepared in an entirely quick manner, but that makes sense because dishes here are prepared specifically to entertain guests. Just make sure you schedule some time for your lunch or dinner, and don&#39;t try and squeeze it in between other tours and travels.

text: If you&#39;re a fan of Gudetama, then this cafe is for you! Located inside of the Suntec City Mall, you&#39;ll be squealing both internally and externally as you come across the cute storefront and then are led inside where there are Gudetama-adorned booths, egg shell chairs, and a plethora of Gudetama faces all over the walls and even ceiling!<br><br>The menu consists of basic savory fare - eggs benedict, waffles, fries, salad, a burger, and more - and dessert - cheesecake, chocolate cake, pudding, milkshakes, etc. Each item is somehow Gudetama-themed, whether it be with an actual egg item or a Gudetama face on something else. <br><br>I ordered the Ta-Ma-Go ($17.9 SGD), which were sweet mini cheesecakes deceptively shaped like savory tamago nigiri with a matcha paste (&#34;wasabi&#34;) and syrup (&#34;soy sauce&#34;) on the side. There were 4 cakes and each was topped with a little piece of toasted cake with Gudetama&#39;s face, covered in little rice krispies, and wrapped in a black fondant &#34;seaweed&#34; strip. While it was cute, it wasn&#39;t QUITE as nice as the photo in the menu, and didn&#39;t have a lot of flavor except for the actual cheesecake. The boyfriend ordered the Mooooo Fries ($18.5 SGD), which were sweet potato fries covered with cheese, bulgogi and an egg. It was surprisingly a decent portion and the bite I tasted was pretty good. He finished it and actually felt reasonably full afterwards. <br><br>Service was a bit...below average on our visit. After we requested a few more minutes to peruse the menu before ordering, no one ever came back so we had flag someone down - with much difficulty as the cafe was FAR from busy but none of the employees were looking in our direction. We had to ask for water. It would&#39;ve also been nice to be able to choose where we sat since one of the adorable Gudetama booths was open but we were sat at a regular table instead. We did receive some Gudetama-shaped cookies after paying which was a nice souvenir, though!<br><br>Overall, it&#39;s a fun place to visit for the novelty and to take photos of and with everything, but probably not worth a second visit due to overpriced, decent but average food and subpar service. I did particularly enjoy the complimentary basket of hard boiled eggs - with bright yellow yolks just like eating Gudetama himself!

text: This is heaven!<br><br>I&#39;m obsessed win Sanrio and made plans to come here months before our trip!<br><br>The decor is superb with everything Gudetama theme! It seriously was so so fun!<br><br>In terms of food.. it was OKAY. It was pretty overpriced and not that good. But reading from past reviews I already expected it so we just shared a dish for pictures lol!<br><br>If you&#39;re a Gudetama fan you have to stop by!<br><br>Service was wonderful !<br><br>Thank you guys!

text: The cafe took over the space formerly occupied by House of Robert Timms. The restaurant had 2 dining area : the main one with the items display for sale and a smaller one in garden theme. As we were early and there was not much customers around, only the main dining area was opened. We had our choice of seat and decided on one of the egg shaped booth table. If you were in a big group, there was a table shaped like a egg tray with eggs in it. So cute.<br><br>&#34;I&#39;m Cold&#34; Smoked Salmon Eggs Benedict ($26.90++)<br>Poached eggs covered with smoked salmon. Drizzled with signature zesty hollandise sauce complete with mashed avocado, ebiko and tater tots.<br>The dish was served in a rather heavy frying pan. It was so cute having the eggs covered with the salmon slices. Looked rather cosy. The simple looking dish was not bad and quite filling too. One could barely finished it.<br><br>Shoyu Ramen ($21.50++)<br>Shoyu Ramen made with chocolate cake, chestnut Mont Blanc and Earl Grey Jelly.<br>Served with a side of panna cotta and sweetened rose tea.<br>The dish looked very nice. While the cake was moist, hidden under the layer of jelly, one could not taste the chestnut in it. The panna cotta was creamy. The rose tea was lightly flavoured, that the flavour was not distinct. <br><br>Finished the meal with Butterscotch Latte ($6.90++) and Matcha Latte ($6.90++) which both tasted rather average.<br><br>As it was Easter weekend, there was free boiled eggs on the table to help oneself to.

text: Meet with friends to have dinner here. The food are really cute with the gudetama expression on it. And it tastes not bad too. Their fries is really good though. We ordered the family platter to share among us. It&#39;s just nice for us. My friends bought back some desserts and I bought their tissue box lols! Because it&#39;s too kawaii ! They have the promotion for it. But I have to say that the price and charges from this cafe is really pricey. Food added service charge and tax. The products that I bought are also with tax.  but just for a one time try, this is good.

This place is so cute and fun for pictures and maybe a date situation. I came here with my friend and we took pictures of everything, even bought some pastries and toys to bring back home. We&#39;re not locals but we came here because of the novelty. There was a wait to get inside but it didn&#39;t disappoint. <br><br>The Shoyu Ramen Dessert wasn&#39;t so good, but all the food and drinks were acceptable. This place is great for pictures. You&#39;re not really coming here because the food is good, but because the food is cute, enjoy!
