text: This place is definitely for the novelty. I&#39;m a Gudetama fan, however, this place just missed the mark when it came to the food. The presentation would make you think otherwise right? Wrong. First of all, the prices were outrageous. Absolutely shocking actually. The food was not the best quality at all. Not even close. There are SO many things you could make with eggs. I think they could have totally had an amazing menu. So let&#39;s just pretend the little Gudetama faces weren&#39;t on the food... well it tasted like something I wouldn&#39;t even pay $5 for. The breakfast meal had simple fried egg on top of a SOGGY bread. The salad was simple and the beans are 100 percent straight from a can. Nothing about this is special. The pizza was nothing special at all. Let&#39;s just say that appearances in this case are deceiving. The staff was not the most pleasant either. When asked if we could have regular fries instead of the sweet potato fries that one of the dishes is made with, the answer was no. And a blank stare. Literally no sorry or anything. Awkward. And when asked if we can take the paper placemats for keepsake, the answer was also no. I mean, it&#39;s PAPER. <br>The only thing this place is good for like I said, is the novelty of it. I would definitely say this was far from eggcellent. Too bad I got too eggcited. By the way, this is no eggzaggeration. I give it a solid one star.

Drizzled with signature zesty hollandise sauce complete with mashed avocado, ebiko and tater tots.<br>The dish was served in a rather heavy frying pan. It was so cute having the eggs covered with the salmon slices. Looked rather cosy. The simple looking dish was not bad and quite filling too. One could barely finished it.<br><br>Shoyu Ramen ($21.50++)<br>Shoyu Ramen made with chocolate cake, chestnut Mont Blanc and Earl Grey Jelly.<br>Served with a side of panna cotta and sweetened rose tea.<br>The dish looked very nice. While the cake was moist, hidden under the layer of jelly, one could not taste the chestnut in it. The panna cotta was creamy. The rose tea was lightly flavoured, that the flavour was not distinct. <br><br>Finished the meal with Butterscotch Latte ($6.90++) and Matcha Latte ($6.90++) which both tasted rather average.<br><br>As it was Easter weekend, there was free boiled eggs on the table to help oneself to.

text: Super cute cafe to meet all your gudetama needs! <br><br>Ambience: 5/5<br>- attention to detail is everything here as chairs are eggshells, the tables are sunny side up eggs, the ceilings even have gudetama. <br><br>Food: 3.5/5<br>- with any cute restaurant, the compromise is usually the taste. I got the Big Nua Breakfast and it was decent but nothing amazing. You honestly just go for the photos. The price point also would deter you from coming back. <br><br>Service: 4/5<br>- not the most attentive, but very very sweet!

text: Had breakfast there this morning with my wife and we had a steak and eggs and a big breakfast.<br><br>Food was substandard, although the coffees were passable. Steak was completely rare when I ordered a medium rare so I sent it back to the kitchen to be re cooked. Eggs were also under done with a slimy layer of clear uncooked eggs floating on top. Potatoes were irregular with some pieces still raw. <br><br>Steak tasted of nothing and they are obviously buying cheap produce despite charging premium prices.<br><br>For the price, go to one of the more established brunch establishments for a more satisfying experience. Only advantage is that it is relatively quiet for weekends brunch, but given the quality of life the food, this is understandable.

text: Generous portions! And decent coffee. Not the best coffee in the world, but decent. They had some nice breakfast options at lunch time and it was completely and utterly deserted on a weekday (except for us). So if you can get over to HillV2 on a weekday - why not?

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/-tZm1w9ZXS3piYxWWSji2Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dean-and-deluca-singapore-4?reviewid=hmN65I7T4lfN6i1XrqJ8BQ&select=-tZm1w9ZXS3piYxWWSji2Q', 'altText': 'Photo of Dean & Deluca - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Decided to grab a quick lunch here. Modern vibes and spacious seating but definitely on the more expensive side. We got pasta and panini but honestly neither of them impressed us. Chicken in the pasta was way too dry and the dish wasn&#39;t too flavorful. Same issue with the panini. We didn&#39;t try their drinks so maybe that&#39;s their selling point. Great place to chill but skip the dining.

text: Nice, quiet place - though it may be a little bit out of the way for those people who don&#39;t drive (but I guess you can always check out their other outlets in Orchard Central!)<br><br>Food wise, it was good. I would recommend their truffle carbonara - comes with a poached egg! Their wagyu lasagna was average - meat was well done though! Portions were very generous as well!<br><br>Service by their manager was really good. The staff kind of forgot the lasagna so we ended up waiting for a really long time, so she brought us some soup and bread so we wouldn&#39;t starve in the meantime. With that said, the soup had a piece of paper in it, rendering it virtually inedible :/

text: Another excellent eatery in the new Hillv2 mall. Lots of organic stuff and healthy drinks, although cheeseburger is also on the menu.<br>Very contemporary atmosphere, brand new and icy cold aircon, accompanied by (too much) thumping music. It&#39;s nice for a quick meal. Don&#39;t stick around too long.
